<FIRST>r a PM-Names     10-16 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angela Lansbury says it took her two decades to
become a leading lady, and then it was 20 years too soon.
   The star of CBS-TV's ``Murder, She Wrote'' says she spent about
20 years as a supporting player in movies before she hit it big as
``Mame'' on Broadway in 1966.
   ``People thought I was fat because I had this round face, and I
think it was the round face that defeated me as an actress,'' the
64-year-old actress said in an interview in this week's People.
   By the time she started in ``Mame,'' Lansbury was 40, ``and
40-year-old actresses didn't have a chance. Nowadays, most of the
women in Hollywood who are successful are in their 40s, so I just
missed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmy-winning actress Candice Bergen, star of
TV's ``Murphy Brown,'' soon will have a Beverly Hills zip code
again, to go with her addresses in New York and France.
   Moving into the one-story, colonial-style residence _ even if it
is part-time while filming the CBS show _ would represent a
homecoming of sorts. Bergen, daughter of the late ventriloquist
Edgar Bergen, lived nearby as a child in a walled hacienda known as
Bella Vista.
   The seller of the new place, which has three bedrooms, maid's
quarters, four bathrooms and a pool, was asking $1.3 million, a
real estate broker unconnected with the deal told the Los Angeles
Times. The deal is in escrow.
   Bergen also has homes in France and New York with her husband,
French film director Louis Malle, and their 4-year-old daughter,
Chloe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The marriage of fashion designer Mary McFadden
to a man 29 years her junior is still gossip fodder, but they say
they are so much in love they want to adopt children.
   ``We want to adopt a son,'' the 51-year-old designer said in an
interview in this week's People magazine.
   ``After that we'll probably adopt another so he can have
company,'' added Kohle Yohannan, a 22-year-old Columbia University
student. ``I know it's difficult, but I plan to have a child within
two years. Mary and I want to go for every experience and live life
in its quintessential form.''
   The couple said they didn't make a formal prenuptial agreement.
   ``We had a verbal agreement that if either one of us gains 20
pounds that it would be cause for divorce,'' Yohannan said four
months into the marriage. ``So far we've both lost 10 pounds, so I
guess things are fine.''
   Yohannan already has begun to take an active role in the
designer's $5 million business, recently designing her knitwear
showroom in Manhattan.
   They're also learning from each other: he's taught her about rap
music while he's learned about Far Eastern art from her.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TV evangelist Billy Graham celebrated his
40th anniversary in the ministry by receiving a star in the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   Actor Kirk Cameron of TV's ``Growing Pains'' was among the 3,000
fans, friends and followers gathered on Hollywood Boulevard for
Sunday's ceremony in front of the Chinese Theater.
   The Salvation Army Band performed and followers in the crowd
frequently shouted ``amen'' and ``Praise the Lord'' during the
unveiling.
   ``This star today is not a mark to recognize a man, but a
marking for the glory of God,'' the 70-year-old Graham said. ``What
this star represents is the faithfulness of God.''
   The stars in the sidewalk lining Hollywood Boulevard and Vine
Street are normally dedicated to entertainers in categories
including motion pictures, TV, radio and music.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz saxophonist Stanley Turrentine was
released from a hospital after five days of treatment for a lung
condition.
   The 55-year-old Pittsburgh native, who now lives in Kensington,
Md., was taken to Mercy Hospital on Tuesday by paramedics after his
wife was unable to awaken him in their hotel room.
   Turrentine was found to have an accumulation of fluid in his
lungs and was placed on a respirator. But he later began breathing
normally on his own and was released Sunday.
</TEXT>
