<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Jordan-Women Bjt   10-16 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jordan-Women, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Will Women, Voting In First Nationwide Ballot, Decide For Whom They
Vote?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman named Shifa, attired in a modest
Moslem headscarf and a full-length dress, says she is ready to vote
in next month's general election _ the first in which Jordanian
women will take part.
   But who will determine her vote?
   ``Of course my husband, because he is the man,'' she told a
reporter who chatted with her on a busy Amman street festooned with
banners for the Nov. 8 parliamentary election.
   Women like Shifa _ she would not give her family name _ have
dampened the optimism of women's rights activists facing their
first nationwide campaign.
   ``Sixty percent of the women at least are not independent
voters. ... they will be influenced by their husband, father or
brother,'' said Laila Sharaf, one of just two female Cabinet
ministers in Jordan's 65-year history.
   Jordan gave women the right to vote in 1974, but nationwide
elections have not taken place since 1967. Women have voted only in
a few local elections to replace deputies who died or resigned.
   This year, several women are running for the 80 parliamentary
seats and women comprise about half the country's 1 million
registered voters.
   ``This is the first time we will have candidates discussing
women and their rights,'' said Mrs. Sharaf, a former minister of
information.
   Some male candidates have targeted appeals to female voters:
``Woman is half of society. She is the one who raises future
generations,'' announced a banner hoisted by one man.
   The election follows two decades of rapid educational
improvement.
   When Jordanians last voted nationwide, only about a quarter of
young women attended secondary school. Today the figure is about 80
percent, and many go on to universities or technical schools.
   But conservative views of women mainly as homemakers remain
deeply held _ some rooted in religion, some in local traditions.
   Many women wear headscarves and long plain dresses that
symbolize their adherence to a conservative vision of Islam.
   ``The world is the world of men, and they always believe the
woman is only for the house,'' said Haifa Bashir, head of the
Jordanian Federation of Women and a candidate for Parliament.
   Women accounted for less than 15 percent of the work force in
the mid-1980s, and activists say the number is declining because of
economic difficulties and the tendency to drop women workers before
men.
   ``Even now, when the family can't pay for all their children (to
study), they prefer to let the boy continue his studies and not the
girl,'' said Asma Khader, a leading human rights lawyers.
   ``They will not present the freedom to us,'' she added. ``We
must work for it.''
   Ms. Khader complained that Jordan's social security, insurance
and pension laws grant more benefits to men than women, and that
women cannot obtain a passport or get married without approval of
male relatives.
   Women married to foreign men cannot pass along Jordanian
citizenship to their children. And Khader said criminal laws allow
male relatives to kill a woman caught having sex out of wedlock.
   While many of the laws are based on interpretations of Islam,
Jordan's official religion, Mrs. Bashir argues that they are
misinterpretations.
   She said both the Koran, Islam's holy book, and traditional
Islamic law ``gave rights to women 14 centuries ago better than
what we are seeking now.''
   The debate flared into the press in September when a column
defending women's rights in the daily newspaper Al Rai prompted a
flood of complaints.
   One letter writer opined that women ``are short of brains based
on women's natural structure, which differs from the man's as her
emotional, psychological structure prevails.''
   ``The weight of a woman's brain is less than the brain of man,''
argued another letter writer.
   Apparently to counter such sentiments, King Hussein used a
recent speech to denounce religious preoccupation with women's
clothing or attempts to limit their freedom.
   ``Islam is the religion of action and production and cannot
accept the crippling of half the society,'' said the king, whose
wife Queen Noor is a Princeton-educated Arab-American.
   Women will have little impact on this year's election, said Mrs.
Sharaf, but ``there will be a time they begin and they learn. ...
By the time the next election is held, women will have increased
their political conciousness and their role.''
   Already, politics has become a part of women's lives.
   ``Everyone, everyone, everyone is talking about it,'' said
Rabiah Adawiyeh, who like Shifa wore Islamic clothing.
   ``There's nothing on their tongues except the elections.''
</TEXT>
