<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Delchamps obit; AMs separates on Zymierski moved as a0706;
on sports wires on Agabashian.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Michal Zymierski</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michal Zymierski, a Polish independence
fighter who became a Soviet-backed member of the first postwar
Communist government, died Sunday. He was 99.
   Zymierski was an officer under Jozef Pilsudski independence,
which was won in 1918. According to an official biography he then
split with Pilsudski was imprisoned from 1926 to 1931. His next
seven years were spent in France.
   During World War II, he became allied with Soviet-backed
Communist resistance forces and organized of the underground Polish
People's Army.
   He was a member of the first postwar government formed under
Soviet auspices on July 22, 1944, in Lublin and was appointed head
of of the armed forces from 1945 to 1949, when he was ousted during
the Stalinist purges.
   Zymierski was and arrested and imprisoned from 1952 until 1955.
After 1956 he was rehabilitated and served a senior position in the
National Bank of Poland. He retired in 1968.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Agabashian</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Agabashian, who drove in 11 consecutive
Indianapolis 500 races during the 1940s and '50s, died Friday in
Alamo, Calif., at age 76.
   Agabashian, whose top finish was fourth in 1953, made his first
Indy 500 in 1947 when he finished ninth. He won the pole position
in 1952 with the Cummins Diesel Special, but again finished ninth.
   After his last Indy 500 in 1957, he went to work for Champion
Spark Plug Co., until his retirement in 1978.
   He also was a color commentator on the speedway's radio network.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lydia Kahn Winston Malbin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lydia Kahn Winston Malbin, a lifetime trustee of
the Detroit Institute of Arts, died Saturday of heart failure at
age 91.
   Malbin had lived in New York City since 1973 but retained strong
ties to Michigan.
   She was the museum's honorary curator of 20th century art. From
1964 to 1984, she served on the Detroit Arts Commission, which
administers the DIA.
   Malbin had been buying art since the 1930s. Her holdings
included works by Pablo Picasso, Fernand Leger, the Italian
Futurists and Henry Moore.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ludwig Gluskin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ludwig Gluskin, a drummer for ``King
of Jazz'' Paul Whiteman who also led his own Big Band-era group
before taking over as music director for CBS radio and TV, died
Friday of kidney failure. He was 90.
   Born in New York City, Gluskin played in his first band with
boyhood friend Jimmy Durante. Later, Gluskin became a drummer for
Whiteman, the so-called 1920s ``King of Jazz.''
   Gluskin toured Europe with Whiteman and then settled in France.
In 1927, he became leader of the Playboys, a Detroit jazz band that
became stranded in Paris. The Playboys made more than 700
recordings in Paris and Berlin.
   Gluskin returned to New York and was hired by CBS in 1935. He
was named director of music in 1937 for CBS Radio.
   He directed the music for Mercury Theatre Of The Air's famous
1938 hoax about a Martian invasion, ``War of the Worlds.'' He also
directed the music for such shows as ``Adventures of Sam Spade,''
``My Friend Irma,'' ``I Was There'' and ``The Phillip Morris
Playhouse.''
   In 1948, Gluskin became music director for CBS-TV and presided
over its shows for 10 years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Delchamps Jr.</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CREOLA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Delchamps Jr., chairman and chief
executive officer of the Delchamps Inc. grocery store chain, died
Sunday in the crash of a World War II-vintage military plane.
   Delchamps, 58, and aerobatic pilot Mark Reynolds, 65, were
killed when the 1942 BT-13 aircraft in which Reynolds was giving
Delchamps flying lessons stalled and crashed about 3:19 p.m.,
authorities and witnesses said.
   Delchamps, board chairman since 1983, began working for his
family's Mobile-based company in 1953. Delchamps operates 107
grocery stores in Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and the Florida
Panhandle and employs 7,600 employees.
</TEXT>
