<DOCNO> AP891016-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SafetyCommission     10-16 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Safety Commission,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Advocates Question Nominee's Qualifications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer advocates and others say they're glad
President Bush is finally filling a vacancy that will put the
Consumer Product Safety Commission back in business _ but they're
troubled with his choice for the job.
   Bush last week nominated Jacqueline Jones-Smith as the panel's
third commissioner. If confirmed by the Senate, she would succeed
Terrence M. Scanlon to head the commission and would provide the
quorum the panel needs to conduct business.
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' said Mary Ellen Fise, product
safetyrector at the Consumer Federation of America, thgest consumer
advocacy group. ``We're happy that finally the commission will be
able to act again.''
   ``There was concern for the overall commission in the fact that
it can't function now. They can't take formal action,'' said one
congressional aide.
   The agency has been virtually powerless without its
congressionally mandated quorum of three since Scanlon's departure
nine months ago. It cannot hold meetings to proceed with rulemaking
or many enforcement activities.
   Earlier, consumer advocates attacked Scanlon's emphasis on
voluntary ety standards and cooperation with industry. Theny
criticized Bush for allowing the commission to languish without its
third member.
   But now, some expresss about whether Jones-Smith has the
necessary bexperience in the consumer arena.
   Jones-Smien a staff attorney in the general counsel's ofl
Election Commission since 1987. She also was an assistant county
attorney in Montgomery County, Md.
   ``Whdn't find was any evidence of experience in consumer product
safety issues,'' said Pam Gilbert, consumer program director of the
Public Interest Research Group, founded by consumer advocate Ralph
Nader.
   ``That's where I would register my concern. She would be the
chairman of the Consumer Product Safety Commission with little or
no experience in product safety issues,'' Gilbert said.
   However, Bonnie Guiton, head of the White House office of
consumer affairs, said, ``There is value to someone who hasn't been
so locked in that they can't see things with a balanced
perspective.''
   ``Jackie is very bright, very capable and her legal background
makes her very thorough,'' said Guiton, a friend of Jones-Smith.
   There also has been concern on Capitol Hill about her ``lack of
formal background in consumer matters,'' according to one House
Commerce committee staffer who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   However, most in consumer interests circles say they believe
Jones-Smith will be confirmed by the Senate.
   The commission is an independent regulatory agency established
by Congress in 1972. It is responsible for assuring the safety of
more than 15,000 types of consumer products, except prescription
and over-the-counter drugs, automobiles and cosmetics.
   The uthorizes five commissioners, appointed by the president and
serving staggered seven-year termsess has provided funds for only
three commissioners in recent years.
   Since Scanlon's January departure, Ane Graham, acting
chairwoman, and Carol G. Dawson, both Republicans, have continued
on the commSmith would fill a Democratic spot on the panel.
   Jones-Smith is married to Republican businessman Joshua I.
Smith, who was a Bush campaign fund-raiser.
