<FIRST>r w PM-CleanAirSnafu     10-16 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air Snafu,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Shows Disorganized Strategy on Clean Air Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil and auto company lobbyists had worked
furiously to weaken President Bush's plan to produce millions of
clean-fuel cars _ and it was time for a crucial subcommittee vote
on gutting the program.
   Rep. Norman F. Lent, R-N.Y., the bill's chief sponsor, told the
packed hearing room that White House Chief of Staff John Sununu
told him the administration did not oppose the weakening amendment.
   But Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., piped up that he just got a
call from Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William K.
Reilly, saying the administration vigorously opposed the change.
   The mixup exposed a disorganized administration seemingly in
conflict with itself over President Bush's clean air bill. The
weakening amendment passed the House Energy and Commerce
environment subcommittee on Wednesday, 12-10.
   ``I don't know where the administration is and it may be all
over the lot ... on both sides,'' said Waxman, the subcommittee
chairman, shortly before the vote. ``It tells a lot about how
they're handling the bill.''
   Actually, the administration did have a workable strategy _ to
oppose the industry amendment but show a willingness to negotiate
changes to restore the thrust of Bush's proposal.
   But the strategy broke apart the day of last week's vote.
   The administration only had to turn one GOP vote around, but the
mixed signals were ``the blessing from the Pope that Republicans
needed'' to vote with the special interests, according to a
Democratic staffer, speaking only on condition he not be named.
   The incident was just the latest example of administration
officials sowing confusion about their position on a key issue.
   When the Senate was debating repeal of catastrophic health
coverage for retirees, Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan publicly endorsed an amendment that would have salvaged
most of the program. Within hours, White House Budget Director
Richard G. Darman said Sullivan was not speaking for the
administration, which was not endorsing any particular amendment.
   In the failed coup against Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the administration's actions _ reported as confused and
cautious _ failed to match Bush's rhetoric encouraging dissident
officers to overthrow the strongman.
   The clean air vote ``could have been avoided by sending a clear
message that the administration was opposed'' to the weakening
language, the Democratic staffer said.
   At stake was a provision that the White House previously
characterized as ``the most innovative and far-reaching'' component
of Bush's proposals to clear up urban smog by the end of the
century.
   In fact, according to lawmakers and administration officials,
negotiations to change the amendment were underway as the
subcommittee convened last Wednesday. But instead of communicating
that, Lent and Waxman told of the conflicting phone calls.
   Amid such confusion, eight Republicans and four Democrats backed
the weakening changes, while nine Democrats and one Republican
opposed them.
   The vote weakened Bush's proposed performance standard for fuels
other than pure gasoline, and dropped the required production of 1
million clean-fuel cars a year between 1997 and 2004. The change
would allow automakers to simply certify that they could build the
cars.
   The administration is negotiating with amendment sponsors Jack
Fields, R-Texas and Ralph Hall, D-Texas, to revive the key portions
of Bush's proposal in the full Energy and Commerce Committee.
   White House press spokesman Stephen Hart said Sununu did not
change the administration's position that the amendment should move
closer to the president's language. Any misunderstanding rested
with Lent, he added.
   Lent said in an interview that ``undoubtedly there was a
misunderstanding,'' about Sununu's position _ and acknowledged he
may not have given the subcommittee the full picture by failing to
mention the changes demanded by the administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
