<DOCNO> AP891016-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UNESCO     10-16 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UNESCO,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Return May Hinge on Outcome of Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As UNESCO opens a monthlong meeting to chart its
future course, the United States is expressing doubt that the
troubled world body will jettison enough ideology to bring about
Washington's return as a member.
   The 158-nation organization will also decide whether to admit
the PLO as a full member, a step the United States has said will
rule out any possibility of it rejoining the agency.
   The meeting, beginning Tuesday, represents a crucial test for
Director-General Federico Mayor. The Spanish biochemist and former
education minister took over as head of the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization two years ago.
   He must see that the new, more pragmatic program he has proposed
for the first half of the 1990s gets approved without any of the
ideological overtones that led to U.S. and British withdrawal in
the mid-1980s.
   A former U.S. senator heading an international panel examining
UNESCO policies backed Mayor's plan.
   Republican Robert T. Stafford of Vermont, speaking for the
Americans on the panel, said Thursday that if UNESCO adopts ``the
substance'' of Mayor's plan, ``the United States should resume its
membership in UNESCO early in 1990.''
   But the panel, in a report released today, said UNESCO will
remain an ``underperformer'' unless it adopts reforms and seeks
advice from eminent scientists and experts in human rights,
communications and other fields.
   ``The key to UNESCO's success is professionalization'' in its
programs, says the report commissioned by the U.N. Association of
the U.S.A., a private group interested in strengthening and
improving the United Nations and other international agencies.
   Panelists were drawn from America, the Soviet Union and numerous
other industrialized and developing countries and spanned the
ideological spectrum.
   The United States and Britain, which between them provided 30
percent of UNESCO's budget, pulled out because they said UNESCO had
become too political, spent too much money and was poorly managed.
   Singapore also left, saying it could spend its dues better
elsewhere.
   Some 2,000 delegates will attend the biennial meeting of the
General Conference, the organization's highest decision-making
body. In addition to charting UNESCO's future activities, they will
adopt a budget for 1990-1991.
   The United States and Britain have said they will review their
positions on rejoining UNESCO after the General Conference ends.
   Last month, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State John R. Bolton
told a congressional committee that it was ``extremely unlikely''
the United States would rejoin the body if its current draft plan
for 1990-1995 is approved.
   Bolton said Mayor, who took over in November 1987 from Amadou
Mahtar M'Bow of Senegal, had promised to depoliticize the world
body, introduce budgetary restraints, cut back on activities and
``neutralize'' a drive by Third World nations to set up a new world
information order.
   Bolton said Mayor failed on all counts and has been ``hesitant
to enunciate a clear, new direction, much less institute
significant change or programmatic reforms.''
   Mayor has said his room for maneuver was somewhat limited
because he had inherited M'Bow's programs. He said more reform
would come after the General Conference adopted his proposals.
   But he asserts that since he took over UNESCO has become more
open, improved its management and strengthened its ties with member
states and other U.N. agencies. He promised to make personnel
changes but said he would not remove senior aides appointed by
M'Bow.
   On the Palestine Liberation Organization's request for
membership, he has said the U.N. General Assembly should decide
such issues, not UNESCO. But he has promised to involve the
Palestine observer mission more closely in UNESCO activities.
   UNESCO's executive board recommended Wednesday that the PLO
request be put off until 1991.
   As at previous conferences for more than a decade, one of the
most contentious issues will be the New World Information and
Communication Order.
   Mayor presented a new reform-oriented free press approach in the
communications section of the plan for 1990-1995. But members of
UNESCO's 50-nation executive board, including Senegal's Iba Der
Thiam, made changes steering the plan toward disputed objectives.
   The delegates will have to decide whether to accept the board's
changes or stick with the draft proposed by Mayor.
   To overcome what they see as Western domination in the flow of
information, Third World nations, backed by the Soviet bloc, favor
the new information order so they can regulate content of news and
enlist media support for government objectives.
   Western nations and news organizations say the order could lead
to censorship and other restrictions on journalists.
</TEXT>
