<FIRST>r w PM-Privatization     10-16 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Privatization,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Scandals, Management Reviews Question Reagan's Privatization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, partly because of the
federal housing scandal, appears to be quietly moving away from the
Reagan-era policy of turning more and more governmental functions
over to private enterprise.
   Publicly the administration remains committed to the policy of
``privatization,'' and the sale of some government assets remains
an attractive means to help reduce the budget deficit. But there
are a number of signs that the Bush administration does not share
its predecessor's zeal for finding ways to contract out work done
by government employees.
   After nine months in office, Budget Director Richard Darman has
not yet replaced previous officials who ran President Reagan's
privatization program.
   ``Let's not ignore the proper role of government in determining
those instances where the public benefit outweighs the costs,''
Darman's deputy, Frank Hodsoll, earlier this year told the
Privatization Council, a lobbying group formed in the Reagan years.
   ``We must draw the line between public responsibility and
private provision of goods and services,'' Hodsoll said.
   Conservatives estimate that privatization could save the
taxpayers billions of dollars, but a leading congressional watchdog
of Reagan's efforts, Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., said government
accountability should come before possible savings.
   ``Contractors, not government officials, often have effective
responsibility for the most basic decision-making,'' Pryor said.
   Darman recently told Congress ``the management problems of the
federal government are enormous.'' That assessment was based
largely on a government-wide review he ordered after reports
surfaced of widespread fraud and mismanagement at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development expected to cost the government $6
billion.
   Several officials who responded to the review questioned the
effectiveness of contracting out certain services and said civil
service morale needed a boost.
   ``Management and internal control oversight are inherently
governmental functions which are adversely affected by initiatives
like the current strong OMB (Office of Management and Budget)
emphasis on contracting out,'' NASA Deputy Administrator James R.
Thompson Jr. said in his memo to Darman.
   ``Nearly 90 percent of our funds pass through deliverers whose
operations and accounting systems are not under DOL operational
control,'' Labor Department Deputy Secretary Rod DeArment wrote to
Darman.
   Those who helped Reagan push his privatization plan contend
neither Bush nor Darman was committed to the idea and now can use
the HUD scl as a reason to halt the effort.
   ``It's norivatization that went wrong, it was the execution,''
said the ritage Foundation's Stephen Moore, who was resefor
Reagan's Commission on Privatization. ``Pri is being made a
scapegoat here.''
   Moore's ts mirror those of HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, who ushing
ahead with some of the more controversial elements of the Reagan
privatization plan: allowing tenants to public housing and
providing rent vouchers to instead of subsidies to their landlords.
   `t the idea, it was the implementation of the ide Kemp said when
asked if the $1 billion losses a HUD co-insurance program stemmed
from privatiin that case giving private lenders the power tove
government-insured loans.
   Under Reagan,rivatization was established within the budget
office and aidesere told to search for government assets and seo be
turned over to the private sector. As a rember of government
agencies now contract out secial and food service work, computer
processing and repairs and other work.
   HUD allows private lenders to process and approve government
loans; the Environmental Protection Agency hires consultants to
interpret regulations and the Energy Department contracts out
management of its nuclear facilities.
   Reagan's OMB in late 1987 estimated the government had saved
more than $2 billion through privatization and that several billion
more could be saved annually if more government work was contracted
out.
   Heritage, a conservative think tank, estimated $3 billion a year
could be saved by expanded privatization and a commission Reagan
appointed put the annual savings at $4.6 billion if work now
performed by 400,000 federal workers was contracted out.
   File NOT Found
</TEXT>
