<SECOND>PM-People-Homeless,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Participate in Weekend Charity Work _ And Fun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Father-and-son actors Martin Sheen and Emilio
Estevez pounded the pavement to help the city's homeless find
shelter.
   The two celebrities were joined by more than 100 recovering drug
addicts from Skid Row in Saturday's third-annual Run for the
Homeless in Griffith Park.
   ``I'm so proud of myself because I thought about quitting or
cheating by tripping somebody near me during the race,'' said Betty
Wright, 25, who finished next to last among the group of Skid Row
runners. ``But I figured if I could do this honestly, I can do
anything.''
   More than 1,000 participated in the 5-kilometer run, raising
more than $100,000, sponsors said. The event benefited Chrysalis, a
non-profit organization that finds jobs and shelter for the
homeless.
   Roni Apple, 32, who lives in a Salvation Army treatment center
on Skid Row, said the race ``showed me _ amazingly enough _ that I
still have my health'' after years of drug abuse.
   ``Bad luck and timing have put many families out in the cold,''
Sheen said in a statement issued before the run. ``This is one way
to get these homeless people back in the running.''
