<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-Sisulu     10-16 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Sisulu,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sisulu Ranks With Mandela Among Prominent Black Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt ^By GREG MYRE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African blacks view Nelson
Mandela and Walter Sisulu as virtual equals, and the Sisulu clan is
widely considered the first family of the anti-apartheid movement.
   But during their long imprisonment, Mandela, a college-educated
lawyer and charismatic speaker, captured the international
spotlight rather than Sisulu, a former laborer and high school
dropout.
   ``I am happy to be with the people and to receive a civilized
welcome,'' Sisulu told hundreds of supporters and journalists
gathered outside his small stucco house in Soweto after his release
from 26 years in prison Sunday.
   Despite his unpromising origins, Sisulu has become one of the
most respected thinkers and strategists of the outlawed African
National Congress. His wife and six children are committed and
respected activists in the anti-apartheid movement.
   Wearing glasses and a gray suit, the white-haired, 77-year-old
Sisulu looked more like a church elder than leader of an outlawed
guerrilla group.
   But he remains completely dedicated to his organization, which
was formed in 1912, the year he was born in the Xhosa homeland of
Transkei, also Mandela's birthplace.
   Unlike Mandela, who is related to a tribal chief and was trained
for leadership, Sisulu was born into rural poverty and quit school
at 15 to help support his family.
   He held jobs as a baker's assistant, domestic servant, dairy
worker, factory laborer and gold miner. After quarreling with
employers over wages and work conditions, he set up his own real
estate business, which lasted only a few years.
   Sisulu joined the then-legal ANC in Johannesburg in 1940, and
became known as the person young men from the rural areas should
see to get a start in the big city. He advised and helped Mandela
and current ANC President Oliver Tambo, who are both six years
younger.
   Sisulu was secretary-general of the ANC and ran its day-to-day
operations from 1949 to 1954, when the government ordered him to
resign. After that, he continued to participate behind the scenes.
   He was imprisoned eight times from 1953 to 1964 and was one of
156 defendants in the 1956 to 1961 treason trial of government
opponents, which ended with acquittals for all.
   In 1962, Sisulu was arrested six times, but charged only once.
He was convicted in March 1963 of furthering the aims of the ANC,
which had been banned in 1960.
   Released on appeal, Sisulu went underground and joined the ANC's
armed wing. In July 1963 he was arrested with others at the ANC's
secret headquarters in Rivonia, outside Johannesburg, and charged
with sabotage.
   During the trial, Sisulu acknowledged the ANC had used sabotage
but denied the state's charge that a guerrilla war had been
launched because, he said, ``There was still hope.''
   ``Leading Afrikaner intellectuals began to meet leaders of the
African people,'' he said. ``It was my view that well-conducted
political action could bring about a changed situation.''
   Sisulu's wife, Albertina, is a prominent activist in her own
right. She was banned from 1964 until 1981, and was served with new
restrictions in 1988 because of her role as co-president of the
banned United Democratic Front, an anti-apartheid coalition. Her
restrictions were lifted on Friday.
   The government granted her a limited passport in June, allowing
her to leave the country for the first time. She met President Bush
and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, among other world
leaders.
   The couple's oldest son and daughter, Max and Lindiwe, live in
exile. Their third child, Zwelakhe, editor of the New Nation, was
freed in 1988 after being detained without charge for two years. He
is prohibited from working as a journalist.
   The Sisulus' adopted son, Jonguzi, was sentenced to five years
on Robben Island for treason. Another son, Mlungisi, runs a small
business in Soweto. The youngest daughter, Nonkululekhe, attends
the University of the Western Cape.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
