<DOCNO> AP891016-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion     10-16 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Governors Plea to Supreme Court Wins Pro-Choice Applause</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten governors, in an unusual
friend-of-the-court brief filed with the Supreme Court are urging
the justices to reject efforts to restrict abortion.
   The governors asked the high court to strike down an Illinois
statute they said would impose ``extremely burdensome
requirements'' on abortion clinics.
   They added that while it is their job to enforce constitutional
rights, it is up to the courts to define those rights.
   They urged the high court not to scale back the principle laid
down in the landmark 1973 case, Roe v. Wade, holding that women
have a constitutional right to abortions during the first three
months of pregnancy.
   The amicus curiae brief in the Illinois case, Turnock v.
Ragsdale, was signed by Govs. Madeline Kunin of Vermont, James
Blanchard of Michigan, Richard Celeste of Ohio, Steve Cowper of
Alaska, Mario Cuomo of New York, Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts,
Booth Gardner of Washington, Neil Goldschmidt of Oregon, John
McKernan of Maine and Roy Romer of Colorado.
   McKernan is a Republican; the other nine are Democrats.
   Kunin told reporters after addressing the closing session of the
20th annual conference of the National Abortion Rights Action
League on Sunday, ``The climate has dramatically changed in the
past two weeks.''
   She cited the failure of abortion restrictions during a special
session of the Florida legislature last week, and the House vote to
expand Medicaid eligibility for abortions to victims of rape and
incest.
   President Bush said Friday he is looking to see if there is
``room for flexibility'' to avoid a veto on the Medicaid abortion
funding.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, speaking Sunday
on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' said a veto ``would be a tragic
mistake on his part. We're talking here about the poorest, most
vulnerable American women, those who have become pregnant after
being victims of rape or incest, and can't afford to pay for an
abortion.''
   The governors' brief, dropped off at court offices Saturday,
said:
   ``It would be unprecedented for this court, having recognized a
fundamental constitutional right, to withdraw that right and throw
the abortion issue back into the political arena.''
   The governors expressed ``concern that the workable and
restraining constitutional guidelines that have developed since Roe
v. Wade may yield to laws that discriminate unfairly against large
segments of our population, are easily evaded by persons with
money, or are so widely ignored that evenhanded enforcement becomes
impossible.''
   They said they are also worried that respect for law is eroded
by statutes such as the Illinois one ``that purport to regulate
health when their true purpose _ restricting abortions _ is
apparent.''
   If the right to a first trimester abortion is abandoned, they
said, women's ability to choose ``would be determined primarily by
whether she fortuitously resides in, or has the ability to travel
to, a state where abortions'' remain legal.
   The Supreme Court has scheduled arguments Dec. 5 on the Illinois
statute, which a federal judge and the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals
already have struck down.
   However, a new bid is being made in Illinois to settle the case
before it goes any further.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
