<DOCNO> AP891016-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-MississippiElection     10-16 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Election,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP's Anderson Racing to Make Up Lost Ground in Congressional Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a boost from President Bush,
Republican Tom Anderson is racing to make up ground in Tuesday's
special election that could cost the GOP its last U.S. House seat
in Mississippi.
   Based on returns in the primary election and recent polls,
Democratic state Sen. Gene Taylor is the front-runner to take the
5th District seat Republicans have held 16 years.
   Anderson, 43, is an aide to Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., a national
spokesman on conservative issues who formerly held the south
Mississippi House seat now being contested.
   Anderson acknowledges he's chasing Taylor.
   ``It has been a long campaign in a very short period of time.
We've got a long way to go. And, I am the underdog, but we can do
it,'' Anderson said at a rally last week.
   Taylor, 36, who represents Bay St. Louis in the Legislature,
captured 42 percent in Oct. 3's open primary, while Anderson
finished second with 37 percent.
   The seat become vacant when freshman Republican Rep. Larkin
Smith, a popular former sheriff, died in an Aug. 13 plane crash.
Smith won the office in 1988, beating Taylor.
   The national parties view the campaign as a key battleground
less than a year before the 1990 congressional elections.
   Bush visited last week at Lott's urging and appeared at a rally
for Anderson.
   ``Part of the legacy of Larkin Smith is making sure that his
successor carries on the work you sent him to do in Washington. I
know Tom Anderson is the right man,'' Bush said.
   ``Tommy took on two Democrats who ganged up on him at every
turn, and tried to smear his good name,'' said Rep. Guy Vander
Jagt, R-Mich., chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee. ``But Tom remained on the high road and continued to run
on the issues, and he was rewarded for that by the intelligent
voters of Mississippi's 5th District.''
   The candidates differ little on issues.
   Anderson has tried to pin the ``liberal'' label on Taylor, who
contends his voting record in the Mississippi Senate is
conservative.
   ``I'm a conservative Southern Democrat,'' Taylor has said.
   The district, which includes Gulfport and Biloxi on the thriving
coast, has a history of voting Republican. It twice rejected
southerner Jimmy Carter and went 87 percent for Richard Nixon in
1972, the highest percentage he won in any congressional district.
   In 1972, Lott, then a top aide to U.S. Rep. Bill Colmer, was
elected to Congress from the district. Lott, who was minority whip,
gave up the seat to win the Senate post of the retiring Democrat
John C. Stennis in 1988.
   Anderson has been Lott's chief of staff since 1972, except for
two years as he spent as ambassador to Barbados during the Reagan
administration.
   Anderson has spent more than $500,000 bolstering his name
recognition after living in Washington for 17 years. Taylor has
spent more than $100,000.
   Anderson also has had to deal with the appearance of being
Lott's hand-picked candidate.
   Lott rallied Republicans around Anderson after clearing the
field of other Republicans, including Sheila Smith, wife of the
late congressman.
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee has filed two
ethics complaints against Anderson _ for allegedly failing to list
all flights he took while a Lott aide on the jet of a Mississippi
corporation, and for alleged discrepancies between financial
disclosure statements filed with the Senate and House.
   Anderson and the Republicans have labeled the complaints as
smear tactics, but Democrats contend the issues are real.
   ``Mississippi has a long history of sending members to Congress
who are beyond reproach when it comes to integrity and honesty,''
said Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of his party's
congressional campaign committee. ``Tom Anderson is a walking
ethics scandal. The voters of the 5th District can't possibly
approve of these actions by Mr. Anderson.''
   If Taylor wins the election, the Democrats would have all five
Mississippi seats in the U.S. House for the first time since 1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
