<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneFire     10-16 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Fire,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Probe Charred Boeing 727</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators seeking the cause of a flash
fire that gutted a parked Delta Air Lines jetliner said they are
focusing on an area in the belly of the Boeing 727 that houses
computer gear.
   A team of federal inspectors arrived Sunday to join the
investigation of the blaze, which burned a 4-by-15-foot hole in the
side of the plane as it sat at a Salt Lake International Airport
boarding gate.
   Saturday's fire forced the nine passengers and six crew members
aboard to evacuate. Five crew members and one passenger were
treated for smoke inhalation.
   The investigation, assisted by representatives of Delta and
Boeing Co., should take three or four days, said Bob Johnson,
regional director for the National Transportation Safety Board in
Denver.
   The fire broke out 20 minutes before Flight 1558 was to leave
for Edmonton, Alberta. The flight, which began in Los Angles, had a
one-hour layover in Salt Lake City and most passengers were in the
terminal.
   Those aboard reported hearing a loud pop before smoke began
billowing from a vent in the first-class section.
   Early indications are the fire broke out in a spot below and
behind the cockpit, where the plane's computer and avionics nerve
center are housed, said Johnson and Delta spokesman Fred Rollins.
   ``We are focusing on that area,'' Rollins said. ``But it's
really too early to speculate on the cause.''
   Investigators have determined that the fire didn't begin in the
baggage area. FAA officials initially sealed the plane and kept the
baggage from being returned to the passengers, but Rollins said the
luggage was released later.
   Firefighters extinguished the flames within 15 minutes,
authorities said.
   Delta has yet to determine if the $30 million airliner can be
flown again, said Rollins, who was unable to provide a damage
estimate.
   The fire heavily damaged the aircraft's interior and melted
portions of the metal skin.
</TEXT>
