<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-MarketScene     10-16 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Market Scene,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Markets On Hold; Watching Wall Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors' message to Wall Street today
was: ``It's up to you now. We held on.''
   Instead of unloading their shares in panic as they did two years
ago after Wall Street crashed, most Japanese market players were in
a holding pattern.
   They watched anxiously today as the Tokyo Stock Exchange posted
a sharp, but not disastrous, loss in thin trading.
   ``I did not sell much, but it's tough to buy shares on a day
like today,'' said Hiroshi Yamamoto, a private investor watching
price displays before the Ginza branch of Nikko Securities Co. in
central Tokyo.
   ``Depending on how New York will do, today's drop may turn out
to be just timely relief for the Tokyo market, or an omen of
another crash,'' he said.
   Dealers and traders tried to build confidence and show they
learned from the 1987 crash, while investors remained calm compared
with two years ago.
   ``I don't think there were many investors who sold their
holdings in panic,'' said Keiichi Nishida, a dealer with Kidder
Peabody Securities in Tokyo. ``It was nothing like two years ago
when investors rushed to the brokerages to unload their holdings.
   ``So many investors only lost money two years ago when they sold
their shares quickly after Black Monday in New York, and these
shares quickly won back their loses,'' Nishida said. ``They have
learned lessons from that experience.''
   A day after Black Monday, when the Dow Jones industrial average
plunged 23 percent, the Nikkei average lost about 15 percent. But
the barometer gained back most losses in the next two days.
   The Nikko Securities retail brokerage office was somewhat busier
than usual today. Scores of phone calls poured in from investors
anxious to find out where their holdings stood.
   ``I am telling you that it's not time to sell yet. It's not too
late if we wait until tomorrow and see how New York will do,'' a
broker was overheard saying on the phone.
   Some investors said they were waiting for bargains rather than
to unload their shares.
   ``I expect the Nikkei index to remain bearish all day, but I am
not so worried because we all know it is due to external factors,''
said an investor watching the key index at Nomura Securities
shortly after the market opened.
   ``I am going to sit and wait for a while and start buying shares
later on as they start hitting the bottom,'' he said.
   A dealer at Nikko Securities said, ``Japanese private investors
seemed to have learned the lesson that fluctuation of the Wall
Street index is only one of many aspects of the Tokyo market. It is
undoubtedly an important element, but not necessarily as dominant
as it was thought to be.''
   Nishida said many investors remained hesitant to place purchase
orders today because ``they want to make sure that the New York
plunge was only a one-time thing, and the Dow Jones will not go
down further there.''
   Some investors said there was no reason why the Tokyo market
should suffer because of New York.
   ``If Tokyo plunges after New York, the whole world is in
trouble,'' said Motoko Goto, a veteran private investor.
   ``I think the Dow Jones average fell in New York because it was
Friday the 13th,'' she said. ``It may have a negative implication
in the Christian world, but there is no reason it should depress
the stock market in Japan.''
</TEXT>
