<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-USEspionage     10-16 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-US Espionage,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Officials Protest To Soviets in Espionage Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials today lodged a formal protest with
Soviet authorities after two Soviet officers were allegedly caught
trying to obtain classified military documents from a U.S. Air
Force airman in West Berlin.
   Anthony Sariti, a spokesman for the U.S. diplomatic mission in
West Berlin, said the protest was filed after two Soviet majors
were ``apprehended while engaging in espionage activities.''
   Sariti said Sunday night that the U.S. Air Force airman, whose
name was not released, was caught in the act of passing classified
information to the Soviets.
   But he said today that he had been mistaken, that the airman had
not been caught in the act. Sariti said he had erred Sunday night
because he did not at that time have with him the official news
release prepared in the case.
   Sariti said today that the Soviets were detained after asking
the airman to hand over documents on Saturday night. He said the
airman was cooperating with authorities.
   Sariti would not say how serious the case was.
   Both Soviet officers were questioned and then returned to ``the
Soviet sector,'' Sariti said in reference to East Berlin.
   He refused to say where the meeting had taken place and declined
to provide further details.
   He said returning the Soviets to East Berlin after questioning
was ``normal procedure.''
   Sariti said agreements with the Soviets regarding the divided
city provide that ``(military) forces from one side cannot be
arrested by the forces on the other side.''
   He said U.S. officials lodged a verbal protest with the Soviets
on Saturday night. Sariti said the Soviets had not responded to the
protests as of late this morning.
</TEXT>
