<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0478 10-16 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Arrives In Egypt For First Visit In 16 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Mubarak, Gadhafi arriving;
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERSA MATRUH, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi
arrived in this seaside resort today for talks with President Hosni
Mubarak, a milestone in ending one of the Arab world's bitterest
feuds.
   The leaders were to discuss regional affairs and resuming
diplomatic relations, Egyptian sources said on condition of
anonymity.
   ``Talks will concentrate on bilateral relations and how to
develop them,'' one source said.
   Gadhafi traveled the 150 miles from the frontier between the
North African neighbors to this historic town in a motorcade.
Mubarak flew from Cairo to Mersa Matruh. Welcoming ceremonies with
an honor guard and presentation of flowers were performed at the
airport.
   Mubarak and Gadhafi were to spend the night in Mersa Matrouh, a
popular Mediterranean resort 300 miles northwest of Cairo, then
travel to the Libyan border town of Tobruk for more talks on
Tuesday, sources in Cairo said.
   The visit is Gadhafi's first to Egypt in 16 years, but his
second meeting with Mubarak this year.
   Gadhafi led Arab opposition to Egypt's 1979 peace treaty with
Israel and was considered an archenemy until May, when he and
Mubarak met at an Arab summit in Morocco.
   After the reconciliation, the two countries opened their
borders, closed for 12 years, and land and air travel between the
nations resumed.
   Each country's media toned down persistent carping about the
other. The official Libyan agency stopped using the phrase
``Oppressed Egyptian Capital'' for Cairo.
   Unlike most visits to Egypt by Arab leaders, when host cities
are decked with banners and posters, no such signs of welcome were
in evidence in Mersa Matruh. There was, however, a notable increase
in security on city streets.
   Of the 17 Arab countries that broke relations with Egypt after
Mubarak's predecessor, Anwar Sadat, made peace with Israel, only
Libya and Syria have not resumed diplomatic ties.
   Gadhafi last visited Egypt in November 1973 when he joined Sadat
in a special Parliament session honoring top Egyptian military
officers for their performance in the 1973 Arab-Israeli war.
   But relations had already begun to sour a year earlier, when
Sadat refused overtures by Gadhafi to merge the two countries.
Gadhafi threatened to lead Libyan civilians on a march across the
border to enforce the merger.
   Relations further deteriorated in 1974 after Sadat's
rapprochement with the United States and his preliminary steps
toward peace with Israel, a move in which Egypt still stands alone
among the Arabs.
   Egypt blamed Libya for several bombings in Cairo and other
cities in 1975 to 1976, and the two fought a five-day border war in
July 1977. The border was sealed after that and remained closed
until after the May summit in Casablanca.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Profiles     10-16 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Profiles,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profiles of Eight Freed Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING TO FIX CYCLE DESIGNATOR.</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-SAfrica-Sisulu</UNK>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are profiles of the seven
South African political prisoners freed Sunday with Walter Sisulu.
Five were tried and sentenced in 1964, along with Nelson Mandela,
to life in prison for sabotage and conspiracy in a trial in the
Johannesburg suburb of Rivonia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AHMED KATHRADA:
   Kathrada, arrested at age 17 for participation in a passive
resistance campaign in 1946, was a member of the high command of
the African National Congress' military wing. He is one of only two
Rivonia defendants who denied all the charges against him. He was
convicted on only one count, sabotage.
   Kathrada was born Aug. 21, 1929, in the western Transvaal to a
scholarly Moslem family and became involved in politics at age 11.
He joined the Communist Party in the early 1940s and as general
secretary of the Transvaal Indian Congress was instrumental in
linking it to the African National Congress. He was acquitted in
the 1956-61 mass treason trial but placed under house arrest in
1962. He went underground a few months before his arrest at Rivonia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ELIAS MOTSOALEDI:
   As a founder of the Johannesburg regional command of the ANC's
military wing, Motsoaledi hid recruits and helped send them abroad
for military training and procuring arms, prosecutors alleged at
the Rivonia trial. He said he joined the military wing in 1962.
   Born in northern Transvaal Province on July 26, 1924, the son of
a migrant laborer, Motsoaledi worked in Johannesburg as a servant
and at factories. He joined the Communist Party in 1949 and the
congress in 1948.
   In 1949, he became chairman of the Council of Non-European Trade
Unions, organized strikes and was banned in 1952. He was held in
solitary confinement for three months in 1960 before going
underground. His wife, Caroline, lives in Soweto. Three of their
seven children are in exile.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RAYMOND MHLABA:
   At the Rivonia trial, Mhlaba denied he belonged to the high
command of the ANC's military wing. But he was identified in the
South African press as the man who became commander-in-chief after
the arrest in 1962 of Mandela.
   In 1952, Mhlaba was the first congress leader arrested as part
of the defiance campaign, when he led blacks through the ``whites
only'' entrance to a train station.
   He was born Dec. 2, 1920, son of a policeman. He dropped out of
school, became active in trade unions in Port Elizabeth, joined the
Communist Party in 1943 and the congress in 1944.
   In 1986, prison authorities allowed him to marry the mother of
three of his eight children.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ANDREW MLANGENI:
   Mlangeni said at the Rivonia trial he had agreed to carry
messages for the ANC's military wing, but he denied he was a
member. He was accused during the trial of being responsible for
explosives and being a member of the Johannesburg command.
   Born in Johannesburg on May 30, 1926, he worked as a golf caddy
to pay for school and later as a clerk, bus driver and journalist.
He joined the ANC in 1951 and was regional secretary for the
township of Soweto from 1958-60, before he went underground.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WILTON MKWAYI:
   Mkwayi, 66, briefly took command of the ANC's military wing
after the arrest of Mandela's colleagues in 1963. He was arrested
shortly afterwards and sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 after
being convicted on 58 counts of sabotage. The judge said Mkwayi
received guerrilla training in China and had taught ANC members how
to make bombs. In 1987, Mkwayi was allowed to marry his common-law
wife, Irene. She died in December.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAFTA MASEMULA:
   Masemula, 58, a member of the outlawed Pan Africanist Congress
guerrilla organization, was sentenced to life in prison in 1963 for
sabotage. At the time of his arrest in 1961, he was a primary
school teacher in Atteridgeville, near Pretoria. Some other members
of the Pan Africanist Congress were freed last year after agreeing
to a government offer of release in exchange for renunciation of
violence. Masemula refused to do so.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OSCAR MPETHA:
   The country's oldest political prisoner, 80-year-old Mpetha
began campaigning for black rights as a union organizer in the
1940s. A diabetic, he had a leg amputated in 1983 and been
hospitalized for most of the past three years.
   Born Aug. 5, 1909, he joined the ANC in 1951 and became its Cape
Town regional chairman in 1958. He helped found the
Communist-oriented South African Congress of Trade Unions.
   In 1980, he was charged with murder and terrorism in connection
with the slaying of two whites at a roadblock erected by black
youths near Cape Town. He was convicted of terrorism in 1983 and
began a five-year sentence in 1985 after losing an appeal.
   In August 1983, Mpetha was elected co-president of the United
Democratic Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition.
   Mpetha's wife and a son died while he was jailed. He was denied
permission to attend the funerals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Markets 3rdLd-Writethru a0482 10-16 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0482,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Fall In Early Trading, Then Recover Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE figures; ADDS trading elsewhere;
Picks up 13th pvs, `It's havoc...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plummeted in heavy but orderly
trading on London's stock market today in response to Wall Street's
plunge on Friday, then recovered slightly as bargain hunters
stepped in.
   Shares fell sharply on other European exchanges, then
stabilized. In Amsterdam, a limit was imposed on price declines,
and in Milan and Paris, trading in some shares was suspended
because of insufficient buying orders.
   In Brussels, an unusually heavy volume and order imbalance
delayed the start of computer-assisted trading by an hour.
   The London market, Europe's largest, was less panicky than
during the October 1987 crash, and the Stock Exchange said the
trading system was holding up well.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down
142.4 points, or 6.4 percent, at 2,091.5 two hours after it opened
and volume was a heavy 387.4 million shares.
   The index had opened 157.1 points _ down 6.8 percent. In trading
before London's exchange officially opened, the index was estimated
down 200 points, or 9 percent.
   Dealers are allowed to trade stocks outside exchange hours, and
it was during the pre-opening trading that bargain hunters entered
the market and triggered the partial recovery.
   ``There isn't the same panic as there was during the 1987
crash,'' said Bob Wade, joint head of market making at Robert
Fleming and Co. ``So the pressure on the dealing machinery hasn't
been so intense.''
   Charles Larkum, an equity analyst at the London investment firm
James Capel and Co., said, ``The market is looking for a level
which it is comfortable holding.''
   The dollar also sank and then partially recovered in European
trading. It was quoted at $1.5785 to the pound at midmorning
compared with $1.5625 late Friday. The dollar cost 1.8561 West
German marks and 140.99 Japanese yen, down from 1.9025 marks and
144 yen late Friday.
   Market makers, who are required to make continuous prices
available in certain stocks, were quoting prices on the exchange's
screen-based trading system normally, the exchange said.
   On Friday, Wall Street slumped after the London market closed
for the weekend, and initially, London investors were not reassured
by a relatively calm response in Tokyo earlier today.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before London dealings begin, the
Nikkei Stock Average fell 647.33 points, or 1.8 percent, to close
at 34,468.69 today.
   The Securities Association, which governs the London Stock
Exchange, met early today to assess Asia's response. Some
stockbrokers stayed in central London hotels overnight to get an
early start in trading.
   Stock Exchange Chairman Andrew Hugh Smith said before trading
began: ``I certainly do not think there is any reason to panic.''
   London market makers moved prices sharply lower in an effort to
protect themselves from any flood of sell orders, dealers said.
   ``It's havoc at the moment but we expect the market to stabilize
at lower levels ahead of the New York opening later Monday,'' said
Richard Dingwall-Smith, an economist at the London investment firm
County Natwest Woodmac Securities.
   Analysts said the London market was concerned that a fresh burst
of computer-driven selling on New York later today could drag the
market sharply lower.
   The plunge of 190 points in Wall Street's Dow Jones industrial
average Friday occurred two years after a 108-point Dow drop
presaged the Oct. 19, 1987 Black Monday crash of a record 508
points.
   The Bank of England said Saturday it saw ``no reason for such an
exaggerated fall in London share values.''
   It said it regarded the New York price fall as ``a special case,
sparked off by the collapse of the high-risk `junk bond' market,
which does not exist on anything like the same scale in London.''
   Michael Hughes, an economist with Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.,
said on BBC-TV that the apparent determination of governments to
prevent a 1987-style crash ``gives underlying support for the
market, so I wouldn't get overexcited'' about the danger of a full
crash.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve was reported ready to move large
amounts of cash into the American banking system if money was
needed to prevent a financial crisis. An option would be to lower
interest rates.
   But that was not seen as a choice for Britain, because of its
7.6 percent inflation rate. Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson last week raised base lending rates to an eight-year high of
15 percent to control inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
