<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0905EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JetCrash     10-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jet Crash,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Under Way Into Fatal Air Force Fighter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force investigators studied the
wreckage of an F-16 fighter jet today to determine what caused it
to turn upside down and slam into the ground, killing the two men
aboard.
   The jet, which had been on a training mission, went down Sunday
morning at Carswell Air Force Base, said a base spokesman.
   The fighter crashed just 200 feet from ``Bomber Row,'' a section
of the airfield's taxiway where about 10 B-52s were parked. Three
of them were slightly damaged.
   The victims were identified as the pilot, Reserve Maj. Robert M.
Tucker, 37, of Roanoke, Texas, and Marine Corps Capt. James T.
Bourne, 33, of Dallas, officials said.
   The crash site was restricted because of fuel that had spilled
and because of unspent ammunition that was aboard the aircraft,
said 1st Lt. Stephen Norton, a base spokesman.
   Officials said the jet was making a simulated attack run on the
base when the crash occurred. Witnesses said the fighter was 200 to
300 feet high when it listed to its right, turned upside down and
slammed into the ground.
   The jet was assigned to the 944th Tactical Fighter group, Air
Force Reserve, stationed at Luke Air Force Base near Phoenix, said
Luke AFB spokesman Capt. Joe Davis.
   The $20 million aircraft was en route from Dallas Naval Air
Station to Carswell on a training mission when it crashed, Norton
said.
   Col. John Sams Jr., the base commander, said it could take eight
to 12 months to determine the cause of the crash.
   Sunday's fatal crash followed by two days the crash of an Air
Force RF-4C jet that went down in a pasture near Bangs, Texas,
killing one of its two crewman. The RF-4C was stationed at
Bergstrom Air Force Base in Austin, about 150 miles from Bangs in
central Texas.
</TEXT>
