<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Parts     10-16 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Parts,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Parts Found in Northwest Iowa Farm Fields</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AH1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fan blade fragments probably severed the
hydraulic controls of a DC-10 this summer, crippling the aircraft
and causing it to plunge to the ground in a fiery crash, officials
said.
   General Electric Co. flight saftey investigator Jerry Clark
speculated about the cause of the crash Sunday night after more
than 100 volunteers swept farm fields in northwestern Iowa looking
for the missing parts from the No. 2 engine of United flight 232.
   The July 19 crash at the Sioux Gateway Airport _ 60 miles from
here _ killed 112 of the 296 people aboard.
   ``It is much more likely that the hydraulic lines were hit by
fan belt blade fragments than fan disc fragments,'' Clark said in a
telephone interview.
   Federal investigators are not sure whether the fan disk that has
already been recovered will solve the mystery.
   ``We won't know that until we analyze it, but we want to recover
everything that is out there,'' said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a spokesman
for the National Transportation Safety Board.
   Searchers on Sunday found a sheared off bolt buried 3 inches in
the ground of a field near Alta. On Saturday, searchers found a
part of a fan blade sticking out of the ground in a nearby field.
   The search was financed by GE, which made the plane's engine in
1972.
   Alta-area farmer Janice Sorenson earned a $119,000 reward for
finding about two-thirds of the rear engine fan disc while
harvesting corn on her farm last Tuesday. The remainder of the disk
was found Thursday on the nearby farm of Harold Halverson, who will
collect about $40,000.
   GE paid $1,000 each for the bolt and fan blade fragment
discovered this weekend. An equal payment of $1,000 was made to the
metal detector clubs that found the parts and the owners of the
land, Nick Droegmiller and Dale Sorenson.
   ``The important thing is to try to get as much of the rotating
parts of the engine back to Cincinnati (where GE makes engines) so
we can understand the complete failure sequence,'' said Clark.
   The engine broke apart north of Alta, cutting parts of hydraulic
lines that controlled the flight of the jumbo jet. Pilots were able
to guide the craft erratically to Sioux City, but the plane crashed
in flames on landing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
