<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany     10-16 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regional Communist Leaders Reportedly Urge Ouster of Honecker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's regional Communist Party leaders
have urged a sweeping reshuffle of the ruling Politburo and the
ouster of hard-line leader Erich Honecker, a West German newspaper
reported today.
   Also today, the government's labor chief warned of growing
tension among the nation's work force. Opposition activists planned
a mass protest in Leipzig tonight to press for democratic reforms.
   The mass-circulation Bild newspaper, quoting what it called
``well- informed'' sources in East Berlin, said 13 of the 15
regional Communist Party chiefs are demanding dramatic changes in
leadership as well as an easing of the nation's hard-line policies.
   Bild said the demand for Honecker's ouster and the reshuffling
of the Polituro comes ``because they (the regional Communist
chiefs) fear that strikes and unrest will break out all across the
nation.''
   According to Bild, the regional chiefs are demanding that the
government enter into talks with opposition groups, loosen travel
restrictions to the West and hold free elections with independent
candidates.
   Bild is owned by the conservative Springer publishing group,
which has been at odds with East Germany's leadership for decades.
   Honecker's hard-line stance has come under increasing criticism
at home.
   Party sources have said leaders in East Berlin are unhappy over
the way Honecker, Communist Party chief since 1971, has handled the
current unrest in the country and that he has lost support in the
163-seat Central Committee.
   ``I can say openly that the climate among the workers is
tense,'' said Harry Tisch, a member of the ruling Politburo who
oversees the nation's nearly 8.6 million workers.
   In an interview with the state-run newspaper newspaper Junge
Welt, Tisch said Communist leaders must respond to complaints from
workers ``or others will'' _ an apparent reference to the nation's
growing opposition movement.
   Despite official warnings against street protests, opposition
activists plan to demonstrate tonight in Leipzig to press demands
for democratic reforms.
   More than 70,000 people joined in a pro-democracy march in
Leipzig last Monday, the largest single protest in nearly four
decades.
   Tens of thousands of East Germans have taken to the streets in
recent weeks to demand reforms in the largest protests since a 1953
uprising that was crushed by Soviet tanks.
   More than 52,000 East Germans have fled West since Sept. 10 from
Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Poland. Some 70,000 more have been
allowed to emigrate legally so far this year, or have refused to
return to their homeland.
</TEXT>
