<FIRST>u w PM-BusinessInventories     10-16 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Inventories,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growth in Business Sales Far Outstrips Inventory Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.3 percent in
August, but business sales gained a hefty 3.1 percent, the
government reported today.
   The combination of sales advancing far faster than the
accumulation of goods on shelves and backlots normally is good news
for the economy. If inventories were to pile up excessively, it
could mean cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs.
   The Commerce Department said inventories climbed to a seasonally
adjusted $789.9 billion in August, following a gain of 0.9 percent
in July.
   Business sales, meanwhile, rose to a seasonally adjusted $526.8
billion after dropping 0.9 percent in July.
   The August business activity produced a decrease in the ratio of
inventories to sales. It was 1.50, meaning it would take one and
one-half months to exhaust inventories at the August pace. The
ratio stood at 1.54 in July.
   The business picture could have continued to improve last month.
The Commerce Department reported last week that September retail
sales were up a moderate 0.5 percent after a 0.7 percent gain in
August.
   Manufacturers' inventories, which represent about 45 percent of
the total, rose 0.3 percent while retailers' backlogs increased 0.7
percent. Wholesalers registered a 0.1 drop.
   Overall inventories were 7.1 percent above those of a year ago.
   Manufacturers' sales, on the other hand, rose 5.6 percent.
Retailers' sales were up 0.7 percent and wholesalers' 1.5 percent.
   Total sales were up 7.1 percent from August 1988.
</TEXT>
