<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Contempt     10-16 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Contempt,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaRouche-Linked Committee Loses Appeal, Faces Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political action committee linked to fringe
presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche lost a Supreme Court appeal
today, and now faces having to pay $2.7 million in
contempt-of-court fines.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear the National
Democratic Policy Committee's challenge to fines stemming from a
federal mail fraud and conspiracy prosecution.
   LaRouche is serving a 15-year prison sentence after being
convicted of conspiracy to commit mail fraud involving more than
$30 million in defaulted loans, 11 counts of actual mail fraud
involving $294,000 in defaulted loans, and one count of conspiring
to defraud the Internal Revenue Service.
   Four organizations associated with LaRouche _ Caucus
Distributors, Campaigner Publications, Fusion Energy Foundation and
the National Democratic Policy Committee _ were cited for contempt
in connection with a grand jury investigation of him.
   U.S. District Judge P. David Mazzone in Boston ruled that the
organizations had failed to comply with subpoenas ordering release
of all fundraising records.
   Mazzone originally imposed $6.55 million in fines against Caucus
Distributors, based in Leesburg, Va., and $5.1 million fines
against each of the three other organizations.
   The amounts were set aside by the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, and Mazzone was ordered to recalculate the fines.
   Last Sept. 13, the judge ordered Caucus Distributors to pay $2.6
million and the three other organizations to pay $2.7 million each.
   The appeal acted on today was filed last August, before
Mazzone's latest action. The appeal was filed in behalf of the
National Democratic Policy Committee only.
   Peter Gelhaar, a federal prosecutor in Boston, said denial of
Supreme Court review would clear the way for payment of the
contempt fines.
   ``We're going to go forward vigorously to collect these fines,''
he said in an interview.
   The case is National Democratic Policy Committee vs. U.S.,
89-320.
</TEXT>
