<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Union     10-16 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Union,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal by Right-to-Work Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
a right-to-work group that sought to limit the power of unions to
collect dues from non-members.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments in an
Illinois case that the group was treated unfairly by a federal
appeals court.
   The justices also turned down a related appeal by the heirs to a
non-union worker who had opposed the way his dues were spent.
   The National Right to Work Legal Defense and Education
Foundation of Springfield, Va., said it was unfairly maligned in a
January ruling by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court in that decision ruled against nine non-union
employees of Illinois state and local agencies.
   The workers had sued the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees (AFSME), accusing the union of using
non-members' dues to promote political and ideological causes.
   The 7th Circuit court upheld a federal judge's decision that
noted the union had agreed to refund any improper overcharges.
   What sparked the main appeal acted on today were references by
the 7th Circuit court to the role of the National Right to Work
Foundation.
   For example, the appeals court said the foundation was ``trying
to hamstring the union.''
   The foundation said it was not involved in the Illinois workers'
suit and sought vindication from the Supreme Court.
   AFSME, in urging the justices to reject the appeal, said a
foundation lawyer did represent the Illinois workers and that the
appeals court references to the group were proper.
   In the companion appeal, heirs to the late Jack Gilpin, one of
the non-union workers, asked the high court to throw out the 7th
Circuit court ruling.
   The cases are National right to Work Foundation vs. AFSME,
89-287, and Gilpin vs. AFSCME, 89-292.
</TEXT>
