<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 10-16 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0523,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb At Newspaper Kills Two Workers, Wounds Seven Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with details. Pick up 6th pvs,
`On Sunday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded early today near the
offices of a newspaper in the city of Bucaramanga, killing two of
the paper's workers and injuring at least seven others, police said.
   The director of the Vanguardia Liberal newspaper said in a live
radio broadcast that drug traffickers were responsible for the
bomb, which exploded in a car parked near the offices and was
packed with up to 130 pounds of dynamite.
   The newspaper is the main daily in Bucaramanga, 175 miles north
of Bogota.
   ``Although I can't identify the perpetrators, I can say that
basically they are the same group of drug traffickers that have
carried out these types of attacks in the past,'' Alejandro Galvis
Ramirez said on the national radio chain Caracol.
   The blast killed a night watchman and a maintenance worker at
the paper's downtown offices, a Bucaramanga police spokesman said
in a telephone interview.
   It injured another seven people and caused extensive damage, the
spokesman said. He added that 15 houses nearby were affected, and
three of them were almost completely destroyed.
   Police initially estimated the damage caused by the explosion at
$1.2 million. ``The area is a mess,'' the spokesman said.
   The attack is the second major bombing of a Colombian newspaper
since the government began a crackdown on drug traffickers Aug. 19.
   On Sept. 2, the main offices of Bogota's El Espectador newspaper
were targeted in a car bomb attack that injured 83 people.
Journalists at the paper blamed the attack on drug lords angered by
the paper's hard line on traffickers.
   Galvis Ramirez said he did not know if the Vanguradia would be
able to continue publishing in the city of 400,000 people.
   ``We don't yet know if the machines are still functioning or
even if we have electricity,'' he said.
   Another police officer, Col. Jorge Ernesto Ferrero, said on the
radio that some of the injured were workers at the paper while
others were passing by when the bomb, placed in a Renault, exploded.
   He said police had made no arrests in connection with the blast.
   On Sunday, the visiting director of the U.S. Information Agency
said international publishers pledged $1 million in donations to
the Bogota newspaper El Espectador, which also has been battered by
a terrorist campaign blamed on traffickers.
   Also Sunday, authorities captured a man convicted of drug
trafficking charges in New York and seized an alleged accountant
for one of Colombia's powerful drug lords, news reports said.
   Police arrested Victor Eduardo Mera Mosquera, 36, at his
apartment Friday in the southern city of Cali, according to reports
in the daily El Tiempo and in El Espectador.
   He was arrested in New York in February 1984 and charged with
taking part in a drug ring operating in New York, Florida, Texas,
California and Arizona, El Tiempo reported.
   El Espectador said Mera Mosquera was freed from a Manhattan jail
because of a ``bureaucratic error'' but was later convicted in
absentia. It did not elaborate.
   The paper reported that he was arrested again in Bogota in 1986
but was released months later by a judge who ruled authorities had
not completed the paperwork for his extradition to the United
States in the time alloted by the law.
   Spokesmen for the national and local police in Cali said they
could not confirm Mera Mosquera's arrest or details about him. The
U.S. Embassy in Bogota says it cannot comment on specific
extradition cases.
   In a raid Saturday on a Bogota apartment, police captured Tulia
Consuelo Rincon Barrera, 35, whom they said was an accountant for
Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, one of the three leaders of the
Medellin cocaine cartel, El Espectador reported.
   The woman maintains she never met the Medellin cartel leader and
only filled out income tax forms for one of his reputed underlings,
Leonardo Vargas Vargas, who was arrested last week, El Espectador
said.
   President Virgilio Barco announced his war on drugs after the
assassination Aug. 18 of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, the leading
presidential candidate and an anti-drug crusader. Barco said he
would seize the property of drug traffickers and extradite reputed
narcotics figures to the United States.
</TEXT>
