<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Estate     10-16 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Estate,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Backs Out of Deciding IRS Issue on Inheritance Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today backed out of deciding
whether the Internal Revenue Service, when assessing inheritance
taxes, may challenge deductions state courts have allowed for legal
fees and executor's commission.
   The justices agreed last February to decide the issue in an
appeal by a New York lawyer who acted as executor and attorney for
a $450,000 estate.
   In a brief announcement today, the court said without further
explanation that the appeal had been ``improvidently granted.''
   The court voted, 8-1, to dismiss the case. Justice Byron R.
White dissented.
   The justices' action has the effect of permitting an IRS
subpoena of the files of James M. White, a Rochester attorney who
handled the will of Helen P. Smith after she died in November 1982.
   A state judge who presided over enforcement of the will, a
procedure known as probate, ruled in 1984 that White should be paid
$16,800 for his legal services and $17,548 as an executor's
commission.
   White deducted those amounts when calculating the federal tax
owed by the estate.
   The IRS said White must provide records to justify the
deductions. The lawyer refused to comply, contending the amount of
time he spent handling the settling of the will and the hourly
rates he charged did not bear on whether the fees were reasonable
under New York law.
   A federal judge ruled that the IRS failed to show its
investigation of the case is reasonable. The judge said the IRS did
not demonstrate any reason to suspect ``fraud, overreaching or
excessiveness'' by White to justify inspecting his records.
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the federal
judge's decision and said White must provide the documents even
though there is no claim he acted improperly.
   The IRS has the authority to require the information in its
investigation of the tax liability of the Smith estate, the appeals
court said.
   In appealing to the Supreme Court, White said, ``No federal
interest is served by permitting the Internal Revenue Service or
the federal court to redetermine the reasonableness of an
attorney's fee that has already been considered and approved by a
state probate court.''
   The case is White vs. U.S., 88-928.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1110EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion     10-16 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Connecticut Governor Could Escape Hit List, NARAL Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a national abortion rights group
said today it will consider removing Connecticut Gov. William A.
O'Neill from a list of top political targets for defeat next year
if he will agree not to push his anti-abortion views.
   Kate Michelman, head of the National Abortion Rights Action
League, said she was contacted by O'Neill's staff over the weekend
and was trying to arrange a telephone conversation with the
governor.
   His selection to the group's ``NARAL Nine'' drew expressions of
surprise and regret from some Connecticut pro-choice leaders when
it was announced Saturday.
   ``If I get some assurance from him that he will in fact
represent the views of his constitutents and not introduce
legislation and not sign legislation (restricting access to
abortions), then we may remove him from the list,'' Michelman said.
``I have to talk to the governor.''
   Others on the target list include North Carolina Sen. Jesse
Helms and Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, both Republicans, as well as
state legislators and likely candidates for governorships or the
Senate in 1990. O'Neill was one of only two Democrats on the list.
   Michelman said officials of the group's Connecticut affiliate
asked NARAL to reconsider O'Neill's inclusion on the list of
priority targets. O'Neill may seek re-election next year.
   O`Neill spokesman John Sandberg called the listing ``bizarre''
and said the Connecticut governor has not supported failed attempts
in the state's legislature to cut off Medicaid funding for
abortions.
   Lynn Blackwell, president of the board of the Connecticut NARAL
group, said O'Neill ``is not an active anti-choice politician. He's
never used his power, his considerable power, to advance his
personal opinion on abortion.''
   Michelman acknowledged that O'Neill has not used his influence
as governor to oppose abortion rights. But, she said, ``He is an
anti-choice governor _ there's no question.''
   Michelman and abortion-rights supporters in Congress, meanwhile,
voiced opposition to any attempts to compromise with opponents in
an attempt to head off a possible presidential veto of legislation
that would expand federal Medicaid funding for abortions for poor
women who are victims of rape or incest.
   ``We're not interested in any compromise,'' said Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., a supporter of abortion rights.
   President Bush said Friday he was looking for ``flexibility''
and awaiting the outcome of negotiations in Congress on the
legislation, which passed the House last week and goes back to the
Senate, where it has already been passed, for agreement on another
provision.
   Packwood said Bush appeared to be seeking the addition of
language allowing the Medicaid abortions only when the rape or
incest was reported within 48 hours of the occurrence. As passed by
th House the bill requires the event be reported ``promptly.''
   Michelman commented as abortion-rights activists from around the
country presented members of Congress with what they said were
petitions bearing 1 million signatures stating opposition to ``any
attempt to interfere with the fundamental right of a woman to make
her own decision about abortion.''
   The activists gave the petitions to Packwood and Rep. Don
Edwards, D-Calif., then spread out around Capitol Hill to take
their message to other congressmen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Protests     10-16 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Protests,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0504 to change keyword, which duplicated that of
a0458.</HEAD>
<HEAD>California Initiative Proposed; Rally in New Jersey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands demonstrated their support of abortion rights in New
Jersey and in California, where the state attorney general
announced he would sponsor a ballot initiative to protect a woman's
right to have an abortion.
   In Trenton, N.J., several thousand pro-choice demonstrators
chanted, waved banners and marched on the Statehouse on Sunday to
urge lawmakers not to change laws that allow abortion.
   The battle over abortion has heated up nationwide since the U.S.
Supreme Court issued a ruling in July broadening states' rights to
restrict abortion, and the issue figures in the New Jersey
governor's race.
   Eleanor Smeal, former president of the National Organization for
Women, urged the demonstrators in Trenton to use the election to
send a message to the rest of the country.
   ``It's a political fight, it's a medical fight and it's a public
health fight,'' Ms. Smeal said.
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate James Florio opposes any new
restrictions on abortion. James Courter, the GOP candidate, has a
long anti-abortion voting record, but in recent weeks has said he
wouldn't impose his personal views on New Jersey women.
   State police estimated the crowd at 6,500; organizers claimed
10,000.
   In San Francisco, a crowd estimated by police at 30,000 marched
down Market Street on Sunday, carrying signs and chanting their
support for abortion rights.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp, sporting a
``Choice'' button, told the crowd he would sponsor a ballot
initiative to protect abortion rights.
   As in New Jersey, the issue is becoming a matter of
gubernatorial politics.
   The ballot measure proposed by Van de Kamp, one of three
Democratic hopefuls in the 1990 governor's race. If the measure
attracts enough signatures it will appear on the ballot in November
1990.
   The measure is designed to negate a provision of a crime
initiative that will appear on the ballot in June that is sponsored
by Sen. Pete Wilson, the expected Republican candidate for
governor, and local prosecutors.
   The Wilson-backed measure would repeal a wide range of state
constitutional rights in criminal cases, including the right to
privacy.
   Van de Kamp, backed by several constitutional scholars and major
abortion-rights groups, contends the initiative could lead to
criminal prosecution for some abortions. That is because abortion
rights in California are based on the state constitutional right of
privacy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
