<DOCNO> AP891016-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JamieFiske     10-16 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamie Fiske,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamie Fiske Readmitted to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old Massachusetts girl whose liver
transplant in 1982 helped shape the nation's organ transplant
policy remained hospitalized today after suffering a mysterious
bout of internal bleeding.
   Jamie Fiske was in stable condition at University of Minnesota
Hospital, officials said. It was the same hospital where she
received a liver transplant as an infant after he father, Charles
Fiske, made a dramatic televised appeal for her life.
   Jamie, of Bridgewater, Mass., left the hospital with her parents
Saturday after removal of her enlarged spleen on Oct. 9. She was to
stay one night at a hotel before returning home, but was readmitted
to the hospital at 5 a.m. Sunday with internal bleeding, said
hospital spokeswoman Mary Stanik.
   The bleeding had stopped today, but doctors did not know where
the bleeding came from and planned to conduct more tests, Stanik
said. She didn't know how long the child would be hospitalized.
   Jamie was admitted to the hospital Oct. 6 after suffering three
bouts of internal bleeding in a month. Her spleen, which doctors
said was seven or eight times the normal size for a child her age,
was removed and doctors believed that would end the bleeding.
   Exploratory surgery found no problems with Jamie's liver, said
her physician, Dr. John Najarian.
   When she received a liver as an infant, Jamie's case raised
questions about the procedures for determining who should receive
organ transplants and the propriety of awarding organs on the basis
of publicity campaigns. Partly as a result, the National Transplant
Act was passed to create a national computer system used to match
donors to recipients.
   Jamie was born Nov. 26, 1981, with biliary atresia, a condition
in which the liver's bile ducts are blocked. Months later, her
parents learned that only a liver transplant could save her life.
   She received a liver in 1982 a few days after Charles Fiske made
his appeal for a donor during a convention at the American Academy
of Pediatricians. Television networks showed him singing a line
from an old song, ``please don't take my sunshine away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
