<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0507 10-16 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Injured in Jerusalem Riot; Palestinian Youth Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Palestinian youth dying, Picks
up 5th graf, `Israel radio ...'; INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf, `The 35-acre
...' with details on death; SUBS last graf to UPDATE death toll.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas and rubber bullets today
to disperse stone-throwing students outside a high school in Arab
east Jerusalem, and 15 students and five policemen were injured,
witnesses and officials said.
   Also today, an 8-year-old Palestinian boy died three days after
Israeli soldiers shot him during a demonstration in the occupied
Gaza Strip.
   Forty Palestinians were detained in the east Jerusalem
disturbance, which took place as thousands of religious Jews
visited Jerusalem for the eight-day Sukkot festival, police
spokesman Uzi Sandori said.
   The unrest began when students from the Rashadiyeh High School
blocked roads with rocks and showered police with stones, witnesses
said. Paramilitary border police fired tear gas and rubber bullets
to disperse the crowd, they said.
   Sandori said five policemen were slightly injured from stones.
Officials at Mukassed Hospital in east Jerusalem said about 15
students were treated for tear-gas inhalation and bruises from
rubber bullets.
   Israel radio said police were investigating whether the riot was
sparked by the plans of militant Jews to lay a three-ton
cornerstone inside Jerusalem's Old City for what they hope will be
a rebuilt Jewish temple.
   The militants, who call themselves the Temple Mount Faithful,
want to rebuild the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
   But police prevented them from taking the cornerstone off a
truck and barred about 100 of the militants from going up to the
Temple Mount.
   The 35-acre Temple Mount site includes the spot where Moslems
believe the Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven. The platform's two
mosques, the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa, are the holiest Islamic
places of worship after Mecca and Medina in Saudi Arabia.
   The Gaza boy, who died in Tel Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv,
was identified by the army as Qassem Abdallah Abu Lubda.
   He was shot Friday in the Khan Yunis refugee camp in Gaza when
soldiers opened fire on Palestinian stone-throwers, the army said.
The army said it was ``checking the circumstances of his injury.''
   Also today, Israeli tax collectors backed by soldiers raided at
least seven shops on the main square of Nablus, the largest town in
the occupied West Bank with 120,000 residents.
   An Arab reporter said the agents confiscated goods from the
stores and sealed some with red wax to prevent them from reopening
until taxes are paid. The shops specialize in shoes, clothes,
jewelry, photographs, and luggage.
   Israeli authorities have stepped up tax raids in recent weeks to
try to break a tax boycott called by the underground leaders of the
uprising.
   Boycotts and strikes have been the main economic weapons of the
uprising.
   Abu Lubda's death raised to 596 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israelis since the uprising began in December 1987. At
least 130 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, most on
suspicion of collaborating with Israel. Forty Israelis have died in
the violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FetalTissue     10-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Tissue,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ban on Use of Fetal Tissue for Research Reportedly Extended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration plans to extend a
19-month-old ban on federal funding for research using fetal
tissue, The New York Times reported today.
   James Mason, assistant secretary for health in the Department of
Health and Human Services, has recommended to HHS Secretary Louis
Sullivan that the ban be continued over the objections of two
federal panels, the newspaper said.
   Sullivan was expected to act within a week, said the Times,
which cited no sources for its information.
   Spokesmen for Sullivan and Mason would say only today that issue
was under review in the department.
   Abortion opponents have strongly opposed using fetal tissue for
medical research, though scientists say transplanting fetal tissue
into adults may be effective in treating diabetes and Parkinson's
disease.
   HHS imposed the ban in March 1988 while the department reviewed
the issue. In December, two panels at the National Institutes of
Health studied the question and voted to recommend that the ban be
lifted.
   The Times quoted Robert Windom, assistant secretary for health
in the Reagan administration, as saying that he had been prepared
to approve fetal tissue experiments in January, but was instructed
by then-HHS Secretary Otis Bowen to leave the decision to the Bush
administration.
</TEXT>
