<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nobel Laureate Recovering, Thanks World for Prayers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANTOSH BASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa attended Mass on ck last month.
   The 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun was released from the
Woodlands Nursing Home on Saturday.
   Mother Teresa's message, written in her distinctive hand, read:
   ``Kindly thank the people of the whole world and the Woodlands
people for all their prayers and tender love and care I have
received. God bless you. M. Teresa MC.''
   ``MC'' stands for the Missionaries of Charity, the order of
Roman Catholic nuns founded by the Yugoslav-born nun in 1950.
   ``Mother Teresa is much better today and progressing quite
steadily. She is quite radiant,'' said Sister Dorothy, who is
taking care of the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize winner.
   Sister Dorothy delivered Mother Teresa's note to a reporter who
had gone to the Missionaries of Charity home to inquire about her
recovery.
   Mother Teresa was staying with her fellow nuns, instead of the
order's headquarters, out of concern that too many visitors might
impede her recovery.
   Doctors have told Mother Teresa to restrict take it easy for the
next 10 days.
   ``She is doing some work and she's reading _ mostly prayer
books, but mostly she's in prayer,'' the nun added. ``Mother Teresa
feels that she has been healed because of the power of prayer.''
   Mother Teresa is eating her normal diet of porridge, bread and
jam in the morning and vegetable soup, boiled fish and fruit in the
afternoon.
   When Mother Teresa was released from the nursing home, her chief
physician, Ashim Bardhan, said she was still very weak and would
need to rest ``for quite some time.''
   Mother Teresa, whose order runs a home for the destitute and
dying in Calcutta and operates missions on six continents, was
hospitalized Sept. 5. She suffered a heart attack three days later
and developed recurring chest pains and a high fever that was
aggravated by infection.
</TEXT>
