<FIRST>r i AM-Latin-Noriega     10-16 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Latin-Noriega,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin American Leaders Isolating Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ICA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civilian government now prevails in Latin
America, and Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega of Panama is being
isolated to a degree not seen since the cases three decades ago of
Gen. Rafael Trujillo and Fidel Castro.
   What role, if any, the rejection will play in bringing Noriega
down is a question. While indicating solid support for President
Bush's efforts to oust Noriega, the condemnation clearly does not
include support for direct U.S. intervention.
   On Friday in Washington, Bush said he believes his feelings
about Noriega, who commands the Panamanian military and controls
the government, ``are shared by my colleagues south of the border.''
   Seven Latin American leaders meeting last week in this desert
city 185 miles southeast of Lima condemned ``the continued lack of
democracy, and human rights violations,'' in Panama.
   They continued the ``indefinite suspension'' of the Noriega
regime from the Group of Eight, an informal group of which Panama
was a founding member three years ago.
   At the same time, the presidents of Argentina, Brazil, Colombia,
Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela said the 1977 treaties that
turn the Panama Canal over to Panama at the end of 1999 should be
respected fully.
   Heat started building on Noriega after U.S. officials accused
him of trafficking in drugs. In February 1988, he was indicted in
Florida on federal narcotics charges.
   At the recent meeting of the Inter American Press Association in
Monterrey, Mexico, Roberto Eisenmann, editor of an opposition
newspaper in Panama, said Noriega had created ``the first
narco-military regime in the world.''
   Noriega has responded to pressure with increasingly harsh
treatment of opponents.
   He is seen in the region as a throwback to the old-style
military dictator. Noriega summed up his view of power recently as
``blows for the weak, bullets for enemies, money for friends.''
   President Alan Garcia of Peru, who extended the red carpet two
years ago when Noriega visited Lima, now is among the general's
severest critics.
   Garcia told the opening summit session he was using the occasion
``to express publicly the Peruvian people's and the Peruvian
government's repudiation and condemnation of the military
dictatorship'' in Panama.
   President Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela, who once had warm
relations with Noriega, called his regime ``a masked dictatorship''
and Guillermo Larcos Cox, Peru's foreign minister, declared: ``We
cannot allow a country like Panama that scoffs at and ridicules the
democratic system to continue with us.''
   In May, after annulling elections outside observers said were
swept by the opposition, Noriega chose economist Francisco
Rodriguez to be president.
   Peru and Venezuela immediately recalled their ambassadors, and
virtually all other Latin American countries followed suit. Even
President Augusto Pinochet of Chile, a general often criticized for
a poor human rights record, quietly ordered his envoy back to
Santiago.
   Now Noriega finds himself isolated from other Latin American
nations, an example of rejection not seen in more than a generation.
   In the late 1950s and early 1960s, Trujillo suffered similar
repudiation, but only after Venezuela presented evidence of the
Dominican Republic dictator's involvement in an attempt to
assassinate the Venezuelan president, Romulo Betancourt.
   Venezuela again sought regional solidarity in the early 1960s
when Castro's Cuba trained and financed leftist guerrillas fighting
the Venezuelan government.
   Cuba was expelled from the Organization of American States and
all Latin American countries but Mexico broke relations. Most
governments have restored ties since, however, and the ICA summit
urged the renewal of Cuba's OAS membership.
   Efforts to isolate Castro were hampered by enthusiastic support
for him among leftist groups throughout Latin America, but no
pro-Noriega voices are being heard.
   Whether Latin American rejection will have an effect on Noriega
remains to be seen; it appeared to have little on Trujillo or
Castro. Trujillo resisted the pressure until his assassination in
1963 and Castro remains in power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
