<FIRST>u a PM-UAL 1stLd-Writethru a0519 10-16 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Restructuring Takeover Plan For UAL Corp.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with stock down sharply; add comment
from spokesman, and to RECAST lead to fix grammar. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
`Published reports...'. A version also moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot-management group trying to take over
the parent of United Airlines will have to consider wooing those
who oppose the deal, bringing in other backers or making an offer
with more securities, analysts said.
   The group's $6.75 billion cash offer for UAL Corp. collapsed
last week when banks, largely Japanese, refused to finance the
deal. That helped trigger the steepest one-day decline in the stock
market since the Oct. 19, 1987 crash.
   UAL stock plunged $60 a share to $219.34 by midday today on the
New York Stock Exchange. Trading in the company's shares was halted
Friday and many traders trying to unload the stock were forced to
postpone their sales until today.
   All parties to the bid _ the Air Line Pilots Association,
United's managers and British Airways PLC _ spent the weekend
restructuring the offer, said pilots union spokesman Hank Krakowski.
   ``We are confident we can restructure the transaction and can
move ahead,'' he said Sunday. ``All I can say is we're not
committing to any timetable, but we intend to move as rapidly as we
can.''
   United spokesman Joe Hopkins said today that the company was not
in a position to comment on a revised offer. A British Airways
statement from London reiterated the company's commitment to
reviewing any revised bid and completing the deal.
   Published reports today said a new bid might be disclosed early
this week. The Chicago Tribune quoted unidentified sources as
saying the original all-cash offer might be a package of cash and
scurities with a nominal value of $300 a share _ the same per-share
value as the initial bid.
   One speculator, whom the newspaper did not identify, said the
revised offer might contain $250 to $270 a share in cash, with the
remainder in securities.
   Bankers who turned down the UAL proposal said in interviews with
the Wall Street Journal that the market might have misinterpreted
the significance of the collapsed deal. They said banks didn't
suddenly become unwilling to finance takeovers, they just didn't
like this particular UAL buyout plan, which called for unattractive
fees and interest rates to banks.
   Industry analyst Louis Marckesano said the pilot-management
group should move quickly with a restructured plan to calm the
market, which tumbled on Friday with a 190-point drop on the Dow
Jones industrial average.
   ``I don't think it has to be done (today), but there has to be
some indication they're working on a revised bid,'' said
Marckesano, of the Philadelphia brokerage Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc.
   ``At this stage, everybody's waiting'' to see what the revised
bid will look like, said Marckesano. ``It'll be two weeks before we
know what the ultimate outcome will be and how it's going to be
structured.''
   He suggested the buyout group try to enlist the backing of the
Machinists union, which had vehemently opposed the takeover bid, to
make the offer more attractive.
   ``Or perhaps bring in outside financing ... somebody like a
friend of the group,'' Marckesano said. ``Perhaps (Marvin) Davis
restating his backup bid at $300 a share could contribute to the
deal in some form or another.''
   But Robert Joedicke, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., said he doubted Davis _ a California billionaire whose bid
was rejected by the UAL board _ could find financing for his offer
since the pilot-management group could not.
   ``I doubt very much if he would be anxious at this point'' to
press a bid, Joedicke said, predicting the restructuring of the
pilots-management offer would involve a combination of cash and
securities.
   A spokesman for Davis said Friday that Davis had no statement on
whether he would pursue his offer.
</TEXT>
