<FIRST>r a PM-Bakker'sMinistry     10-16 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker's Ministry,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Televangelist Returns To Pulpit In Orlando</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Jim Bakker says he will continue
his television ministry, despite his conviction on fraud charges,
as soon as he and his wife, Tammy Faye, can pay some bills.
   ``We're going back on television, whether it's me or Tammy or
Tammy and me together,'' Bakker said Sunday upon return to his New
Covenant Church in Orlando.
   Earlier this month, Bakker was convicted of defrauding
supporters of $3.7 million in connection with his former PTL or
Praise the Lord ministry and its Heritage USA Christian retreat at
Fort Mill, S.C.
   Sentencing is scheduled for Oct. 24. Bakker faces a maximum
120-year prison sentence and fines totaling $5 million.
   Bakker took to the pulpit at the storefront church from which he
and his wife have been broadcasting their new ``Jim and Tammy
Show'' intermittently since moving to Orlando in May.
   No shows have been broadcast since his conviction at Charlotte,
N.C. His lawyers had said after the trial that the TV ministry was
suspended indefinitely.
   Bakker refused to meet with reporters and the media was barred
from Sunday's service, but from outside Bakker could be heard
speaking freely about his trial and his faith to a crowd of 50 to
100 people.
   He denied defrauding so-called partners in Heritage USA who were
told they could have three nights free lodging a year in exchange
for large donations, and said that if he is sentenced to prison he
will go to jail an innocent man.
   Bakker, 49, resigned from PTL in 1987 amid a sex scandal
involving former church secretary Jessica Hahn.
   Mrs. Bakker told the crowd her faith is strong.
   ``I'm counting on God's peace,'' she said. ``I don't know what
the next few weeks might bring. My emotions go up and down like a
roller coaster.''
   After the service, Bakker ducked out a back door trying to avoid
reporters and photographers. A ministry spokesman said he had made
an agreement with his laywers not to talk to reporters.
