<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     10-16 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Increased at U.S. Facilities, National Police on Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were placed on heightened alert
for anti-American protests Monday and security was bolstered at
U.S. facilities after an attack last week on the U.S. ambassador's
residence.
   National Police Headquarters said they feared more anti-American
protests and attacks on U.S. facilities while President Roh Tae-woo
is in the United States this week for talks with President Bush.
   Thousands of radical students in seven cities took part in
anti-U.S. protests Friday and Saturday, burning American flags and
demanding Roh call off his Oct. 15-20 visit.
   Additional police have been assigned to the U.S. Embassy and
other American facilities, but officials declined to give details.
Riot police also were told to enter college campuses to arrest
radical student leaders or stop the burning of U.S. flags, police
said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said security talks between Korean and
U.S. officials were under way to prevent a recurrence of Friday's
violent attack by six radical students at the U.S. ambassador's
residence.
   The students climbed over a stone wall, hurled homemade bombs at
guards and rampaged through the residence of U.S. Ambassador Donald
Gregg with iron bars, smashing artwork and windows. Gregg and his
wife escaped unharmed.
   The country's main dissident alliance, Chominyon, defended the
radical attack and demanded Gregg's recall to Washington, saying he
supported military rule when he was CIA station chief in Seoul in
the 1970s.
   The alliance also demanded the withdrawal of 43,000 U.S. stroops
based in South Korea and an end to U.S. demands for greater access
to South Korean markets. The radicals, a small but powerful
minority, have little support because of their violent tactics.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said Monday that U.S. officials were
conferring with Korean police to determine how security around U.S.
facilities could be upgraded to prevent future attacks.
   ``We're looking for ways to cooperate better with the Korean
police, and for the Koreans to cooperate better with us,'' said a
spokesman, requesting anonymity. The embassy has about a dozen
Marine guards, and the ambassador's residence is protected by a
private security agency.
   South Korea provides protection to diplomatic personnel and
assigns patrols to the perimeters of all U.S. facilities, including
the headquarters of the 8th U.S. Army in Seoul.
   National Police Headquarters, embarrassed over the breach in
security, announced it fired the police station chief for failing
to prevent the attack on the U.S. residence. It also said four
police officers were held for disciplinary action and a warning was
issued to the Seoul police director.
</TEXT>
