<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bananas     10-16 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bananas,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banana Strike Ends in Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 banana workers
returned to work Monday after a 12-day strike, President Jose
Azcona Hoyo said.
   U.S.-based Castle and Cooke agreed to give raises to 70 workers
whose jobs at the El Huguerito plantation, 185 miles north of
Tegucigalpa, were eliminated when a packing plant was sold, Azcona
Hoyo said. The amount of the raise is yet to be negotiated.
   The dispute began Sept. 18 when the company sold the plant to
independent packers and transferred the workers without giving them
raises. Under Honduran law, workers can only be transferred with
their consent and if there are economic benefits.
   The agreement was reached in four days of talks mediated by
Azcona Hoyo, who said Honduras lost an estimated $5.3 million.
   Honduras exports 50 million 100-pound crates of bananas a year
to the United States and Europe.
   Azcona Hoyo had threatened to declare a state of emergency after
the Workers Confederation and the National Farmworkers
Organization, which have 500,000 members, said they would strike.
   The San Francisco-based Castle and Cooke sells about 60 percent
of the country's banana exports. U.S.-based United Brands has the
other 40 percent.
</TEXT>
