<FIRST>u a PM-Wedtech-Wallach 1stLd-Writethru a0582 10-16 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Wallach, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0582,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meese Associate Sentenced To Six Years In Wedtech Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Wallach fine, and with sentences
for co-defendants. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `In a...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E. Robert Wallach, a close associate of former
Attorney General Edwin Meese III, was sentenced today to six years
in prison and fined $250,000 for his racketeering conviction in the
Wedtech Corp. scandal.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen said Wallach used his influence
to gain access ``to the back steps of the White House'' and made
almost half a million dollars as a result.
   Wallach, 55, a prominent personal injury lawyer from San
Francisco, was found to have illegally received $425,000 from the
now-defunct South Bronx defense contractor to influence Meese and
other government officials as part of Wedtech's efforts to gain
government business.
   He was convicted Aug. 8 by a jury in Manhattan federal court of
racketeering, fraud and conspiracy to defraud the U.S. government.
   His co-defendants _ R. Kent London and W. Franklyn Chinn _ were
convicted at the same trial of racketeering, racketeering
conspiracy and fraud charges stemming from payments they received
from Wedtech.
   Chinn, 47, of San Francisco, Meese's former financial adviser,
was sentenced to three years in prison and fined $100,000. London,
46, of Honolulu, a Chinn business associate, was sentenced to five
years in prison and fined $250,000.
   In a statement ot the judge before sentencing, Wallach said
there was a maxim that went, ``Too much success can bring failure.''
   ``I am the epitome of that and I am paying for it,'' he said.
   The judge denied defense motions to throw out the verdict based
on the dismissal of a juror who called in sick, and based on
defense arguments that the law Wallach was convicted of breaking
was unconstitutionally vague.
   Wallach, who was hired by Wedtech as a consultant, was found to
have defrauded the company and its shareholders of a $125,000
payment in 1983, which he billed as work for the company's public
stock offering but was actually for his efforts to influence Meese
and others to secure an Army contract for Wedtech.
   He also was convicted of illegally receiving $300,000 from
Wedtech officials, purportedly for helping the company acquire
shipyards and a Michigan tug-barge system.
   The jury found the money was actually a payment in anticipation
of Wallach's employment at the Justice Department where he could
influence Meese and other officials. Wallach was hired by the
Justice Department.
   The $300,000 payment also was the basis for the conspiracy to
defraud the government charge.
   Wedtech, once a small machine shop, grew into a $100 million
government contractor through a Small Business Administration
program that set aside contracts without competitive bidding for
minority-controlled companies.
   Evidence at trials has shown that Wedtech continued to receive
the no-bid contracts through a series of bribe schemes.
   Wallach testified at the trial that he has been a close friend
of Meese since they attended law school together. He represented
Meese during his confirmation hearings for the attorney general
post and at a special prosecutor's investigation in 1984.
   Meese was never charged in the Wedtech scandal, although his
ethics were questioned by a special prosecutor in Washington who
said Messe could have been hit with tax and conflict of interest
charges.
   The former attorney general testified for Wallach and said
Wallach had never asked him to do anything improper for Wedtech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
