<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-MacIntire     10-16 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-MacIntire,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skyway Bridge Survivor Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wesley C. MacIntire, the sole survivor of
the 1980 Sunshine Skyway Bridge disaster, has died of bone cancer.
He was 65.
   He died Saturday.
   Thirty-five motorists were pitched to their deaths in Tampa Bay
when a freighter rammed the bridge, toppling a 1,400-foot section
of steel-and-concrete road.
   The Gulfport resident also was driving across the bridge, on his
way to work the morning of May 9, 1980, when the Summit Venture
smashed into the southbound span.
   MacIntire's pickup truck rode the bridge down. It bounced off
the bow of the ship, breaking his 150-foot fall, then dropped
backward into the water. He was quickly pulled from the wreckage by
the ship's crew.
   That tragedy haunted MacIntire, a retired truck driver,
relatives said Sunday.
   ``He talked about it a lot,'' said his daughter, Donna L.
Robbins, of Springfield, Mass. ``It was hard for him to talk about,
though. He would get hurt over some of the reactions people would
give him, because he was a sensitive person.''
   ``Because his injuries were not so severe, because he didn't
suffer that much, it was like, `Here you are, what are you
complaining about?' But he suffered for the people who died,''
Robbins said.
   Besides his widow, Elizabeth, and daughter, MacIntire is
survived by a son, a brother, and four grandchildren. Services will
be Tuesday in Gulfport.
</TEXT>
