<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASELTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's taking so long to finalize Kim
Basinger's purchase of this northeast Georgia town that the mayor
is reassuring residents the $20 million deal is still on.
   ``Everything's moving along fine,'' said Mayor Henry Braselton.
``There are still bank approvals which have to be completed, still
surveying and title work which isn't yet done.''
   Real estate agent Charles Morris, who is handling the
transaction, said surveying includes a search for industrial waste
on the 1,800 acres the actress is buying.
   Miss Basinger, featured in the movies ``Batman,'' ``My
Stepmother is an Alien'' and ``9{ Weeks,'' will own a bank, an
industrial park, 50 buildings and two miles of interstate highway
frontage, Braselton said Saturday.
   The mayor belongs to the town's founding family, which agreed in
March to sell to Miss Basinger, a native of Athens, Ga. Braselton
predicted at the time that the deal would take six months to
complete.
   ``Actually, it's farther along than I thought,'' the mayor said.
``But I don't know when this will all be finished. I don't know if
it'll be before Christmas or not.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamie Lee Curtis said she'll probably get
blamed if the television series ``Anything But Love'' is canceled
by ABC.
   ``They will be saying I'm impossible, that I'm not a team
player,'' Miss Curtis said in an interview for the Oct. 21 issue of
TV Guide magazine.
   At the conclusion of the six-episode first season, the
co-executive producer and creator, Wendy Kout, along with
supervising producer and developer Dennis Koenig, quit after
protracted disagreements over scripts.
   But there's no indication the series, starring Miss Curtis and
Richard Lewis, will be canceled.
   ``The scripts weren't always funny enough and I felt from the
beginning that we had no idea what we were doing with my character
and Richard's,'' Miss Curtis said.
   Miss Curtis, whose movies include ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' said
she's preparing to take ``the rap'' if the show goes under.
   ``I've never been very popular, or wanted, by the powerful,''
said Miss Curtis. ``I had to make it slowly, and on my own.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release at 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria Shriver said she depends on her television
career to bolster her confidence and character.
   ``I often sit and wonder, if I had no profession, if everything
were stripped away, would it be OK?'' Shriver said in the November
Glamour magazine. ``I admire people who don't need work to define
themselves, who have great inner strength and a serenity about them
and just feel confident.''
   Shriver, a television anchor, commutes between Los Angeles, New
York and Washington. And when she finally makes it home to her $3
million spread in Pacific Palisades, Calif., her husband, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, is likely to be away making a movie.
   ``It's not like he's waiting for me at home,'' she said. ``But
if I was always waiting for him to come home, it would be worse.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther Bobby Seale may not go to
trial on charges of theft and passing bad checks to cover an
$11,000 debt from a barbecue cook-off.
   The debt stems from Seale's participation with a 12-member team
in the May 1988 National Rib Cook-Off to promote a book he wrote on
barbecue techniques.
   Seale, 52, was indicted in February on two counts of theft and
six charges of writing bad checks to cover the cost of pork ribs
and chicken sold to his team, and to pay the motel where the group
stayed.
   Seale has paid off most of the debt, his lawyers said. His trial
was to begin Monday in Common Pleas Court, but it was postponed
until Nov. 20 to allow him to pay off the rest.
   ``I'm sure I can reach total restitution by then,'' Seale said.
   Seale, who works as a community liaison in Temple University's
African-American Studies Department, said he underestimated the
cost of competing in the cook-off and overestimated sales.
   His lawyer, Terry Gilbert, said ``it's a simple restitution case
and not for a criminal court.''
   Roger Kramer, an assistant prosecutor handling Seale's case,
said there's a good chance charges will be revised or dropped.
</TEXT>
