<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Webster     10-16 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Webster,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Denies That Bush Unhappy With CIA Director</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has complete confidence in CIA
Director William H. Webster and is ``fully satisfied'' with him,
the White House said Monday, disputing a report that senior
administration officials were unhappy with his performance.
   ``Rumors of White House displeasure are totally false,'' said
Brent Scowcroft, Bush's national security adviser.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``Bill
Webster knows he's in good shape. He doesn't have any problems.
He's always been that way. There's never been any problem.''
   Asked how long Webster would have his job, Fitzwater said,
``Everybody comes in with the understanding we serve at the
president's pleasure.''
   In a front-page story, The Washington Post said that
unidentified ``senior officials'' in the Bush administration were
frustrated with Webster's low-profile performance and had begun
talk of replacing him with a more active player.
   The Post quoted White House Chief of Staff John H. Sununu as
saying during a recent staff meeting that he had learned more about
the attempted coup from watching Cable News Network than from
Webster's Central Intelligence Agency. However, Fitzwater said that
was incorrect.
   He said Sununu's comment was made at the time of the crackdown
on pro-democracy forces in China _ not the coup attempt in Panama _
and that it ``did not refer to Director Webster.''
   Fitzwater said he talked with Bush extensively about the Post
story and the president ``thinks the newspaper report was
outrageous.''
   Fitzwater said Bush had not actually used the word
``outrageous,'' saying that was ``my characterization of his
overall comments, which were somewhat more extensive. I'm not going
to give you any quotes.''
   Even before Fitzwater denied the story at his regular news
briefing, Scowcroft took the unusual step of issuing a
strongly-worded written statement on his own.
   ``The president is fully satisfied with the performance of the
intelligence community, including during the Panama episode,''
Scowcroft said. ``The president strongly supports Director
Webster.''
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Roman Popadiuk said Scowcroft
was trying to quell speculation that Webster might be on his way
out.
   Fitzwater said Bush ``has complete confidence in Director
Webster and the leadership he's providing at CIA.''
   The White House has been criticized by members of Congress for
not having a more organized flow of information during the Oct. 3
coup. Some members have criticized Bush for not doing more to
assist those seeking to overthrow Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Webster was the head of the FBI from 1978 to 1987, when
then-President Reagan moved him to the CIA post after the
Iran-Contra affair. Bush, a former CIA chief himself, decided to
retain him in that job.
</TEXT>
