<FIRST>r a PM-Earns-IBM 1stLd-Writethru a0541 10-16 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-IBM, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Earnings Fall 29.7 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `For the...'., to CORRECT revenue figures. A
version also moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. today
announced what it called a disappointing 29.7 percent decline in
its third-quarter earnings, an outcome that the company signaled
last month.
   The computer giant reiterated that its earnings were hurt by the
strength of the dollar, difficulties making transitions to new
products and an increase in leasing instead of buying by customers.
   On the positive side, IBM said revenue and shipments were up
from a year earlier.
   ``While these short-term financial results are disappointing,
demand for IBM products and services continues to be good
worldwide,'' said IBM Chairman John F. Akers in a statement. The
company was ``confident about the long-term prospects for our
business,'' Akers said.
   IBM said it earned $877 million in the three months ended Sept.
30, or $1.51 a share, down from $1.25 billion, or $2.10 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose 4.3 percent to $14.3 billion from $13.7
billion a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, IBM said its
earnings fell 8.4 percent to $3.17 billion, or $5.43 a share, from
$3.46 billion, or $5.83 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 6.5
percent to $42.2 billion from $39.7 billion a year earlier.
   IBM's stock dropped sharply last month after the company said it
expected third-quarter earnings to come in below the then-current
range of analysts' estimates.
   A strong dollar decreases the dollar value of profits earned
overseas in foreign currencies. A switch to leasing lowers the
short-run income from product placements. And a delay in
introduction of a new IBM disk drive for data storage in large
computers has hurt short-term results.
</TEXT>
