<DOCNO> AP891016-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Gramm-Rudman-Glance     10-16 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gramm-Rudman-Glance,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Gramm-Rudman Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law was
scheduled to trigger $16.1 billion in federal spending cuts on
Monday, following the failure of Congress and President Bush to
agree on a plan to cut the government's budget deficit.
   WHAT THE GRAMM-RUDMAN LAW IS: Passed in 1985 and amended two
years later, the law sets a series of declining targets for
projected deficits for each fiscal year, culminating in a balanced
budget in 1993. The cuts are triggered automatically if the targets
are exceeded.
   WHY THE CUTS ARE BEING MADE: Gramm-Rudman requires the cuts to
be made Oct. 16 if the projected deficit for fiscal 1990 _ which
started Oct. 1 _ surpasses $100 billion by more than $10 billion.
The White House's Office of Management and Budget projected the
deficit Monday to be $116.1 billion.
   HAS IT HAPPENED BEFORE? Twice. In 1986, $11.7 billon were
imposed in January and remained in effect through September, the
end of the fiscal year. In 1987, $23 billion in reductions were
imposed in October and were rolled back in December.
   HOW THIS YEAR'S CUTS ARE APPLIED: Half to defense, half to
domestic programs, or $8.05 billion to each. Because the cuts are
from different dollar totals, that calculates to 4.3 percent cuts
in defense and 5.3 percent in domestic programs.
   WHAT PROGRAMS ARE AFFECTED? All defense programs except for
money owed in contracts. Many domestic programs are exempted,
including Social Security, many other benefit programs, and
payments on the national debt. Certain other programs, such as
Medicare, can be sliced no more than 2 percent.
   EXAMPLES OF CUTS: Defense programs cut from $291.4 billion to
$283.3 billion; foreign aid from $16.3 billion to $15.8 billion;
science and space from $13.7 billion to $13.3 billion; agriculture
from $18.8 billion to $18.2 billion; transportation from $29.1
billion to $28.5 billion; education and social services from $38.2
billion to $37.5 billion; health from $56.6 billion to $56.2
billion.
   WHAT THE PUBLIC WILL FEEL: Very little initially, because of the
many exemptions and because agencies have the flexibility to shift
money around within programs. Many people believe most citizens
will not notice anything at all for several weeks.
   HOW LONG THE CUTS LAST: Technically, they took effect
temporarily Oct. 1. By law, they were invoked permanently Monday.
But Congress can pass legislation at any time rolling them back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
