<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1955EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Turkey     10-16 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Turkey,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Summons Dole Over Armenian Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush adminstration, trying to ward off a
diplomatic rift with Turkey, summoned Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., to the
White House Monday to discuss his proposed resolution memorializing
the ``Armenian genocide'' 75 years ago, a Dole aide said.
   The Turks are up in arms about the resolution because ``they
don't want to be compared with Hitler,'' said Mike McNamara, a
lobbyist for Turkey.
   ``It is the most offensive thing that Congress can do to
U.S.-Turkish relations,'' said Daryal Batibay, the deputy chief of
the Turkish Embassy. He said the measure, if passed, would damage
ties between the United States and Turkey, a close NATO ally that
plays host to American military bases.
   Against that backdrop, Brent Scowcroft, the president's national
security adviser, asked Dole, the Senate minority leader, to meet
with him on the issue, according to an aide to Dole who asked that
he not be quoted by name.
   Publicly, the administration has remained mute on the emotional
resolution, which has caught President Bush in a bind.
   During the 1988 presidential campaign, Bush said the United
States must acknowledge ``the attempted genocide of the Armenian
people in the last years of the Ottoman Empire. ...'' Some 1.5
million Armenians were killed in the early part of the century.
   But Marlin Fitzwater, Bush's spokesman, said the administration
had not taken any position on the Dole resolution. The Reagan
administration opposed such resolutions when they previously came
up _ and were defeated _ in the House.
   With the Senate Judiciary Committee scheduled to vote on the
resolution Tuesday, Turkey's lobbyists and Bush administration
officials, including Morton Abramowitz, the U.S. ambassador to
Turkey, worked frantically behind the scenes to convince senators
to drop their support for the Dole resolution.
   Several senators, including Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.; Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., and Robert Kasten, R-Wis., have already withdrawn
their sponsorship. Others, like Daniel Moynihan, D-N.Y., and Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., have added their names to the resolution.
   Dole needs 50 co-sponsors, half of them Republican, to have the
judiciary committee consider the measure, which would designate
April 24, 1990, as the ``National Day of Remembrance of the 75th
Anniversary of the Genocide of 1915-1923.''
   In a letter to other senators, Dole said the resolution was
prompted by his August visit to Armenia, a part of the Soviet
Union, to visit earthquake victims.
   ``And I can attest, from my own recent visit to Armenia, that
the Armenian people feel real friendship for the United States and
our people,'' he said.
   Both Dole and Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., said they didn't want
the resolution to be misunderstood as a slap at Turkey.
   ``I would also like to point out that the resolution does not
implicate the government of the Republic of Turkey in this terrible
event,'' Wilson said. Wilson is running for governor in California,
a state with a large population of Armenian descendants.
   Thurmond, the ranking Republican on the Judiciary Committee,
said he pulled his name as a co-sponsor ``since I've learned the
administration strongly opposes the resolution.'' He said he was
weighing whether to support the measure.
   Leahy said he withdrew his name because the Turkish ambassador
said the Turks will allow scholars to study the events from Ottoman
Empire archives. ``He thinks next year would be a better time for a
resolution,'' said Leahy's spokesman, Joe Jamele.
   Kasten's name had been put on the resolution by a staff member
without the senator's knowledge, said Kasten's spokesman, Jim Sims.
Kasten asked that it be taken off, Sims said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
