<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1956EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Psychiatry     10-16 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Psychiatry,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Moscow Regrets Abuse of Psychiatry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official said Monday that the
Kremlin regrets the past use of psychiatry as a political weapon.
   The comment by Peter Morozov, the secretary of international
relations for the state-sanctioned All-Union Society of Soviet
Psychiatrists, was a depature from the Kremlin view that has only
hinted at possible, isolated cases of abuse in the Soviet Union.
   ``It's clear that we regret our past, not only (political)
abuses but the whole system,'' Morozov said in an interview.
   His comments came on the eve of a vote by the World Psychiatric
Association on whether to readmit the Soviet group to its ranks.
   The Soviet group was forced to withdraw from the world body in
1983 under threat of expulsion because of allegations that
dissidents in the Soviet Union were being certified as insane and
interned in mental hospitals.
   ``We know of a lot of cases (of political abuse) that have been
reported on medical or legal grounds,'' Morozov said. ``Now, we
want (Western) psychiatrists to come and see suspicious cases and
visit psychiatric hospitals.''
   Earlier Monday, Soviet officials told a news conference that
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of reforming society
has led to changes in psychiatric practices in the Soviet Union.
   Yuri Reshetov, the head of the Soviet Foreign Ministry's human
rights department, said the government has not yet appointed the
members of an independent Soviet commission to monitor Soviet
psychiatry.
   A Soviet official told a U.S. congressional panel this month
that the eight-member commission had already been set up to prevent
the use of psychiatry ``for non-medical reasons'' and to ``ensure
maximum openness in specific cases of misuse of psychiatry.''
   Reshetov said the authorities were ``still looking'' for
professionals to become members of the commission, which he said is
not connected to any government department or organization.
   The Soviets say 4.5 million people are registered as mentally
ill in the Soviet Union, a decrease of 1 million in the past 1{
years.
   Fini Schulsinger, the secretary-general of the world body who
backs readmission for the Soviet group, said he believes delegates
will vote Tuesday to its unconditional readmission.
   But some delegates, speaking on condition of anonymity, expected
a fierce debate and said readmission might require the Soviets to
guarantee there will be no political abuse.
   The association also will vote Tuesday on whether to admit a
second Soviet group, the Independent Psychiatric Association. Both
Soviet groups can be admitted.
   Congressional sources predicted the independent group would be
admitted because it ws set up to oppose political abuse of
psychiatry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
