<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1609EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Politics     10-16 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Politics,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Entrepreneurs Facing Price Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers imposed price controls Monday on the
private businesses President Mikhail S. Gorbachev fostered to
supply goods and services the state cannot provide.
   The 542-member Supreme Soviet legislature took the action in
response to public accusations that the businesses, known as
cooperatives, have engaged in price gouging.
   When it began debating restrictions in September, legislator
Veniamin Yarin accused cooperatives of ``open robbery of the
working man.''
   Cooperatives are one of the few successes of Gorbachev's
economic reform program. His economic adviser, Leonid Abalkin, has
said Soviet society must recognize that cooperatives are an
important part of the economy, agree to treat them equally with
state-run business and allow local governments to regulate them.
   Since they were legalized 2{ years ago, they have grown
dramatically and provide $20 billion in goods and services, Abalkin
has said.
   But last year, the government began taxing the cooperatives, and
expects to receive $2.3 billion from these levies next year.
   On Monday, more restrictions were imposed. The official Tass
news agency said local governing councils will set price ceilings
on consumer goods and services of cooperatives. The ceilings will
apply to products the state has contracted to buy from cooperatives
and items cooperatives manufacture using state-supplied resources.
   The businesses also will come under state price control when
they resell goods purchased from the state. Many cooperatives make
huge profits by buying scarce goods from the state and reselling
them at higher prices.
   Another provision forbids cooperatives from reselling imported
goods at a higher price than the state would charge.
   Legislator Anatoly Sobchak was quoted by Tass as saying the
restrictions ``make it possible to keep cooperative associations
intact and at the same time eliminate profiteering.''
   One deputy had proposed closing all wholesale and retail
cooperatives.
   Previously, cooperatives were exempt from state control over
their prices, and they have been able to obtain scarce goods by
paying off people with access to them.
   In the Sept. 26 debate, Gorbachev asked the legislature how the
cooperatives manage to find soap when no one else can. He noted the
cooperative price might be $7.74 for a bar of soap, when a state
store would charge just 62 cents to $1.55.
   Gorbachev stood by his creations, however.
   ``The main thing for us is to preserve cooperatives,'' he said.
``People see the evident difference between them. Those providing
services, manufacturing, producing construction materials,
repairing, helping, are more than welcome by the people. All those
intermediary cooperatives are considered to be thieves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
