<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-16 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diaper-clad ``Indiana Dan'' and his
companion, ``Kennebunk George Bushkin,'' cavort in a coloring book
that takes a cockeyed look at the president and vice president.
   President Bush wears a business suit and has an elephant's nose
and ears in the 48-page book. Vice President Quayle is portrayed as
a chubby baby wearing only a diaper and a golf visor.
   Creator James Travers, a printer and typesetter from Wilmington,
Del., said his inspiration was a nagging question after the two
took office: ``Who is Dan Quayle?''
   The book is called ``Indiana Dan and His Search for Political
Par Excellence.'' In one part, ``Indiana Dan,'' uses a magical golf
putter to play doubles against senators with partner ``Kennebunk
George.'' Before tee-off, Dan must recite the senators' names,
their state capitals, state nicknames and the dates their states
joined the union.
   At the bottom of each page are political quotes from famous
people _ and golf rules and definitions.
   Travers has sold a few hundred copies, at $8.95 each, since the
book was published in July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin pianists Richard and John Contiguglia
blame a ``cursed'' piece of Franze Liszt music for bringing the
curtain down on a weekend concert.
   The two tried to play the ``Grosses Konzertstuck uber
Mendelssohn's `Liederohne Worte' (Great Concert Piece on
Mendelssohn's `Songs Without Words').'' But a storm Saturday night
knocked out power to the concert hall.
   ``This is another episode of the curse. It's uncanny how many
times something has prevented this song from being played,''
Richard Contiguglia said.
   In 1835, Liszt collapsed while premiering the piece. In 1924,
Ferrucio Busone died shortly before playing it.
   The Contiguglias said the curse even struck them before.
   In 1986, when they were to perform the piece at an annual Liszt
Festival in Holland, the 58-page manuscript was seized by the Dutch
government, which thought Liszt's notes were coded espionage
secrets being passed from East Germany to the West.
   ``Now it's stopped by a storm,'' John Contiguglia said. ``I hate
to see what's going to happen next.''
   The twins will try to play the piece again Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALPARAISO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Thomas Blankenship Jr. has
the look and sound of W.C. Fields. Now, he has the name _ and he
even loves little chickadees.
   The truck driver had his name legally changed Tuesday to W.C.
Fields, to whom he bears a striking physical resemblance.
   ``My kids love it,'' he said. ``When we used to watch his old
movies, my little girl would say, `Daddy, that's you.' I would say,
`No honey, that's W.C. Fields.'''
   Two months shy of his 65th birthday, the Portage, Ind., man said
he chose his new identity to bring happiness to friends and family.
He'd been thinking about the name change for years.
   ``It feels good. I have a new life ahead of me,'' said the new
Fields, who has perfected his namesake's rhythmic speech,
accentuated by a cigar
   ``He only wanted to keep people happy. I'm at retirement age and
I figured my looks are to make people happy _ it's for everybody I
come in contact with,'' he said. ``Besides, I love little
chickadees.''
</TEXT>
