<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Fernandez     10-16 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernandez,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Prosecutor Accuses Attorney General of Deliberate Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the Iran-Contra
investigation Monday accused Attorney General Dick Thornburgh of
deliberately sidetracking ``with no legitimate reason'' the
criminal case against a former CIA station chief.
   There is ``every reason to proceed promptly'' in the criminal
prosecution of Joseph Fernandez, the CIA's ex-station chief in
Costa Rica, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh said in a court
brief.
   Fernandez assisted Oliver North's secret Contra supply network
during a congressional ban on U.S. military aid to the rebel force.
   On Friday, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond,
Va., granted the Justice Department's request for a month's time to
consider whether it wants to appeal its ruling that Thornburgh
couldn't intervene in the Fernandez prosecution on secrecy issues.
   Walsh's brief asked the court to reconsider its order.
   Fernandez was scheduled to go on trial in July, but the Justice
Department went to the appeals court after U.S. District Court
Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va., said Fernandez was entitled
to disclose certain government secrets.
   Those include the fact that the CIA has stations in Honduras and
El Salvador.
   Thornburgh has ``repeatedly thwarted'' the prosecution ``by
last-minute, unannounced procedural maneuvers designed only to tie
this case in a knot of endless litigation,'' said Walsh.
   Walsh said Thornburgh ``has asserted no legitimate reason for
delay'' and that ``there is every reason to proceed promptly.''
   Walsh complained that the attorney general provided no notice
that he had decided to file the request for an extension. The
Justice Department and Walsh's office have worked closely on
secrecy issues for three years. In this instance, the Justice
Department mailed Walsh a copy of his request, depriving the
independent counsel of an opportunity to respond before the court
acted, the court papers stated.
   The department's request for the extension was prepared on Oct.
11, the day Justice Department spokesman David Runkel assured
reporters in a memo that ``there are no new developments in the
Fernandez case.''
   Asked last Friday about the discrepancy between his statement
and the department's actions, Runkel said he was unaware that
government lawyers were preparing to file the request for the
extension.
   Walsh said the information Thornburgh seeks to protect ``is
widely known to the public,'' such as the existence of CIA stations
in Latin America. The independent counsel said Thornburgh's only
course in protecting the information is to file an affidavit which
would prohibit its use at Fernandez's trial.
   Such a step could lead to dropping the criminal charges against
the ex-CIA officer, who is accused of obstructing the Tower
Commission and the CIA inspector general's offices and making false
statements.
   In the court papers, Walsh said he was told by Assistant
Attorney General Edward Dennis on Oct. 2 that the Justice
Department probably would not seek further court review. Dennis,
head of the department's criminal division, said that Thornburgh
probably would file an affidavit prohibiting disclosure of the
information at the Fernandez trial, said Walsh.
   In addition, said Walsh, a criminal division attorney indicated
on Oct. 11 that the division had sent a memo to the solicitor
general recommending against seeking further appeals court review.
</TEXT>
