<FIRST>r a AM-AxSlayings     10-16 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ax Slayings,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Gets Life in Prison for Ax Slaying of Parents, Siblings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Judge's first name Ancy is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was sentenced Monday to life
in prison for using an ax to kill his parents, brother and sister,
a case the judge called ``an extreme and monumental tragedy.''
   David Brom was sentenced to three consecutive life terms in the
deaths of his parents and brother and a concurrent term in the
death of his sister. He will not be eligible for parole for 52{
years.
   Brom had pleaded innocent by reason of mental illness in the
February 1988 slayings at the family's rural Rochester home. He was
16 at the time of the slayings but was tried as an adult.
   A jury found him guilty of four counts of first-degree murder
Oct. 3 _ Brom's 18th birthday. It rejected his insanity defense
Sunday in completing Minnesota's two-part trial system for insanity
pleas.
   Brom was impassive during his entencing Monday by Olmsted County
District Judge Ancy Morse, who said the case was an ``extreme and
monumental tragedy'' caused by a ``pathetically sick, depressed
mind.''
   He declined an opportunity to speak before the court.
   An appeal is automatic.
   During trial, County Attorney Ray Schmitz told jurors that Brom
repeatedly talked to friends about killing his family as part of
``a kind of game.'' Schmitz said Brom admitted the killings in a
conversation with a friend. And he said Brom told a friend he had
an altercation with his father the night of the killings.
   Defense attorney Terrence Walters had agreed that Brom committed
the slayings but argued they were not premeditated, and that Brom
was mentally ill.
   Brom was convicted of killing his parents, Bernard and Paulette,
both 41; his sister, Diane, 13, and brother, Ricky, 11.
   During the trial, five psychiatrists agreed that Brom suffered
from a major mental illness; only one said Brom met Minnesota's
legal standard of insanity.
</TEXT>
