<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1706EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Markets-Foreign     10-16 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Foreign,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Stock Markets Tumble In Response To Friday The 13th</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock markets around the world tumbled Monday as foreigners
reacted to Wall Street's Friday the 13th plunge with a deluge of
sell orders that clogged exchanges from Tokyo to Lisbon.
   ``The general perception is there was a bit of a panic,'' said
Guy Stern, a research analyst at ABD Securities Corp. in New York.
   But analysts said that despite sharp drops in stock prices, the
global backlash was nowhere near what it was two years ago in the
wake of Wall Street's Black Monday collapse.
   Some also said Wall Street's rebound on Monday, which saw the
Dow Jones industrial average rise nearly 90 points, could spark a
similar upturn when foreign exchanges reopened Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, the first major market to open following Friday's
abrupt 190-point plunge in the Dow industrial average, the key
225-share Nikkei Stock Average shed some 600 points at the opening,
rallied, and then slumped again to close down 647.33 points _ or
1.8 percent _ at 34,468.69.
   That compared with a record 15 percent Nikkei drop on Oct. 20,
1987, the day after Black Monday. Other Asian markets posted
moderate to large losses.
   Across Europe, trading delays and computer problems stemming
from extremely heavy trading plagued the markets.
   ``Along with Japan going down, the whole continent started to
drop very heavily,'' said Stern.
   London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down
by more than 9 percent at one point but recovered to finish at its
high of the day, off 70.5 points, or 3.2 percent, from Friday at
2,163.40.
   Trading was extremely heavy. Volume came to 959.3 million
shares, more than double Friday's volume.
   Share prices on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange tumbled in their
steepest fall ever, with the German Stock Index plunging 12.8
percent in what one Frankfurt dealer called ``a blood bath.''
   Price drops of 15 percent triggered temporary trading
suspensions in many shares in Paris, Brussels and Lisbon _ measures
designed to calm roiled markets. In Paris, dealing was temporarily
suspended twice due to insufficient buying orders.
   A mass of sell orders caused computer problems in Brussels,
where there was little trading all session. Amsterdam also had
computer problems during its session.
   Exchanges in Frankfurt, the Netherlands and elsewhere stayed
open late to compensate for the trading difficulties.
   Some European exchanges considered closing for the day but
decided against it. Several took extra precautions to stem a
freefall. In Milan, for example, traders were prohibited from short
selling, the practice of selling borrowed shares in speculation
they can be bought back later at a lower price.
   ``Things started off more or less the same as two years ago, but
the big difference is that when (trading) came back to New York,
the market had rebounded,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist at
Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   After gyrating wildly throughout the morning, the Dow average
had moved into plus territory and stabilized, finishing the day up
88.12 at 2,657.38 _ a 3.43 percent gain.
   Analysts predicted that foreign markets would feed off of Wall
Street's Monday gain, just as they reflected last week's decline.
   ``The markets overseas are probably going to rebound strongly as
long as the U.S. market stays fairly stable,'' Stern said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
