<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DeltaReport     10-16 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delta Report,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Issues Report on Problems in Mississippi River States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poverty, unemployment and infant mortality add
up to misery in the lower Mississippi River region, and the remedy
must include help from the federal government, a commission said
Monday.
   The Lower Mississippi River Delta Development Commission
acknowledged the economic ills that burden seven states bordering
the river and said those woes should not prevent the region from
``participating as a full partner in America's future.''
   ``In short, the region is not only worth saving, but because of
its location, resources and climate, could make a major
contribution to the rest of the nation and the world,'' the
commission said.
   The commission was created by Congress in 1988 to come up with a
10-year plan to aid 214 counties near the Mississippi. It did not
offer specific recommendations Monday; those are due in May.
   The commission, however, did address some issues that could get
attention in the final report:
   _Flood control. Local communities are required to pay a 25
percent share of federal flood-control projects.
   ``For some of the poorest counties in the Delta, we should have
no match or at least a much smaller match than 25 percent,'' said
Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, the commission chairman.
   _Infant mortality. Support for provision of midwives would
``cost a small amount of federal funds ... and would produce
enormous returns.'' In 1984, the commission said, 14 counties lost
more babies per 1,000 births than Chile, Cuba, Malaysia and French
Guiana.
   _Corporate help. Workers at a Louisiana company had a high
incidence of low-birthweight babies. After a $10,000 program to
educate pregnant women, improvement was dramatic.
   The commission said economic development has been harmed by a
history of racial clashes, which have the fueled a perception of
the Delta as a ``social and political backwater.''
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., said the region's overall problems
represent the ``most pervasive shame of America.''
   ``Yes, we'll ask for some things from the federal government,''
Clinton said, ``but they won't be massive dollar commitments.
   ``We do not expect the national government, given the present
budget realities, to write us a big check. ... We want a
partnership over 10 years with strict accountability for all,'' he
said.
   The states covered by the commission are Arkansas, Louisiana,
Tennessee, Illinois, Missouri, Kentucky and Mississippi.
</TEXT>
