<DOCNO> AP891016-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-USDABudget     10-16 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USDA Budget,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicken Inspectors May Have To Go</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gramm-Rudman Cuts, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department eventually will
have to furlough some chicken inspectors and other employees to
reduce spending under the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law, a
budget official said Monday.
   But Dennis Kaplan, chief of USDA's budget control and analysis
division, said there is widespread belief that ``Congress will pass
some kind of reconciliation'' measure soon that will make the
Gramm-Rudman mandatory cuts, or sequester, unnecessary.
   The department's programs ``are going to go on basically as they
always have over the next couple of weeks ... there'll be no real
impact on programs'' during that time, he said in an interview.
   ``Even if we go through the sequester, you're not going to see
any major impact until toward the end of the year,'' Kaplan said.
   Some USDA agencies that have big payrolls would be hit hard
eventually. The Food Safety and Inspection Service, for example,
which handles federal meat and poultry inspections, ``will probably
furlough a lot of their employees,'' he said. ``But that won't
occur until August or September.''
   Other agencies in a similar boat include the Forest Service,
with its vast organization of regional and lower-echelon offices;
the Farmers Home Administration, including county offices that
service loans for financially pressed farmers; and the Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, including its quarantine and
disease-control activities.
   Kaplan said much of USDA's spending is exempt from Gramm-Rudman
cuts, including the vast food stamp, school lunch and other child
nutrition programs.
   Farm price support operations are subject to the Gramm-Rudman
cutback, which averages 5.3 percent for domestic agencies, or about
$8.1 billion. Defense cuts also must total $8.1 billion, or 4.3
percent.
   After deducting all the exempted programs from USDA's projected
spending for fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1, the base used for the
cuts is about $9.59 billion, Kaplan said. The 5.3 percent
Gramm-Rudman reduction would amount to around $509 million.
   Two years ago, in another Gramm-Rudman round that was later
rolled back by Congress, USDA underwent an 8.5 percent pruning of a
base exceeding $8.25 billion, meaning a reduction of around $702
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
