<FIRST>u a AM-HurricaneJerry     10-16 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Jerry,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jerry Toll In Texas: Two Dead, $8.5 Million In Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remnants of small but deadly
Hurricane Jerry blew out of Texas and into Louisiana and Arkansas
on Monday after causing scattered damage estimated at less than $10
million.
   At least two people were killed.
   The small storm grew unexpectedly from a tropical storm to a
hurricane early Sunday and roared ashore with wind gusting to 100
mph, toppling trees and power lines, tearing up roofs and
shattering windows in cars and residences.
   Cleanup crews began collecting downed tree limbs and debris
Monday and the city of some 62,000 southeast of Houston quickly was
returning to normal.
   All but one of the city's schools were open Monday. That school
was closed because of a power failure.
   Mayor Jan Coggeshall said the city would not seek a disaster
declaration from the governor.
   ``We've had much more serious storms. But for the people who did
have damage, it was very serious for them,'' the mayor said.
   Initial damage estimates ranged as high as $25 million, but Mrs.
Coggeshall said that after an aerial survey and ground inspection
by city officials, damage was put at $5 million to $8.25 million.
   ``We don't think it's as serious as Alicia,'' she said,
referring to the 1983 hurricane which caused hundreds of millions
of dollars in damage.
   Some 75,000 Houston Lighting &amp; Power customers were without
electricity at the height of the storm. Most power was restored
Monday.
   After slamming into the island community of Galveston, the storm
drove up the Houston Ship Channel, crumpling four Houston Lighting
&amp; Power transmission towers built to withstand 90 mph wind.
Although customers were not affected seriously by the collapse of
the towers, traffic on the ship channel was halted by the downed
wires and the channel likely would be closed until Tuesday, utility
spokeswoman Geri Konigsberg said.
   Most Galveston residents decided to stay in their homes behind
the seawall instead of evacuating. No mandatory evacuations were
ordered, although a curfew was in effect overnight to discourage
looting.
   Several hundred residents who sought protection in shelters were
allowed to return home Sunday night.
   The hurricane barely brushed Louisiana but it stirred up enough
waves to eat away more of the delicate coastline of Grand Isle,
La., a barrier island and popular resort community.
   Grand Isle Mayor Andy Valence said wind was light and tides were
only about 2.3 feet above normal, but more than 4 feet of beach was
eroded in some areas.
   ``We had to get in touch with a couple of the camp owners to
have them come down and perhaps shore up some of the building
sections,'' said Valence.
   At least six tornadoes accompanied the hurricane, which was
downgraded to a tropical storm at 11 p.m. Sunday with winds at 45
mph. By 5 a.m. Monday, the National Weather Service reduced the
storm again to a tropical depression. The tornadoes caused mostly
roof and powerline damage.
   By midday Monday, the storm was moving through northern
Louisiana and into Arkansas with forecasters warning of 3 to 5
inches of rain and possible tornadoes. During the afternoon, the
low pressure center that once was the hurricane was moving
northeastward out of southwestern Arkansas and showers and
thunderstorms were scattered across the lower Mississippi Valley
into the lower Ohio Valley.
   The only fatalities were a 26-year-old Coast Guardsman and his
2-year-old daughter, whose bodies were found on the rock jetties of
Galveston's protective seawall. They were in a pickup that
apparently got blown off the seawall, Detective Sgt. Leo Singleton
said Monday.
   A third person was believed to have been in the pickup but had
not been found, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Syse     10-16 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Syse,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway's New Prime Minister: An Urbane Country Boy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Norway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan P. Syse, who became Norway's prime
minister on Monday, is a bright, witty, eloquent and capable lawyer
who calls himself just a boy from the country.
   But many easygoing Norwegians view him as a bit too polished and
urbane.
   Standing for the first time as party leader in an election, Syse
failed to galvanize the electorate and his Conservative Party came
out of the Sept. 11 vote with its worst showing in 20 years.
   But Syse patched together the three centrist non-socialist
parties in a coalition to replace Gro Harlem Brundtland's Labor
government, which also experienced its worst election since World
War II.
   The contrast between the two leaders in the public mind goes
deeper than politics.
   Mrs. Brundtland is known abroad as a stateswoman,
environmentalist and champion of women's rights. In Norway, she is
simply known as Gro.
   The new prime minister is normally referred to as Syse _ proper
but formal.
   The 58-year-old attorney usually appears controlled, measured
and reserved. Mrs. Brundtland, a 50-year-old physician and
Harvard-educated public health specialist, has a fiery temper but
also will openly show grief.
   ``Syse is an excellent speaker, philosphical and funny. He is a
relatively moderate politician,'' said Bernt Ole Aardal, of the
Institute for Social Research.
   Syse became chairman of Norway's second largest party upon the
sudden death of Rolf Presthus in January 1988, when the party was
in the midst of a structuring crisis. He had little time to
establish his leadership before the elections, Aardal noted.
   Critics call Syse a tough and clever politician, strong on
law-and-order and moral issues. But he is burdened with his image.
   ``He is seen as what Norwegians would call too Oslo West,
meaning that he's from the wealthy part of town, very high society
and implying that he is above other people,'' said Aardal.
   Born on Nov. 25, 1930, Syse was in fact raised on the pastoral
island of Notteroey, south of Oslo. He stresses his rural
upbringing, even after almost 40 years in the capital.
   ``I really have trouble comprehending this resilient myth that
I'm so urbane,'' said Syse. ``I am a country boy from Noetteroey.''
   But his heavy-rimmed glasses, flawless diction and rigid posture
enhance the image of an intellectual. An Oslo newspaper joked that
Syse would wear a tie with his towel in Parliament's sauna.
   Syse's quest for a folksier image has sometimes backfired.
   He invited news media to record him fishing from a trawler this
summer and ended up with a giant hook through his finger, removed
in a highly publicized effort involving a hacksaw and pliers.
   The son of a dentist-local politician and his school principal
wife, Syse was politically active early on and was elected chairman
of the Conservative Students Association in 1952. He earned a law
degree from the University of Oslo in 1957.
   He began his career as a lawyer for a shipowner, later working
in non-political, upper-echelon government jobs. He married teacher
Else Walstad in 1959 and has two sons, one who also is a politician.
   He trod a familiar path through party ranks, and was elected to
Parliament in 1973.
   Political scientist Gunnar Vogt said Syse may prove to be a
surprisingly strong leader, as demonstrated by his ability to
stitch together a coalition from three deeply divided parties _ the
Conservatives, the Christian People's Party and the Center Party.
   Mrs. Brundtland, became Norway's first woman prime minister in
1981 and, at 44, its youngest. Her first term lasted seven months.
   She returned to power in May 1986 and gained international
stature as head the U.N. World Commission on the Environment and
Development. Norwegians prefer her international record to her
domestic one.
   Mrs. Brundtland quickly set some new rules. Eight of the 18
Cabinet ministers were women, and her Labor Party made it a rule
that each sex must have at least 40 percent of all party positions.
   Syse's 19-member Cabinet also has eight women.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
