<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Markets-Scene     10-16 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Scene,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Maalox Moment' Outside NYSE, Anarchist Protesters Say `Down with
the Dow'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curious tourists, scraggly anarchists screaming
``Sell today, jump tomorrow!'' and a man handing out free antacid
tablets turned the streets around the cavernous New York Stock
Exchange into a spectacle Monday.
   Inside, frenzied traders sweated through hair-rising price
swings.
   ``It's just crazy,'' said a blue-jacketed exchange worker who
identified himself only as Billy, stepping out for a smoke while
the Dow Jones industrial average bounced around in some of the
heaviest trading in history.
   The best-known stock barometer of 30 stocks gyrated wildly and
finished with an 88.12 point gain, erasing nearly half its
190.58-point drop of last Friday.
   The rebound helped the market avert another Black Monday like
Oct. 19, 1987, when the average tumbled a record 508 points.
   The ``Big Board,'' as the NYSE is known in Wall Street parlance,
decided to keep its visitors' gallery closed, deploying its
tan-uniformed sentries at all entrances. But that didn't stop
scores of curious tourists from coming down to the exchange
building, hoping for a glimpse inside.
   ``I've got some money in there, too, so that makes it more
exciting,'' said Robert Overton, 21, of Chapel Hill, N.C., an
accounting major in his senior year at the University of North
Carolina. He expressed optimism.
   ``It crashed two years ago and it really didn't hurt the
economy,'' he said. ``Business is going to be in business, no
matter what happens today.''
   Others weren't so sanguine. John Egan, 24, a New Yorker with a
couple of hours to kill, said, ``I feel like I'm watching a car
accident.''
   As on previous occasions when the stock market has made big
news, protesters flocked to Wall Street. About a dozen police
officers, some on horseback and others on motorcycles, deployed
themselves nearby.
   ``Down with the Dow, revolution now,'' read a placard held by a
black-scarved man in a group of anarchist-squatters who've been
camped out in a local park.
   ``Watch out for falling stockbrokers!'' they chanted. ``Whether
it crashes today, tomorrow, or next week, isn't the question,''
said one member of the group, who identified himself as John Squat.
``It's the fundamental economy we're talking about.''
   Laura Januzzi, a 26-year-old tourist from Cincinnati, said,
``Where there's dead meat, there's the flock.''
   Perhaps the most enterprising spectator was a man wearing a
Maalox T-shirt, giving away free samples of the antacid from a tub
he carried. ``Maalox sir?'' he asked passersby.
</TEXT>
