<DOCNO> AP891016-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1829EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-FalklandTalks     10-16 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falkland Talks,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine, British Delegations Prepare for Talks in Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina and Britain begin talks Tuesday
on restoring diplomatic relations, broken in 1982 by a 74-day war
over the bleak, windswept Falkland Islands that cost nearly 1,000
lives.
   Neither side would comment on the talks set for Tuesday and
Wednesday, but a joint statement issued Aug. 18 said both sought
``normalization of relations and the furtherance of their mutual
interests in peace and stability in the South Atlantic.''
   The agenda of the closed negotiations in Madrid is expected to
center on renewal of consular ties and air and sea links.
   Argentina is expected to seek an end to the 150-mile exclusion
zone Britain has imposed around the islands, which keeps Argentine
boats out of rich fishing grounds 300 miles off its coast.
   Spanish diplomats said Argentina probably would call for a
reductions in the 2,000-man military force Britain has kept in the
islands since the war. The Argentines invaded the Falklands, which
they claim and call the Malvinas, on April 2, 1983.
   Indirect relations have been handled through a British interests
section at the Swiss Embassy in Buenos Aires and an Argentine
interests section at Brazil's embassy in London.
   Argentina's delegation to the Madrid talks is led by roving
Ambassador Lucio Garcia del Solar. Leading negotiations for Britain
is its U.N. ambassador, Sir Crispin Tickell.
   Sovereignty over the 200-island archipelago is not an issue
because President Carlos Menem dropped the Argentine insistence
that its claim to the British colony be the first issue considered
in a discussion of normal relations.
   An attempt at talks in March 1984 in Bern, Switzerland,
foundered over sovereignty.
   Although the Argentine invasion force surrendered on June 14,
1982, no formal end to hostilities has been declared.
   When the joint communique was issued Aug. 18, at U.N.
headquarters in New York, Garcia del Solar said he felt hostilities
ended in 1982 and no formal declaration to normalize relations was
necessary.
   Most of the 1,900 Falklanders, whose economic mainstays are
sheep-ranching and fishing, are descendants of British sailors.
   The islands were believed sighted in 1592 by the English
navigator John Davis. The British established a naval base at what
is now Saunders Island in 1765, then the Spanish drove them out in
1770.
   Louis-Antoine de Bougainville of France established the first
settlement in 1764 and named it Les Malouines, because most of his
crewmen were from the French port of St. Malo. Spain later bought
out the French.
   Argentina bases its claim on the 1494 Treaty of Tordesillas, in
which Spain and Portugal settled New World territorial disputes and
agreed on Spanish possession of the Falklands, to which Argentina
succeeded after independence in 1816.
   A British warship regained control of the islands for Britain in
1833 without firing a shot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
