<DOCNO> AP891016-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1833EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Thornburgh     10-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Thornburgh,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Favors New Legislation for Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Monday he
will support new legislation that could admit 30,000 more Soviet
Jews a year to the United States than allowed by immigration quotas.
   American officials said last month that 70,000-80,000 Soviets
could enter the United States next year, but they expect 300,000
applications as more citizens of all nationalities seek to leave
the Soviet Union.
   Thornburgh, the first U.S. attorney general to visit the Soviet
Union, met with Soviet Jewish activists to calm their fears that
new U.S. quotas would force emigrants to go elsewhere.
   Under rules effective Oct. 1, Soviet Jews no longer can leave
the country with visas for Israel, then apply in Vienna or Rome for
refugee status in the United States.
   When the new regulations were announced, thousands of Jews and
Armenians went to the U.S. Embassy seeking explanations and
application forms.
   Jewish activist Leonid D. Stonov, 50, told Thornburgh
anti-Semitism was growing in the Soviet Union and the new rules
should be eased.
   ``Jewish emigration is now more on the order of an evacuation,''
Stonov, who has tried to leave for 10 years, said in a meeting with
Thornburgh at the U.S. Embassy.
   Soviet Jewish emigration has increased dramatically under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, from 8,000 in 1987 to 19,000 last
year and a projected 35,000 in 1989. Non-Jewish emigration this
year is expected to reach 15,000.
   Thornburgh said he understood the concerns of Soviet Jews and
would support proposed legislation allowing President Bush to raise
the Soviet quota by 30,000 a year for five years.
   ``We have urged that the Congress act ... so it will act
somewhat as a safety valve for the conditions you describe,''
Thornburgh told the activists.
   An aide said most of those getting special emigration status
probably would be Soviet Jews.
   Thornburgh arrived Sunday for a five-day visit.
</TEXT>
