<FIRST>r w AM-ColombiaCommendation     10-16 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia Commendation,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Commend Colombia's Courage in Drug Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday commended the government
and people of Colombia for ``tremendous courage and fortitude in
standing up to the atrocities'' of drug traffickers.
   In a 348-0 vote, the House approved a resolution that urged the
Bush administration to continue to provide support ``in terms of
equipment, training, intelligence and financial assistance'' to
help the South American country fight the illegal drug trade.
   The resolution, which now goes to the Senate for a vote,
commends President Virgilio Barco and ``expresses to the government
and people of Colombia the support, respect and empathy of the
Congress and the people of the United States in this most difficult
time.''
   The assassinations of presidential candidate Juan Carlos Galan
and other high-ranking officials have been blamed on drug lords,
along with the deaths of 200 Colombian judges, 11 Supreme Court
justices and four counsels of state.
   Thousands of others, including mayors, law enforcement officers,
public officials, journalists, lawyers and doctors also have died
in the drug wars which have included the bombing of public places
and offices.
   The House said drug dealers ``are exporting their terror by
smuggling the illegal, deadly drug concaine into the United States,
Latin America, the Caribbean and Europe.''
