<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast     10-16 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Urges PLO To Support Talks With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department urged the Palestine
Liberation Organization on Monday to authorize talks with Israel
``if we are ever to get the (negotiating) process off the ground.''
   At the same time, spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said the Bush
administration was not fazed by criticism of its strategy by
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Specifically, Shamir objected to having Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak select the Palestinians for the talks and to holding the
session in Cairo.
   ``We are not upset, we do not think it is a step backwards,''
Ms. Tutwiler said of Shamir's statements to the Israeli newspaper
Ma`ariv.
   She said Secretary of State James A. Baker III would keep
working with Foreign Ministers Moshe Arens of Israel and Esmet
Abdel-Meguid of Egypt to get negotiations started.
   But her criticism of the PLO was clear.
   ``If we are ever to get the process off the ground, Palestinians
are going to have to find a way to respond positively,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said.
   The PLO Central Council, at the end of a two-day meeting in
Baghdad, Iraq, on Monday rejected Baker's plan and said the PLO
alone has the right to decide who should talk to Israel.
   A declaration by the Central Council accused the Bush
administration of ignoring the PLO as the ``sole legitimate
representative'' of the Palestinians. It said the American
proposals were only a version of the Israeli peace plan.
   Robert Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, met last
Friday with PLO officials. Mubarak, meanwhile, is acting as a
middle-man between Baker and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   PLO approval is considered essential before any Palestinians
would negotiations with Israel.
   Baker is working on a plan to have Palestinians and Israelis
meet in Cairo on Shamir's proposal for an election on the West Bank
and in Gaza.
   The elected Palestinians then would negotiate limited self-rule
with Israel, to be followed after five years by negotiations for an
overall Middle East settlement.
   The PLO has denounced the proposal as a ploy to prevent
establishment of a Palestinian state on Israeli-held territory.
   On another subject, Ms. Tutwiler indirectly criticized Mubarak
for his recent meeting with Col. Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan leader.
   ``Our position on Libya, its support for terrorism and other
regional activities involving destabilization is well known,'' the
spokeswoman said. ``We have made known to Egypt our views and
concerns.''
   President Bush talked to Mubarak about Libya when the Egyptian
President was at the White House last month, Ms. Tutwiler said.
   ``We are confident that Egypt understands our position on
Libya,'' she said.
</TEXT>
