<FIRST>r a AM-ChildPlacement     10-16 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Placement,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached on Overnight Placement of Children in State Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children under state care would no
longer be shuffled from place to place at night but would have
permanent places to stay under an agreement presented Monday to a
judge.
   Child Advocate Laureen D'Ambra, who works for the state to
protect children's rights, said Rhode Island's Department For
Children and Their Families promised to add 45 beds in foster homes
and group programs by June 30 and to spend $1 million to add 45
more by Jan. 31, 1991.
   U.S. District Judge Raymond J. Pettine said he would decide
within three days whether to accept the agreement. D'Ambra said the
department acted in good faith and she believed it would try to
adhere to the agreement.
   The agreement would end D'Ambra's quest for a contempt citation
against department Director Joseph J. Picano, who did not meet a
July 15 deadline to end most night-to-night placement to settle the
child advocate's 1986 lawsuit against the department.
   The department now has agreed to shuffle children on a
night-to-night basis for no more than three consecutive nights by
Nov. 30 and eliminate any night-to-night placement by June 30,
except for emergencies.
   The state pays foster homes and other facilities $20 per night
per child beyond the their licensed capacity, D'Ambra said.
   ``It was easy for them,'' she said, but the children had to
leave every morning and fend for themselves at various day programs
before finding out where they would sleep the next night. They do
not go to school, D'Ambra said.
   ``They're carrying their clothes around in trashbags and they
are certainly not in a postion to receive counseling,'' said
D'Ambra. The routine ``wears them down to the point of hopelessness
in many cases.''
   Some children under 13 not allowed in the various day programs
have been forced to stay in the department's offices during the
day, said D'Ambra.
   She estimated an average of five children per night don't know
where they will sleep. Stephan H. Lieberman, the department's
assistant director of community resources, said the caseload of
those up to age 21 who need placement has grown 8 percent to 10
percent yearly, or about 200 children a year, ranging from new
children in the system to those kicked out of other programs.
   There also has been a decrease in the number of foster homes,
D'Ambra said.
   Among the alternatives are more group homes, residential
programs and apartments for older teen-agers, D'Ambra said.
   Lieberman said the state had created 45 beds, exceeding the 40
called for in the original settlement of the 1986 lawsuit, but then
lost 21 through the closing of the overnight section of a group
home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
