<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 4thLd-Writethru a0718 10-16 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0718,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>120,000 March in Leipzig; Paper: Leaders Seek Honecker Ouster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with later crowd figures, Baker
speech. Picks up graf 13 pvs, `Mounting pressure ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 120,000 pro-democracy demonstrators
marched peacefully through downtown Leipzig for three hours Monday
night in the largest protest of communist East Germany's 40-year
history, opposition activists said.
   Official media said, in their first prompt report of such a
protest, that ``tens of thousands of citizens'' participated.
   Security was increased in East Berlin, the nation's capital.
Knots of police and other security forces could be seen on many
streets.
   Activists reported no incidents in Leipzig, where more than
70,000 protesters marched Oct. 9 after a month in which tens of
thousands of East Germans fled to the West.
   Protesters assembled for Monday's march after services in five
churches, said the main evening news program ``Aktuella Kamera.''
It did not show the march.
   ``After peace services ... tens of thousands of citizens took
part in a demonstration,'' the program said. ``Thanks to the
restraint of the police and other security forces, no incidents
occurred.''
   Christoph Wonneberger, pastor of St. Luke's Lutheran Church in
Leipzig, said in a telephone interview with West Germany's ZDF
television that more than 120,000 people marched. Wonneberger often
speaks for pro-reform groups.
   Marchers chanted ``We are the People!'' and ``Democracy Now or
Never!''
   In a foreign policy speech in Washington, Secretary of State
James A. Baker III said reunification of their nation was a
``legitimate right'' of Germans.
   The Monday demonstration followed weekend protests in Halle by
20,000 people and in Plauen, near the Czechoslovak border, where
more than 15,000 gathered, opposition sources said.
   They said the Plauen march lasted about two hours Saturday
afternoon and the crowd chanted ``Democracy now!'' Banners bore the
same inscription and placards called for free expression and a free
press.
   An opposition source told The Associated Press no uniformed
police were in the area and there was no interference.
   Late Sunday, 4,000 young East Germans demanding reform jammed
the Lutheran Church of the Redeemer in East Berlin for a rock
concert, chanting in English: ``We are here to stay!''
   A West German newspaper said regional Communist Party officials
demanded the dismissal of hard-line leader Erich Honecker.
   Mounting pressure was evident on Honecker, 77, and other members
of the aging, doctrinaire leadership. Unrest spread and the flight
of thousands of East Germans continued.
   Among those leaving were more than 1,300 refugees under the care
of the West German Embassy in Warsaw, who have been promised
special exit permits. West Germany gives automatic citizenship to
East Germans.
   Reports have spread for days that Honecker's 18-year tenure as
head of the Communist Party may be about to end.
   The mass-circulation West German newspaper Bild reported Monday
that dissatisfaction had spread to the regional party leaders.
   It quoted ``well informed'' sources in East Berlin as saying 13
of the 15 regional chiefs were demanding Honecker be ousted and the
21-member Politburo shaken up.
   Bild said the regional leaders ``fear that strikes and unrest
will break out all across the nation.'' It said they want the
government to meet with opposition groups, ease travel restrictions
and hold free elections.
   The newspaper, owned by the conservative Springer publishing
group, said the regional leaders demanded a special meeting of the
party Central Committee to make the changes. Bild sent its report
to other news media Monday, in advance of publication in Tuesday
editions.
   Politburo members hold their regular weekly meeting Tuesday and
there has been speculation this week's session would indicate
Honecker's future.
   Several street protests in East Germany this month were the
largest since Soviet troops crushed a workers' rebellion in 1953.
   Most were broken up by police using clubs, but on Oct. 9, about
70,000 people marched in Leipzig without police interference,
chanting ``Freiheit!'' _ the German word for freedom.
   Most protesters are young East Germans who insist they want to
stay and help reform the country, not flee to the West.
   Harry Tisch, the government's labor chief, has acknowledged
growing unrest among the 8.6 million East German workers.
   ``I can say openly that the climate among the workers is
tense,'' Tisch, a Politburo member, said in an interview with the
official newspaper Junge Welt.
   As head of the state labor federation Freie Deutsche
Gewerkschaftsbund, he oversees the nation's work force.
   More than 52,000 East Germans have fled West since late July,
either across Hungary's open border with Austria or after seeking
refuge at West German embassies in Warsaw or Prague.
</TEXT>
