<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     10-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Begins Dismissing Public Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government started cutting the
public payroll with dismissals Monday and Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega rearranged military ranks thinned by disloyalty.
   Noriega, who commands the Panamanian Defense Forces and runs the
country, named close associates to several key posts over the
weekend but many important positions, including the chief of
intelligence, remained open.
   Col. Guillermo Wong, the former intelligence chief, was among
those arrested after an unsuccessful coup Oct. 3. Failure to
replace him suggested Noriega may be having trouble finding enough
trustworthy senior officers.
   Gustavo Gonzalez, the planning and economic policy minister,
told journalists Monday there would be no ``massive firings'' of
public employees but said the public payroll must be reduced.
   ``We do not have a budget,'' he told reporters at a luncheon
with the Bankers Association. ``We are operating on a cash flow
basis and that flow is now about 50 per cent of what it was two
years ago.''
   Panama's economy has been hurt badly by U.S. economic sanctions
imposed after Noriega was indicted on U.S. drug trafficking and
money laundering charges in February 1988.
   Noriega claims the charges and the coup attempt are part of a
U.S. plot to remove him and keep the Panama Canal, which by treaty
is to be turned over to Panama at the end of 1999.
   Bankers Association president Edgardo Lasso said lack of
confidence caused by the sanctions and political instability had
caused a serious recession. He denied Panama was a center for
laundering drug money.
   Gonzalez said high public officials had taken salary reductions
ranging from 20 to 30 percent, and ``that includes Gen. Noriega.''
   One public employee told journalists she and four others had
been accused of ``conspiring against the state'' Monday and fired.
   Government officials, including Noriega, urged the dismissal of
public employees who celebrated or showed disloyalty while the
attempted coup was in process.
   ``War laws'' announced by Noriega after the coup include
disloyalty among the reasons for dismissal of public employees.
   The government said an International Monetary Fund mission was
arriving to ``evaluate the country's situation and study measures
the government is considering to improve the economic situation.''
   Panama's foreign debt is $3.8 billion and it is $1.2 billion
behind in payments on interest and principal.
   Capt. Rafael Gaytan, for two years the director of Noriega's
personal security, was named head of the Special Anti-Terrorist
Forces, an elite unit said to have been blocked by U.S. forces from
aiding Noreiga the day of the coup.
   Capt. Rafael Cedeno, another officer close to Noriega, was named
deputy director of intelligence. Cedeno has worked closely with
Noriega since the early '80s.
   Capt. Rafael Jurado became commander of the 2nd Military Zone
near the Costa Rican border and Col. Roberto Armijo was named
director of personnel, replacing Col. Julio Ow Young, arrested in
connection with the coup.
</TEXT>
