<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-RightToDie     10-16 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Right To Die,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Asks High Court to Uphold Missouri Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department urged the Supreme Court
on Monday to uphold a Missouri decision barring doctors from
shutting off a life-support system for a severely brain-damaged
woman.
   Siding with the state of Missouri in the first ``right-do-die''
case before the high court, the department argued that the parents
of Nancy Cruzan, 31, did not have a right to stop their daughter's
treatment without a court order.
   The Justice Department urged the high court to uphold a 4-3
decision of the Missouri Supreme Court that barred Joe and Joyce
Cruzan from allowing doctors to remove a feeding tube surgically
implanted in their daughter's stomach.
   Ms. Cruzan, who breathes normally and has periods of
wakefulness, is kept alive by feedings through the tube. Doctors
say that Ms. Cruzan is incapable of interacting with her
environment and has no thoughts or emotions.
   A mentally competent adult may have a right to refuse or end
treatment, but the decision to withdraw life-support systems cannot
be left to guardians acting on behalf of a person unable to express
a choice, the Justice Department said.
   ``There is no basis for concluding that petitioner's parents
have a due process right to halt her treatment that is somehow
independent of petitioner's own desires,'' the department said in a
friend-of-the-court brief.
   ``Whatever may be said about the rights of a currently competent
adult, an adult who is now incompetent cannot make an informed
decision to refuse treatment, and thus cannot be said to have a
qualified fundamental right,'' the Justice Department said in its
brief submitted by Solicitor General Kenneth Starr.
   The Justice Department offered an argument that was at odds with
the American Medical Association and other groups, which joined the
Cruzans in urging the high court to allow withdrawal of the tube.
   The department said the federal government has an interest in
the case because it operates 443 hospitals and nursing homes where
``issues about termination of treatment arise ... on a continuing
basis.''
   ``Reasonable minds can differ on whether courts are best suited
to determine an incompetent patient's preferences'' but the
Missouri court ``applied reasonable rules in this case,'' the brief
argued.
   The Missouri court ``reasonably concluded that any error should
be made on the side of life,'' it continued.
   ``In so doing, however, the court did not take an unreasonably
rigid approach to the evidence of petitioner's wishes.''
   The Cruzans testified that at one point their daughter told them
she would not want to be kept alive in a permanent coma. But the
Missouri court did not accept their statement as deciding the issue.
   ``In view of the state's powerful interests in protecting
incompetent persons against abuse an ensuring that any decision
made in the past was well-considered, state rules of evidence and
procedure designed to give effect to previous decisions to refuse
treatment should be upheld as long as they are `reasonably
designed' to serve an important state interest,'' the Justice
Department said.
   The department has argued that this standard should also be
applied to laws that prohibit or restrict abortion. The brief's
discussion of privacy rights mirrored the position the Justice
Department has taken on the abortion issue.
   The department said the ``court should decline petitioner's
invitation to extend the `right of privacy' to cover all types of
decisions about medical treatment and procedures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1952EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Britain-Chess     10-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Chess,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yusupov and Karpov Draw Seventh Game; Match Tied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Grandmasters Artur Yusupov and Anatoly
Karpov agreed to a 61-move draw Monday in the seventh game in their
World Chess Championship Candidates' semifinal to leave the match
tied 3.5-3.5 with one round remaining.
   In the other semifinal, Jan Timman of the Netherlands took a
timeout, postponing the eighth game of his tied semifinal with Jon
Speelman of England. After seven games, each player has scored 3.5
points.
   Final round faceoffs in both contests are set for Tuesday.
   After a zig-zag battle, Karpov emerged from a nerve-wracking
time scramble, a pawn behind in an endgame but in a position where
Yusupov had very few chances to win.
   The winner of the Candidates' cycle will challenge world
champion Garri Kasparov for his title in a 24-game contest starting
October 1990. The winning semifinalists will face off in the
Candidates' final next March.
   If either of the eight-game contests ends in a 4-4 tie, a
two-game minimatch will be played, followed if necessary by sudden
death tiebreakers.
   A win scores one point and a draw a half.
   Karpov held the world title for 10 years until 1985 and had been
widely expected to crush his opponent.
   His poor performance led Spanish chess commentator Leontxo
Garcia to remark, ``Karpov is very close to the abyss and only the
advantage of the white pieces can save him.''
   Karpov and Speelman will play white on Tuesday.
   A decisive victory in the sixth game on Saturday left Speelman
with the psychological initiative.
   Playing white on Monday, Yusupov failed to gain any advantage
from the opening and began to fall dangerously short of time.
   But a faulty plan from Karpov starting on the 24th move let
Yusupov escape the pressure, and white suddenly gained the
initiative in the center by combining a battery of two rooks and a
queen.
   Karpov sank deep into thought, leaving himself three minutes to
make 10 moves.
   As Yusopov exchanged down to reach an ending with an extra pawn,
Karpov's nerves began to show.
   But after reaching the time control, Karpov had few problems in
achieving a draw.
   Yusupov played on for a further 20 moves, but finally gave up
and offered a draw after playing his 61st move.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
