<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     10-16 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Repeats Acceptance Of Minimal Role For Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Monday repeated
that it would not oppose including the Khmer Rouge in a Cambodian
coalition government as a means of ending the civil war in that
country.
   The U.S. position remained that the Khmer Rouge, the communist
force that slaughtered thousands of their compatriots while in
power in the 1970's, should have no more than a minimal role in any
new government in Cambodia.
   State Department officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the U.S. position had changed little since a multilateral
conference in July failed to find a solution to the Cambodian civil
war.
   Administration officials have met representatives of China and
the Soviet Union to discuss the formation of a coalition Cambodian
government to replace the Hun Sen regime currently in power, State
Department spokesman Margaret Tutwiler told a briefing.
   Hun Sen, installed after the Vietnamese invasion that drove the
Khmer Rouge from power in 1978, remains in charge despite the
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops, and he has refused proposals for a
coalition government.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III discussed the issue with
his Soviet counterpart, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, at their meeting in
Wyoming last month, but neither Tutwiler nor other State Department
officials would discuss the behind-the-scenes negotiations.
   Tutwiler told reporters that ``we have made clear that our
ability to support any Cambodian government is directly and
inversely related to the degree of Khmer Rouge participation, if
any, in it.''
   Tutwiler's statement differed only slightly from the position
enunciated before Congress earlier this month by David F.
Lambertson, deputy assistant secretary of state for East Asian and
Pacific Affairs.
   ``Unfortunately, absent a viable political process, the
Cambodian factions are likely to turn increasingly to military
means to resolve their conflict, a result most likely to benefit
the Khmer Rouge,'' Lambertson told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on Oct. 2.
   ``The United States remains unalterably opposed to a return to
dominance of this abhorrent group, which left a legacy of brutality
and depravity from its reign of terror in the 1970's,'' he said.
   ``A durable settlement in this conflict must be constructed to
ensure that the Khmer Rouge can never regain control and subject
the Cambodian people once again to the horrors of the past,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
