<HEAD>$40 Million In Compromise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators agreed Monday
night to provide $40 million this year in federal aid for a major
new airport near Denver.
   The agreement in the conference committee on the appropriations
bill for the Transportation Department came on a voice vote without
dissent.
   It would be the first major airport built in the United States
since the Dallas-Fort Worth airport opened in 1974.
   The House version of the bill provided no money for the Denver
airport, while the Senate had provided $50 million.
   The bill provides $11.9 billion for transportation programs
during the fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
   The committee still has to resolve several other disagreements
and it will be several days before the bill is returned to the
House and Senate for final passage and transmittal to President
Bush for his siganture.
