<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Terrorism     10-16 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Terrorism,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Palestinians Plead Innocent To Terrorism Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Palestinians accused of terrorist
attacks on U.S. and Jewish targets pleaded innocent Monday at the
first day of their trial amid heavy security rarely encountered in
this country.
   The trial marked Sweden's first court case involving Middle East
terrorism, although police suspect the country has been used as a
hideout for underground Palestinians.
   Police took the security measures apparently fearing reprisals
for the Palestinians' arrests.
   The front of the District courthouse was sealed off, nearby
parking spaces were cleared and surrounding buildings were
searched. Plainclothes policemen occupied the first row of seats in
the courtroom gallery.
   Three of the Palestinians were charged with murder and attempted
murder for planting bombs in Copenhagen, Denmark, and Amsterdam,
the Netherlands, in 1985, and in Stockholm in 1986. All denied any
connection to the attacks.
   One bomb placed outside Copenhagen's Northwest Orient Airline
office killed a Danish bystander and wounded more than 20 people.
Northwest is based in Eagen, a Minneapolis suburb.
   Other targets were a synagogue and an office of El Al Israel
Airlines.
   The fourth defendant admitted he helped assemble explosives but
said he refused to carry out his assignment and threw his bomb into
a Copenhagen canal.
   He pleaded innocent to charges of being an accomplice but
implicated the others during the police investigation.
   The three defendants accused of murder could face a maximum of
20 years in prison in convicted.
   Mohammed Abo Talb, a 35-year-old defendant facing murder
charges, has been called the group leader. He has been described as
senior officer of the Syrian-based Popular Struggle Front, a
hard-line faction that opposes peace overtures of Palestine
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat.
   The trial was scheduled to last until mid-November.
</TEXT>
