<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-HongKong     10-16 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Hong Kong,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says City Must be Assured Political Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong's British governor said Monday that
China must assure the city that both political liberty and economic
freedom will continue after the 1997 Chinese takeover if it wants
to reap the financial rewards.
   A crucial time in the transition is next spring when the Beijing
government will publish the basic law, or constitution, for Hong
Kong, said Sir David Wilson.
   The 1984 British-Chinese agreement provides ``one country, two
systems'' for at least 50 years after 1997, and this ``must include
a different political system as well as economic system,'' he said.
   ``I hope the Chinese draftees of the basic law will pay full
attention'' to this, he added, because ``it is tremendously
important not only for post-1997, but for the (pre-1997) vision
people will have'' of their future in Hong Kong, he added.
   ``I believe it enormously important that'' China not dampen Hong
Kongers' confidence in the future, Wilson said at a luncheon at the
National Press Club.
   The basic law is a Chinese document, ``and what the draftees
will finally put into it, I don't know,'' he said.
   But Hong Kong can continue benefitting China ``only if the full
play of capitalism and all the political freedoms that go with it
continue after 1997,'' he said. The benefits flow from the fact
that ``China is quintessentially a capitalist society,'' he said,
providing China a source of foreign exchange, a bridge to Western
technology and a window on the West.
   ``There is no use pretending,'' Wilson said, the crackdown last
June on democracy in China ``shook confidence'' in the future for
Hong Kong. Hong Kongers now require assurances about the future to
encourage them to stay there.
   The British government has declared it will not allow unlimited
migration to Britain of its millions of Hong Kong subjects.
   Emigration from Hong Kong to all countries was running at 20,000
a year from 1981-86, and this year 42,000 departures are expected,
Wilson said.
   Wilson is on a quick visit to Washington, Los Angeles and San
Francisco to generate continued confidence in Hong Kong and its
economy on the part of officials and business people in the United
States, Hong Kong's major export market and investment source.
</TEXT>
