<FIRST>u a AM-Abortion-Illinois 1stLd-Writethru a0732 10-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Illinois, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top State Officials Meet With ACLU Lawyer to Settle Abortion Lawsuit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD that meeting was first since Supreme
Court agreed to consider lawsuit, edits to conform; picks up 5th graf,
`Ragsdale, of ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top state officials and the American Civil
Liberties Union said they made headway Monday toward settling a
lawsuit the state attorney general fears will be used by the U.S.
Supreme Court to restrict abortions.
   It was the first face-to-face meeting of the major figures in a
physician's lawsuit challenging state regulations for abortion
clinics since the Supreme Court agreed in July to consider Dr.
Richard Ragsdale's lawsuit.
   Attorney General Neil Hartigan, state public health chief Dr.
Bernard Turnock and ACLU attorney Colleen Connell agreed to meet
again next week to discuss the case.
   Neither Hartigan and Turnock, who are named as defendants in the
lawsuit by Dr. Richard Ragsdale of Rockford, nor Connell, who
represents the physician, would elaborate on Monday's meeting or
identify any obstacles to a settlement.
   Clinics that perform abortions contend the regulations are
unncecessary for patient safety. Ragsdale, of Rockford, operates an
abortion clinic.
   In March 1988, the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck down
the regulations, agreeing with a trial judge who said they would
force abortion clinics to become ``the functional equivalent of
small hospitals.''
   The state's appeal is one of three cases abortion-rights
activists fear the Supreme Court will use to severely limit
abortions. Anti-abortion activists fighting to overturn Roe vs.
Wade, the 1973 case that legalized abortion, wanted the high court
to consider the Illinois case.
   The Supreme Court is scheduled to take up the case in December.
   Hartigan, who is pro-choice, said Monday that he opposes ``the
idea of Illinois being used as a football for ... a much broader
decision.'' Hartigan, a Democrat who has announced he will run for
governor next year, said his defense of the abortion clinic rules
should not be viewed as an attempt to overturn Roe vs. Wade
``because that is not our intent.''
   Hartigan indicated the settlement talks are aimed at preventing
the Supreme Court from using the Ragsdale case to overturn Roe vs.
Wade.
   ``I don't think there's any question ... that in fact this case
... might be used for something else,'' he told reporters.
   At issue are state requirements for non-hospital surgical
centers. Ragsdale contends the requirements are medically
unnecessary and designed to discourage abortion providers by
forcing them to build ``the equivalent of a small hospital,'' an
expensive proposition.
   Requirements include 80-square-foot examining rooms,
250-square-foot surgical rooms, some corridor widths of 8 feet,
lounges, lockers and separate toilets for male and female
employees, and a janitor's closet adjoining surgical suites.
   In 1985, U.S. District Judge A. Nordberg certified the lawsuit
as a class action, thus suspending enforcement of the challenged
provisions for all Illinois doctors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 2119EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 2ndLd-Writethru a0644 10-16 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0644,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Free Of Technical And Legal Barriers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0776 to make it a 2nd Ld-Writethru, sted 1st
Ld-Writethru. SUBS grafs 7-10 with six grafs to UPDATE with security chief's
warning of alligators, wild hogs; and Department of Energy to have plutonium
detection equipment at center. Picks up 11th graf, `The mission...'. Spelling
of Lennard in 11th graf pvs is cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CSB2,4,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle Atlantis, freed
from technical and legal barriers, was declared ready for a Tuesday
launch with its nuclear-powered cargo. NASA said it expected
neither weather nor demonstrators to interfere.
   ``The vehicle is in good shape, the crew is ready to go fly and
the weather looks like we'll have a good chance to get airborne,''
NASA administrator Richard H. Truly said Monday. ``It's been a long
haul for this mission.''
   The launch from the seaside pad at the Kennedy Space Center is
scheduled for 12:57 p.m. EDT.
   Environmental activists, concerned that an accident could spread
nuclear poison into the atmosphere, demonstrated at a gate leading
to the Kennedy Space Center headquarters, and eight were arrested.
   ``This is just only the beginning of the government's plan to
use nuclear power and weapons in space, including in the Star Wars
program,'' said Jane Brown of the Florida Coalition for Peace and
Justice.
   The coalition is one of three groups that lost a suit to stop
the launch in U.S. District Court last week. A three-judge panel of
the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington upheld the judge Monday,
saying his ruling was not appealable.
   The protesters vowed to infiltrate a 30-by-10-mile security zone
and stop the launch. NASA had 200 armed security guards in the area
and there were sea and airborne patrols.
   The space center security chief said perhaps the best protection
is the natural barrier surrounding the launch pad.
   ``We have about 7,000 alligators there, I don't know how many
rattlesnakes, a lot of wild hogs, and probably millions of
mosquitoes,'' Gary Wistrand said.
   Galileo, weighing 6,700 pounds, will be released from Atlantis's
cargo bay 6{ hours after the ship is in orbit, the start of a
six-year, 2.4 billion-mile journey to Jupiter, the largest planet
in the solar system.
   Electricity to run the space probe will come from two nuclear
power packs, each loaded with 24.7 pounds of plutonium-238. NASA
has used such radioactive fuel on 22 previous flights. Three have
been involved in accidents, but no plutonium was released.
   The space agency said in court last week that detailed studies
show the chances of release of radioactive material are
statistically low and that the environmentalists' fears are
unwarranted.
   A large team of experts will be scattered around the center with
detection devices to sample the air in case there is an accident as
the shuttle lifts off. The Department of Energy will have an
airplane aloft and another 150 people standing by, said agency
spokesman Chris West.
   The mission was originally planned to begin in 1982, but was
delayed, first by money troubles and then by the explosion of the
space shuttle Challenger. The cost of the project to date is $1.5
billion, NASA said.
   ``Galileo's been a long time in coming and it's delightful to
sit here and be ready to fly,'' said Lennard Fisk, NASA's chief
scientist. ``These are very exciting times for space science in
general. Magellan is on its way to Venus, Voyager is on its way to
interstellar space having gone by Neptune, Galileo is sitting on
the pad and there is even more to come.''
   Astronaut Donald Williams is the commander of the crew of five.
The others are Mike McCulley, the pilot, and mission specialists
Shannon Lucid, Ellen Baker and Franklin Chang-Diaz.
   Their liftoff was scheduled for last Thursday, but one of the
shuttle's engine computers malfunctioned and had to be replaced.
The countdown for Tuesday's launch began at 12:01 a.m. Monday.
   In December 1995, a 737-pound probe is to be released from
Galileo and plunge into Jupiter's cloud layers to take the first
samples of the Jovian atmosphere.
   The main Galileo craft will enter an orbit around the planet,
and its cameras and 10 scientific instruments will gather
information on temperatures, magnetic fields, radiation, cloud
characteristics and gravity.
   Galileo also will study Jupiter for clues to the formation of
the solar system. Many scientists believe the planet still holds
much of the material, in its original state, from which the sun and
planets formed 4.6 billion years ago.
   Planners say the craft's examination of Jupiter will be the most
scientifically rich interplanetary mission yet. The pictures it
relays will be up to 1,000 times sharper than those obtained by the
Voyager spacecrafts.
   ``It is indeed a correct statement to make,'' said Fisk, ``that
this is the second golden age of space science for the United
States.''
</TEXT>
