<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0650 10-16 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Effort to Lay Stone For Temple Sparks Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7 pvs `Meanwhile, an ... the violence' with 7 grafs
to UPDATE with new settlement, no trial for reprimanded officer. Picks
up graf 8 pvs, `The plans ...' TRIMS thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN SCHECHET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Israelis tried to lay a cornerstone
for a new Jewish temple in Jerusalem's Old City on Monday, sparking
a riot by Palestinians that injured at least 20 people.
   Police barred the Jewish group from bringing the three-ton
cornerstone within the ancient city's walls, foiling an effort by
the Temple Mount Faithful movement to take a first step toward
rebuilding the temple destroyed in 70 A.D. by the Romans.
   High school students in Arab east Jerusalem, apparently enraged
at reports of the planned ceremony, threw rocks at police and
paramilitary border police.
   Fifteen Palestinian students and five policemen were reported
hurt in the melee, one of the most violent incidents in Jerusalem
during the 22-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule.
   At least 40 students were arrested, police said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, Jewish settlers dedicated a new
settlement on the ruins of Kefar Darom, a kibbutz overrun by the
Egyptian army in 1948.
   The new Kefar Darom is one of the eight new settlements approved
for construction this year. It joins 132 others already set up in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Near Jericho, Israeli soldiers prevented another group of
settlers from establishing still another settlement because they
failed to get permission, Israel radio said.
   Meanwhile, an 8-year-old Palestinian boy died Monday, three days
after he was shot by Israeli troops during a demonstration in the
occupied Gaza Strip. He was identified by the army as Qassem
Abdallah Abu Lubda of the Khan Yunis refugee camp.
   Abu Lubda's death raised to 596 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israeli soldiers or civilians since the uprising began in
December 1987. At least 130 Palestinians have been killed by fellow
Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating with Israel. Forty
Israelis have died in the violence.
   Also Monday, the national news agency Itim said the attorney
general ruled that an Israeli colonel reprimanded for ordering his
troops to break the limbs of Palestinian rioters will not be tried
in a civilian court.
   The official made the decision following an appeal by human
rights groups to try the officer. The attorney general said the
reprimand was sufficient and that the officer would be allowed to
remain in the army until he retires in three years, Itim reported.
   About 100 followers of the Temple Mount Faithful group had
planned to place the three-ton stone at the foot of a ramp leading
to the Temple Mount. Two of Islam's holiest shrines, the Al Aqsa
and Dome of the Rock mosques, sit atop the 35-acre mount.
   But police blocked the metallic gray truck carrying the
cornerstone from entering the Old City. They also prevented the
group from going up to the Temple Mount area.
   Gershon Salomon, the 53-year-old leader of the group, sat
cross-legged at the foot of the ramp. He sang Israeli folk songs
and promised to return daily until the cornerstone was allowed
inside the Old City.
   ``They will throw stones, and we will put up cornerstones here
on the Temple Mount,'' Salomon said. He vowed to place a second
stone for the new temple during the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah in
December.
   The demonstrators were largely ignored by thousands of Israelis
and tourists making the traditional pilgrimage to the Western Wall,
the sole remnant of the Second Temple, during the eight-day Jewish
Sukkot holiday.
</TEXT>
