<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     10-16 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Christians Demand Faster Syrian Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian legislators from Lebanon
pushed Monday for a quicker withdrawal of Syrian troops than Arab
mediators have proposed, sources said at a peace conference in this
city.
   They demanded written guarantees that Syria withdraw its 40,000
troops from Lebanon altogether after an initial pullback from the
capital to the eastern Bekaa Valley, the sources said on condition
of anonymity.
   The lawmakers also said the first withdrawal should be made
faster than the two years proposed by Arab mediators, the sources
reported.
   In Beirut, Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun said the 63 members
of Lebanon's parliament gathered in Taif, a Saudi resort, must not
``weaken their demand for the withdrawal of the occupation army.''
   The Christian deputies' position was contained in a memorandum
handed to Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal. He relayed
its contents to King Fahd.
   The Saudi monarch late Monday chaired a Cabinet meeting to
discuss the document, but few details were released afterwards.
   Saudi Arabia is hosting the conference that began Sept. 30 in an
effort to end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war and the latest round
of violence between Syrian and allied Moslem fighters and Christian
forces.
   Syria sent troops to Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. However, Aoun says the Syrians have violated
that mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   The Syrian pullout is being debated as part of a peace plan that
would give more power to Lebanon's Moslems.
