<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-USBases     10-16 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US Bases,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filipino Lawmakers Pass Bill for Vote on U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lower house unanimously approved
a bill late Monday allowing Filipinos to vote whether to allow the
United States to keep its military bases in this country.
   The move was seen as an effort to counter opposition to the
bases in the Philippines Senate. However, the upper chamber of
Congress must now vote on the referendum bill, which a majority of
senators opposes.
   U.S. and Filipino negotiators began talks in Manila in December
on extending the lease on Clark Air Base, the Subic Bay naval base
and four smaller installations after the current agreement expires
in September 1991.
   Any agreement must be ratified by two-thirds of the 23-member
Senate. Twelve senators say they oppose any extension. Most
surveys, however, show a majority of Filipinos support the bases.
   In its unanimous decision Monday, the 199-member House of
Representatives approved a proposal by Deputy Speaker Antonio
Cuenco for a national referendum within 60 days of completion of
talks on a new bases agreement.
   Under the House bill, results of the referendum would be
non-binding. But political analysts say a strong vote in favor of
the bases would put political pressure on the Senate to approve an
extension.
   ``The best way to give the people the opportunity to participate
in the resolution of the issue is to submit the same in a
referendum to clearly reflect the choice and thus guide the
government in its decision on the matter,'' Cuenco said in his
proposal.
   On Friday, President Corazon Aquino told ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning, America'' that the public should be consulted before the
Senate decides the issue.
   U.S. officials say the bases contribute about $1 billion a year
to the Philippine economy through salaries to local workers,
purchases from local suppliers and spending by 40,000 troops,
military dependents and civilian employees.
   However, opponents of the bases have been riding a wave of
anti-Americanism.
</TEXT>
