<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Military     10-16 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Military,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Military Official Denies Diverting US Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces chief Monday
denied a published report that he sold military equipment donated
by the United States and deposited the income in an account he
controlled.
   ``Those press reports are totally false,'' Gen. Humberto
Regalado Hernandez told The Associated Press by telephone.
``Apparently it is a crude and vulgar press campaign against the
armed forces.''
   He called a meeting of the armed forces general staff ``to
analyze the serious accusations presented by The New York Times,
which damage me personally and also all our armed institution.''
   The Times, citing high-ranking Honduran officers who want to see
the general replaced, reported Sunday that Regalado had sold
donated U.S. military equipment to the Honduran military and
deposited the proceeds in a special account he controlled.
   The newspaper said many of the officers, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, were among Regalado's most loyal supporters until
they discovered the arms deals.
   The Times said Honduras has asked the U.S. Defense Department to
investigate corruption complaints against Regalado because of a
possible congressional cutoff of military aid to the country.
   ``It's a wild tale against me,'' Regalado said. ``I don't
control one cent of those funds. I live from my salary, and I am
not rich.''
   His official salary is believed to be about $5,000 a month.
   Regalado, 50, has been chief of the armed forces since January
1987.
   The United States began increasing military aid to Honduras
after the leftist Sandinistas came to power in Nicaragua. Military
aid for 1989 was $41.1 million, and $61.3 million is planned for
1990.
