<FIRST>u i AM-PLO-Peace 1stLd-Writethru a0731 10-16 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Peace, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Says No to U.S. Peace Plan Because PLO is Left Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with U.S. comment. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO officials rejected the Middle East
peace plan of Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Monday
because it excludes their organization.
   Diplomats in Baghdad said the Palestine Liberation Organization
position also represented a rejection of a peace plan put forth by
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
   In a final declaration after two days of meetings, the PLO
Central Council said only the PLO had the right to decide what
Palestinians should talk to Israel.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler
urged the PLO to authorize talks with Israel ``if we are ever to
get the (negotiating) process off the ground.''
   Baker's plan does not mention the PLO and Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir of Israel has rejected PLO participation in talks about
elections in the Israeli-occupied territories. Israel views the PLO
as a terrorist group.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the Bush administration was not fazed by
Shamir's criticism of its strategy. She said Baker would keep
working with foreign ministers Moshe Arens of Israel and Esmet
Abdel-Meguid of Egypt to get negotiations started.
   ``The PLO and the PLO alone has the right to name the
Palestinian side to any talks with Israel, whether they be
Palestinians inside the occupied territories or outside,'' the PLO
Central Council declaration said Monday.
   The council acts as an intermediary between the policy-making
Palestine National Council and the PLO Executive Committee.
   Its declaration accused Washington of ignoring the PLO as the
``sole legitimate representative'' of the Palestinians and said the
American proposals were only a version of the Israeli plan.
   It said Palestinian-Israeli peace talks proposed recently by the
United States and Egypt could only be preliminary, leading to an
international peace conference under U.N. auspices.
   Sheik Abdel-Hamid Sayeh, chairman of the Palestine National
Council, said: ``There has been a clearcut and overwhelming
opposition to the new American move by all participants'' in the
meetings.
   The 80-seat Central Council convened to unify positions on U.S.,
Israeli and Egyptian peace proposals.
   Sayeh stopped short of specifically criticizing Mubarak's plan,
which also did not mention the PLO.
   ``The general consensus is that the Baker proposals are a new
formula to sell the Shamir plan,'' he said.
   Shamir proposed in May that elections be held in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip to allow Palestinians to choose their own
representatives under a plan for limited self-rule. He ruled out an
Israeli withdrawal and recognition of a Palestinian state.
   Mubarak proposed a modified 10-point election plan under which
Israel would accept the idea of trading land for peace and hold
direct talks with the Palestinians, which he proposed be held in
Cairo.
   Baker later invited the foreign ministers of Egypt and Israel to
preliminary talks in Washington.
   On Monday, the Central Council said the PLO would reject all
plans other than its own, which it urged Arabs to accept.
   Arab diplomatic sources said the reference to Arab countries was
meant as a rejection of the Mubarak plan, although the declaration
did not mention it.
   Yasser Abed-Rabbo of the PLO Executive Committee, the main
negotiator in a PLO-U.S. dialogue initiated in December, has said
the PLO accepts the concept of face-to-face negotiations with
Israel provided it is allowed to choose the delegates.
   Radical Palestinian leaders George Habash and Nayef Hawatmeh had
pushed for outright condemnation of the Egyptian and U.S. plans.
</TEXT>
