<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-16 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Arrives as Sri Lanka Violences Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Red Cross team arrived Monday to
help trace missing people and provide humanitarian aid on this
island nation where 13 more deaths from a Sinhalese uprising were
reported.
   The Red Cross team came from Switzerland after an invitation
last week from President Ranasinghe Premadasa.
   He invited the team following charges by opposition politicians
that pro-government death squads were killing sympathizers of an
underground group trying to overthrow the government.
   The government has denied the charge. It blames the People's
Liberation Front, the ultranationalist Sinhalese group that
advocates overthrowing the government, for most of the 5,000
killings the past two years.
   Human rights activists and opposition politicians welcomed
Premadasa's invitation to the Red Cross. But some said they feared
it was prompted by economic concerns, noting that major Western aid
donors are to meet in Paris this week to consider Sri Lanka's $750
million request for foreign help.
   Members of the four-member Red Cross team from Geneva refused to
speak to reporters. Their duties are expected to include visiting
detention centers.
   Also Monday, the government said its troops shot and killed two
Sinhalese extremists who tried to escape arrest in Matara, 85 miles
southeast of Colombo.
   Other killings reported the previous 24 hours included two
Sinhalese youths whose bodies were found in Kandy, 55 miles east of
Colombo.
   Nine Sinhalese civilians died in three separate attacks by
Sinhalese extremists in southern and central Sri Lanka, a
government communique said.
   It also said two Sinhalese Buddhist monks had been abducted by
unknown gunmen.
   The People's Liberation Front has accused the
Sinhalese-dominated government of giving too many concessions to
members of the Tamil minority, whose own ethnic war has claimed
11,000 lives since the Tamil separatist insurrection began in 1983.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, make up 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise
18 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
