<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--USSRoberts     10-16 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--USS Roberts,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repaired Frigate Returned to Navy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Samuel B. Roberts, a
guided-missile frigate that nearly sank last year after striking a
mine in the Persian Gulf, was returned to the Navy in a ceremony
Monday.
   The ceremony was held aboard the ship at Bath Iron Works'
shipyard.
   The 3,700-ton ship, which was built by the shipyard, ran into
the mine while escorting an oil tanker through the Persian Gulf
during the Iran-Iraq war. The explosion ripped a 9-foot hole in the
frigate's bottom and a 21-foot-long crack in the side.
   The Navy is tentatively scheduled to take the Roberts to its
home port of Newport, R.I., next Monday. The ship then will go to
the Caribbean for a year of ocean exercises.
   The 13 months of repairs cost about $37.5 million, $3.5 million
less than budgeted, officials said.
</TEXT>
