<DOCNO> AP891016-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Israel-Lebanese Adv23   10-16 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanese, Adv 23,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs Oct. 23 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands of Lebanese Cross into Israel Daily to Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTY KUFUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>METULLA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every working day, nearly 2,000 Lebanese
pass through four ``Good Fence'' border crossings on their way to
jobs in Israel.
   In doing so, these Lebanese Christians, Moslems and Druse
contribute to Israel's security and are a sign of growing ties
between Israel and southern Lebanon, where the Israelis have
established a security zone.
   Israeli analysts said the loyalty of the 200,000 Lebanese
residents of the security zone, created as a buffer against
Palestinian and Lebanese Moslem militias, would weaken if
widespread unemployment took hold in the area.
   ``The security zone is relatively quiet mainly because of the
sense that economic stability prevails. There's too much for the
people to lose,'' said Yosef Olmert, a Middle East expert at Tel
Aviv University.
   An Israeli army official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said a requirement for entry for Lebanese workers was having a
relative serving in the South Lebanon Army, a 2,500-member
Christian-led militia that is trained and armed by Israel to help
defend the frontier.
   The security zone is about 75 miles long and 2{ to 12 miles
deep. It was established in 1985 after Israel withdrew from Lebanon
following a three-year occupation. So far this year, 71 guerrillas
infiltrating the zone have been killed.
   Metulla's ``Good Fence'' is a cluster of buildings, a watchtower
and a fence next to an Israeli army post. Workers show identity
cards, present work permits and empty their pockets in a check for
contraband.
   ``We all are running away from the war in Lebanon, and we are
here to work,'' Nadeen Badawi, 23, said after driving from the
Druse town of Hasbaya, 11 miles north of the border.
   Arriving about sunrise, he works Sunday through Friday at an
Israeli textile factory.
   Awaiting a chartered bus to another factory, a 48-year-old
Lebanese Christian said most of the workers earn the equivalent of
$17 a day.
   ``Most of the men are working in agriculture. A few, like me,
work in factories,'' said the former electronics technician who
declined to give his name for fear of reprisals.
   Some Lebanese complained the Israeli wages are too low but most
conceded they could do no better in Lebanon, where purchasing power
has been steadily eroded by inflation and the average monthly wage
is the equivalent of $75.
   Israeli officials say 1,500 to 2,000 Lebanese workers now enter
the country daily compared to only a few hundred in past years.
   Half are women who work in hotels, restaurants and as
housekeepers.
   Men generally take jobs in factories or on farms, where extra
money can be made during harvests. Skilled automobile mechanics are
also in demand. Most return home nightly, but some are provided
with housing for stays of up to several weeks.
   Israel provided about $1.3 million for road repairs last year in
southern Lebanon, in addition to funds for schools and hospitals
and salary supplements for city hall bureaucrats and police.
   ``In areas where the central government in Lebanon should have
built infrastructure and promoted social activity and education,
and didn't take care of it, we are taking care of it,'' said Uri
Lubrani, Israel's coordinator for Lebanon policy.
   He recently opened a new crossing primarily for Shiite Moslems.
   Although Iran has a strong influence among the Shiites, Lubrani
predicted 300 to 400 would cross daily and that the number would
increase.
   The Israeli shekel currency also has begun to circulate in
southern Lebanon along with the U.S. dollar and the Lebanese lira.
   Frances Rizk, a Lebanese official of the Christian Voice of Hope
radio, estimated trade at $2 million a month, with Israel providing
agricultural products and the Lebanese providing labor.
   ``Our financial situation is still the best in all of Lebanon,''
Rizk said.
   Officials say Israel would withdraw if Syria pulled out its
40,000 troops out of Lebanon and a government was established in
Beirut that could maintain peace throughout the country.
   ``Israel has no territorial claims on Lebanon,'' said Yossi
Amihud, the Foreign Ministry spokesman. Israel's concern is
``preventing the organization of terror and the use of Lebanese
territory for acts against Israel,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday PMs Oct. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
