<SECOND>BC-History, Adv22,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Oct. 22, the 295th day of 1989. There are 70
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Oct. 22, 1962, President Kennedy went on radio and television
to announce he had ordered U.S. air and naval forces to blockade
Cuba, following the discovery of Soviet missile bases on the
island. Kennedy demanded the Soviets dismantle the rocket sites.
   On this date:
   In 1746, Princeton University in New Jersey received its charter.
   In 1811, Hungarian composer Franz Liszt was born in Raiding.
   In 1836, Sam Houston was inaugurated as the first
constitutionally elected president of the Republic of Texas.
   In 1883, the original Metropolitan Opera House in New York held
its grand opening. The first opera performed at the Met was
Gounod's ``Faust.''
   In 1928, President Hoover made a speech in which he spoke of the
``American system of rugged individualism.''
   In 1934, bank robber Charles ``Pretty Boy'' Floyd was shot to
death by federal agents at a farm in East Liverpool, Ohio.
   In 1954, West Germany joined the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   In 1978, negotiators for Egypt and Israel announced in
Washington they had reached a tentative agreement on the main
points of a peace treaty.
   In 1981, the Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization
was decertified by the federal government for its strike in August.
   In 1986, Jane Dornacker, a traffic reporter for WNBC radio in
New York, was killed when the helicopter she was in crashed into
the Hudson River.
   Ten years ago: The U.S. government allowed the deposed Shah of
Iran to travel to New York for medical treatment _ a decision that
would precipitate the Iran hostage crisis two weeks later.
   Five years ago: A day after their second debate, President
Reagan and Democrat Walter F. Mondale both claimed victory in the
confrontation, and predicted eventual victory.
   One year ago: The 100th Congress adjourned after an
early-morning session that produced sweeping legislation to combat
drug abuse in America.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Joan Fontaine is 72. Sen. John
Chafee, R-R.I., is 67. Actor Christopher Lloyd is 51. Actor Derek
Jacobi is 51. Actor Tony Roberts is 50. Actress Annette Funicello
is 47. Actress Catherine Deneuve is 46. Actor Jeff Goldblum is 37.
   Thought for Today: ``If there is no hell, a good many preachers
are obtaining money under false pretenses.'' _Attributed to William
A. ``Billy'' Sunday, American baseball player turned evangelist
(1862-1935).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Sunday, Oct. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
