<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv23   10-16 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv23,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Oct. 23, the 296th day of 1989. There are 69
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Oct. 23, 1983, 241 U.S. Marines and sailors in Lebanon died
in an explosion caused by a suicide truck-bomber who crashed into
the U.S. compound at Beirut International Airport. An almost
simultaneous attack on French forces in the Lebanese capital
claimed the lives of 58 paratroopers.
   On this date:
   In 1864, forces led by Union General Samuel R. Curtis defeated
Confederate General Stirling Price's army in Missouri.
   In 1910, Blanche S. Scott became the first woman to make a solo
public airplane flight, reaching an altitude of 12 feet as she
sailed across a park in Fort Wayne, Ind.
   In 1915, 25,000 women marched in New York City, demanding the
right to vote.
   In 1942, during World War II, Britain launched a major offensive
against Axis forces at El Alamein, Egypt.
   In 1946, the United Nations General Assembly convened in New
York for the first time, at an auditorium in Flushing Meadow.
   In 1947, Screen Actors Guild President Ronald Reagan told the
House Un-American Activities Committee the best way to combat
communist influence in Hollywood was ``to make democracy work.''
   In 1956, an anti-Stalinist revolt that was subsequently crushed
by Soviet troops began in Hungary.
   In 1958, Soviet poet and novelist Boris Pasternak, author of
``Doctor Zhivago,'' won the Nobel Prize in literature. However,
Kremlin authorities pressured Pasternak into relinquishing the
award.
   In 1973, in a surprising reversal, President Nixon agreed to
turn White House tape recordings requested by the Watergate special
prosecutor over to Judge John J. Sirica.
   In 1978, China and Japan exchanged treaty ratification documents
in Tokyo, formally ending four decades of hostility between the two
Asian powers.
   In 1980, Soviet Premier Alexei N. Kosygin, a fixture in the top
Soviet leadership for 16 years, resigned his post because of
illness.
   In 1987, the Senate rejected, 58-42, the Supreme Court
nomination of Robert H. Bork.
   Ten years ago: Six human rights activists in Czechoslovakia,
including dramatist Vaclav Havel, received prison sentences of up
to five years after a hasty trial in which all six were convicted
of subversive activities.
   Five years ago: ``NBC Nightly News'' aired British Broadcasting
Corporation footage of the drought in Ethiopia, resulting in an
outpouring of charitable contributions.
   One year ago: Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and the Rev. Jesse Jackson
accused Republican George Bush of injecting race into the
presidential campaign by focusing on prison escapee Willie Horton _
a charge a Bush spokesman labeled ``absolutely ridiculous.''
   Today's Birthdays: ``Tonight Show'' host Johnny Carson is 64.
Senator John Heinz, R-Penn., is 51. Soccer great Pele is 49. Author
and movie director Michael Crichton is 47. Parodist ``Weird Al''
Yankovic is 30. Football player Doug Flutie is 27.
   Thought for Today: ``Truth is not introduced into the individual
from without, but was within him all the time.'' _Soren
Kierkegaard, Danish philosopher (1813-1855).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Monday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
