<FIRST>s i BC-OverseasChinese-Home Adv22   10-16 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Overseas Chinese-Home, Adv 22,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Area in Southern China Thrives on Help from Overseas Chinese</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Overseas Chinese, b0506-b0507</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIANGMEN, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing larger than life in front of the
Chenjinglun Middle School is a white marble statue of a man in a
three-piece suit.
   The $13,000 statue is of Chen Jinglun, a native son of Xinhui
county who built the school with part of the fortune he made as a
rice merchant in nearby Hong Kong.
   Behind the statue is an Olympic-size swimming pool, a gymnasium
and classrooms filled with bright-eyed students, some hunched over
expensive computerized typewriters _ all far more advanced that the
usual Chinese school.
   ``To show respect to Mr. Chen, the local government and people
of Xinhui named the school after him,'' said Guan Yunjin, the
school president. ``The love from Mr. Chen is very precious.''
   Chen's largesse is just one example of the historically strong
ties between Chinese who move abroad and their motherland _ in
particular this coastal region of southern China, which is the
ancestral home to hundreds of thousands of overseas Chinese.
   Jiangmen, a region in the Pearl River delta, prides itself as
the ``hometown of overseas Chinese.'
   A main reason for the world-wandering ways of Jiangmen Chinese
has to do with the region's proximity to Hong Kong, the British
colony from which shipping lines lead to all corners of the globe.
   About 2.58 million Chinese living in 95 countries, Hong Kong and
the nearby Portuguese territory of Macao trace their roots to
Jiangmen. Many of them return to visit relatives, to donate money
for social services or to invest in local enterprises.
   In nearby Taishan country, a bridge has been built with $940,000
in contributions from native Chinese now living abroad. Springing
up throughout the countryside are three- and four-story villas
built by overseas Chinese for relatives still here.
   A museum with pictures of Chinese in the California Gold Rush of
1849 also has a list of about 100 local schools that have received
donations from Chinese abroad.
   Feng Yuanchao, director of a local Foreign Affairs Office, runs
down the list of North American cities where his kin can be found _
Vancouver, Seattle, Toronto and Chicago.
   As he drives past rice fields in his small van, he points to a
village of low, gray-brick homes in the distance.
   ``That village has sent many people to Chicago,'' he says. ``If
you meet a Chinese in Chicago's Chinatown, the chances are 60
percent'' he is from the town.
   Some overseas Chinese come back for more than a visit.
   One is Tommy Quan, 56, who left Taishan in 1949, when the
Chinese Communists came to power. He made Seattle his home and
became a successful businessman.
   But when he returned in the early 1980s, he found the land
barren. ``I kept asking myself, `Why don't people do something
about it?'''
   Quan did. He established a 400-acre orange orchard that now
employs about 150 people. He spent seven months in China this year
and will spend almost half of 1990 to see his business through its
first critical years.
   Local officials are appreciative of efforts by Quan and other
overseas Chinese to help the Jiangmen area blossom and seem
unconcerned about the possibility of contamination by ``bourgeois
liberalization,'' the Communist term for unwanted liberal Western
influences.
   ``I'll put it this way,'' said Guan, the school president.
``Wherever they go, the Chinese love their hometown and country.
When they get rich they won't forget their country or hometown.
This is one of the merits of the Chinese people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 22</NOTE>
