<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   She came out of grief for her lost husband,
soothed by music, and now she has returned the favor. On Friday her
Philharmonic Center for the Arts opens and she and her community
are the richer.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In her new career as a fund-raiser for the arts,
Myra Daniels tried to sell bricks for the new Philharmonic Center
for the Arts in Naples, Fla., for $100 apiece.
   ``We bought saturation TV ads; that's the way we were taught to
sell soap,'' says the former advertising executive. So she got
before camera and said, ``A wonderful thing is happening in this
community and we want you to be a part of it.''
   The bricks were not a hit, but a little boy recognized her in a
grocery store and asked how much a brick cost. ``I asked how much
he had. $1.29. I took $1.19 without any shame. That kid is a part
of the building.
   ``The arts need advertising. You've got a product here and you
have to sell it,'' Myra Daniels says firmly.
   She adds: ``I believe more top business people should be CEOs of
arts organizations. You can run the arts as a business. You can
remain in the black. You can do anything if you have the funds to
do it and the knowledge to move it.''
   The fact that the $19.4 million Philharmonic Center for the Arts
will open in Naples, Fla., on Friday, debt-free, is a tribute to
Mrs. Daniels acting on her belief and her 33 years of advertising
experience.
   She put an ad in the local newspaper with a coupon to cut out
and mail in a check of a minimum donation of $1,000. The publisher
phoned and said she should save her $1,700 for the ad; people with
$1,000 to donate don't clip coupons out of newspapers. She said she
wanted it to run.
   Five hundred and eight coupons and $2.2 million came in. They
wouldn't buy $100 bricks, but they'd clip coupons for 10 times that
much. It says something about the economic level of Naples, Fla.,
residents.
   ``There are more blue chip corporation CEOs retired in our area
than anywhere else,'' Mrs. Daniels says. However, some of them have
informed her that they've also retired from supporting arts
organizations.
   The center, on 6{ acres, contains 1,221-seat Frances Pew Hayes
Hall, 300-seat Myra Daniels Pavilion, four museum galleries and an
outdoor sculpture garden. The board wanted to name it all for Mrs.
Daniels. She, as board president, vetoed it.
   The center will present 200 events in the first season. Tickets
are sold singly or in subscription groups such as for three
evenings by the Miami City Ballet, four orchestral concerts or five
jazz programs.
   Mrs. Daniels added a line on the order form: ``I want
everything, $1,695.'' Two hundred people marked that.
   ``We know our break-even point is 70 percent of the hall filled.
We know we'll do better than that.''
   It all started with something even smaller than a dream to build
a performing arts center in an area of Florida that didn't have
one. It started with grief and a reaching out for the soothing,
healing properties of music.
   The year, 1965, that Myra Janco of Chicago was named ad woman of
the year by the Advertising Federation of America, she met Draper
Daniels when he came to her office to buy her advertising agency.
He, chairman of the board of his agency, named her president. They
married in 1967. ``He was an advertising genius,'' she says. ``He
fathered the Marlboro Man, the Jolly Green Giant in the Valley and
`Sorry, Charlie,' for Starkist Tuna.''
   In 1978, they retired to Marco Island, Fla. Daniels died in
1983, after a four-year illness. His widow took personal inventory.
She knew, after concentrating so long on nursing and then grieving,
that she needed to rejoin the world. ``I'm not very good on a
tennis court any more. I never was good on a golf course. I thought
about going back to Chicago.
   ``I went to a concert by 12 people, in a church in Naples.
There's a sound of live music that mesmerizes you.''
   She invited a friend, state Rep. Mary Ellen Hawkins, to go with
her. ``She said, `I hate amateur music.' I said: `Not as much as I
do. We'll sit by the door. If it's bad, we'll sneak out.'
   ``The man running it spoke to Mary Ellen at intermission and
said they owed money. She said, `Myra will help you.'''
   Mrs. Daniels was not pleased then but says now, ``She pushed me
and gave me the greatest gift.''
   That's how this 63-year-old with a marketing Ph.D. from Indiana
University got back in action. Reluctantly. She invited the
concert-givers to her home the next morning, to give them advice
and send them away. She remembers:
   ``I didn't want to get mixed up with a volunteer group but you
have to help your community. I told them, `You can't play again
unless you have $100,000 in the bank.' They were going concert by
concert.
   ``I said they needed a telephone campaign. They didn't know how.
I said I'd test it for a week, thinking I'd get them out of my
hair. You put a red dot by every so many names in the phone book,
which gives you a random statistical response for the community. I
decided I wouldn't call anyone I knew. They'd be nice to the poor
little widow.''
   One person she called was Frances Pew Hayes from Philadelphia
who said she had already gone through her donation budget, but
``I'll give you twenty-five.'' When the check came it was for
$25,000. Mrs. Daniels says: ``Within a week, I got $100,000. They
thought I could walk on water. They wouldn't let me go.''
   So, Mrs. Daniels, who had had childhood piano lessons and loved
music, thought the next step should be an orchestra instead of 10
amateur and two professional players. ``I started buying musicians.
I worked on the idea that you find fine principal players and let
them build up their sections. We went to 38.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
