<FIRST>s e BC-APN--ArtsAdvertiser Adv29-1stAdd   10-16 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Arts Advertiser, Adv 29-1st Add,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: to 38.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   She invited Mrs. Hayes, whose acquaintance she had made by that
time made, to the first concert, in a high school. ``She said,
`You'll never get any better unless you have a hall of your own.' I
thought, `Is the woman crazy?' She said, `I'll buy the land so
you'll have it when you're ready to build.'
   ``The next morning I put on boots and went to the boondocks,
looking at land. Then, I thought, `Why don't I put her money in
escrow and look for land that could be donated to us.' Westinghouse
Communities of Naples gave us the majority of the land.''
   Then came fund raising for a hall for the symphony _ stabilized
at 70 members _ which became two halls under one roof. ``I don't
feel I'm asking anyone for money. I'm giving them the chance to
build the future civilization of this part of the country and an
opportunity to make their lives better.
   ``I gained 40 pounds. We would bring people to suppers and tell
our story. I have been to more Rotary and Optimist clubs. I go
anyplace people want to hear about this. I say: `Ladies and
gentlemen, it's a matter of money. If you want Itzhak Perlman to
play here...''' The acclaimed violinist is booked for a recital
Feb. 5.
   ``I was a brunette when I started this project. Maybe I'll be a
brunette again if I ever get time to go to the beauty parlor,''
Mrs. Daniels says, touching her gray hair.
   ``I never sit at intermissions. I'm up and many times I'm
collecting funds. I met Curtiss E. Frank, who was vice chairman of
Dun and Bradstreet, at an intermission. He has given $2.28 million.
The foyer will be named for him.''
   Mrs. Daniels wrote a proposal that brought in $3.5 million from
the state, got donations of concrete, windows and marble from near
Naples, Italy. Hugh De Pree, then president of furniture-maker
Herman Miller Inc., told her she could go to his Michigan company
and choose concert chairs and office furniture. He didn't know her
well, she says. She chose the best.
   A retired conductor who intended to give his library to a
university saw the center being built and donated it there. One man
is giving his collection of vintage movies.
   Mrs. Daniels moved from Marco Island to Naples so she could walk
to work and says: ``I don't feel any less juices than I did when I
was a 24-year-old kid going out to conquer the world in
advertising. I'm happy, I guess because I'm in control of what I
can do. You can be a sweet little old lady widow having everyone
feel sorry for you and invite you to dinner parties once in a while
or you can do something for the place you're in.
   ``Dan was a great one to share a great deal of himself; I used
to think we should have more private time. When he was dying and in
and out of a coma, one day he said, `Myra, don't ever forget, every
private person has a public responsibility,' and he went off again.
   ``Damn you, Dan, I've done it now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
