<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1607EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Nicaragua-Campaign Adv22   10-16 1151</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nicaragua-Campaign, Adv 22,1192</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Running Well-Organized for Presidential Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knocking on doors in the early
evening, just before people settle down to watch soap operas
imported from Brazil, the polite campaign workers ask citizens how
they are going to vote in Nicaragua's presidential election.
   Then they make a smooth pitch for the FSLN _ the Sandinista
National Liberation Front, which has run the country since 1979.
   At a news conference on a sunny morning at the foreign
correspondents' club, President Daniel Ortega answers questions
with quotable, well-rehearsed phrases in his quest for re-election.
   Afterwards, everyone is handed a yellow T-shirt with ``Daniel
Presidente'' on the front and ``Vota Por FSLN'' (Vote For the FSLN)
in back. Pinned to each shirt is the name of the recipient, neatly
written in ink on a square of paper.
   If Nicaragua's presidential election Feb. 25 hinges on
organization, party discipline and attention to detail, the
Sandinistas have a decided edge at this stage of the campaign.
   Their main challenger, a coalition called the National
Opposition Union, has been relying on rallies, campaign appearances
and the newspaper La Prensa, published by its presidential
candidate, Violeta Barrios de Chamarro.
   ``Nobody's going to vote for Dona Violeta because of a
T-shirt,'' said Antonio Lacayo, Mrs. Chamorro's son-in-law and
campaign manager.
   In contrast to the Sandinistas, the opposition is fractured into
20 parties, 12 of them supporting Mrs. Chamorro. The Sandinistas
have more and better television ads, a neighborhood organization
that knows the registration status of every household and the power
and patronage of a governing party.
   The Sandinistas have painted walls with red and black signs
reading ``Daniel'' or ``FSLN.''
   The opposition's most pervasive slogans are white painted
graffiti that read ``UNO equals Democracy.'' UNO are the Spanish
initials of the opposition coalition.
   ``Our resources don't allow us great projects,'' said Lacayo,
who is taking six months off from running a company that produces
cooking oil.
   Lacayo denies Sandinista accusations that $5 million has entered
Nicaragua secretly to finance the opposition. He said UNO has
received only meager donations from exiled Nicaraguans, along with
a few loudspeakers, three tape-recorders, batteries and an
electricity generator.
   But he said he isn't worried.
   ``UNO's most important tasks now are to make sure the voter
registration stations are well watched ... and to make people lose
their fear,'' he said.
   Fear indeed is evident.
   ``We'd better not talk about that. Why look for problems?'' said
a 72-year-old woman when asked what she thought of the opposition.
Like other potential voters, she talked to a reporter only on
condition that her name not be used.
   Four Sundays in October were set aside for voter registration.
Reporters who surveyed registration posts found UNO and other
opposition party representatives at about half of them; the
Sandinistas were represented at all of those surveyed. An estimated
1.9 million people are eligible to register.
   ``We have 40,000 militants (workers),'' said the Sandinista
campaign manager, Bayardo Arce. ``We don't think the problem here
is money. What is important is the work we do house by house.''
   In a country where no single radio or TV station reaches the
whole country, and where most people can't read, don't have access
to or just plain can't afford a newspaper, the surest way to reach
each voter is face-to-face.
   With 40,000 workers, the Sandinistas have one worker for every
40 voters expected to register. Lacayo says UNO has 16,000
sympathizers nationwide who help with rallies and encourage people
to vote for UNO.
   In one lower-class Managua neighborhood, a housewife and mother
of two said Sandinista campaign workers had come three times to her
house. She has seen no sign of the opposition.
   ``The first time they asked us to register,'' said the woman.
``Then they came again and said `You're going to vote for the
Sandinista Front, right?'
   ``I said sure. I'm not going to argue with these people. But I
told them everything is too expensive and the government is
responsible. They said it was the fault of Yankee aggression.''
   That doesn't mean she will vote for Mrs. Chamorro.
   ``That woman doesn't know anything about anything,'' the woman
said.
   The 72-year-old woman said Sandinista workers came by her house
in August.
   ``I told them I needed reading glasses because I don't have
money to buy them,'' she said. ``They wrote my name down and said
they would get me some.''
   The woman was amused when asked if she got the glasses.
   ``Look,'' she relied, ``these people have been promising us
everything for 10 years. And what have they given us?''
   While the Sandinistas knock on doors, UNO has marches.
   ``Ortega, tyrant! Your time is coming near!'' is a UNO chant
heard frequently.
   The campaign on television, although less important, is another
contrast. The opposition is given 30 minutes a night, divided up
among nine candidates so UNO gets 10 minutes every three nights.
   The UNO ads show speakers assailing the Sandinista government's
economic performance _ the country's economy is the most depressed
in the hemisphere, according to some experts.
   The Sandinistas' time on TV is virtually unlimited, and their
ads, produced in Mexico, sometimes appear during the most popular
of the Brazilian soap operas on the state-owned television.
   ``This is a David and Goliath confrontation,'' said a UNO
campaign source who requested anonymity. ``We can't fight like
Goliath, so we've got to save our one shot for when it counts _ and
then hit with all our might.''
   He added that the coalition was holding off its main effort
until the final stretch.
   ``Money isn't everything. Even with all the money the gringos
can give, the human material is not here,'' he said.
   The people who have the organizational skills to make a party
work have fled to the United States in the 10 years since the
Sandinistas toppled dictator Anastasio Somoza, the source said.
   With their advantage as the government party, the Sandinistas
have been trying to co-opt sectors that have threatened to drift
away because of the economic crisis.
   Nationwide wildcat strikes by teachers last March were the first
serious labor unrest this year, after Ortega announced a tough
austerity program in January to combat runaway inflation. Ortega
granted a 40 percent pay raise and the teachers fell back into line.
   Next came a strike by taxi drivers, who protested a doubling of
gasoline prices. The government started distributing new
Soviet-made Lada cars to replace a fleet of old, broken-down
U.S.-made cars.
   The Sandinistas got 64 percent of the vote in the last election,
in November 1984, and Arce says they will be pleased if they can do
as well again.
   ``Any percentage above 60 percent is good, and will push the
revolutionary process forward,'' Arce said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
