<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--BoyGeorge Adv27-29   10-16 1192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Boy George, Adv 27-29,1225</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 27-29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The New, Improved Boy George</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boy George, the androgynous former president
of Culture Club, is trying to climb back up the pop charts after
surviving the crushing downers of heroin addiction and the overdose
deaths of two friends.
   ``I'm totally relaxed about my life,'' he says, declaring a new
state of mind. ``I'm totally relaxed about what I am and what I do
and what I feel.''
   Boy George has come to the United States on a temporary visa,
the first time he has been allowed to do so since his 1986
conviction for heroin possession in England.
   The conviction, which led to the disintegration of the
hit-making Culture Club one year later, forced the singer into a
rehabilitation program. Treatment was complicated by the
drug-related deaths of two close friends, one at Boy George's
London mansion.
   During a recent visit to Los Angeles, Boy George _ whose real
name is George O'Dowd _ described himself as happy and healthy,
with an understanding that life isn't always perfect.
   ``I think a lot of the things that happen to me are
self-created,'' he said. ``There are still days when I get out of
the bed on the wrong side and everything goes wrong. That happens
to all of us.''
   His current solo album, ``High Hat,'' was released to favorable
reviews earlier this year but didn't get much airplay in this
country. He hopes his U.S. visit will spur interest in a
soon-to-be-released single, ``Whisper.''
   The singles previously released from the album were ``quite
funky'' and didn't appeal to Top 40 radio stations, he said. He
also believes some radio programmers don't think the public can
forgive him for his past problems.
   But Boy George doesn't seem concerned that his popularity might
have waned over the past three years.
   ``I have a place in the music industry,'' he said. ``I have a
really good following _ a loyal following. I think you really can't
ask for more than that.''
   Now 28, Boy George hit the music scene at the start of the
decade as a backup singer with the British group Bow Wow Wow. In
those days he was known as Lieutenant Lush. He eventually formed
his own group, the Sex Gang Children, which later evolved into the
internationally successful quartet Culture Club. Boy George assumed
the role as the group's most visible member, attracting attention
with gobs of makeup and a smooth-as-silk voice in a 6-foot frame.
   ``If you look at the pop industry, not a lot of people stick out
as being particularly interesting,'' he said. ``I think at the time
we were the most colorful thing happening.''
   Culture Club's four albums _ ``Kissing to Be Clever,'' ``Colour
by Numbers,'' ``Waking Up With the House on Fire'' and ``From
Luxury to Heartache'' _ quickly became top-sellers in the first
half of the 1980s. This was largely due to a unique style that
combined pop, funk, reggae and soul.
   Boy George, however, remains humble when it comes to Culture
Club's popularity.
   ``We were really lucky. We were just in the right place at the
right time,'' he said. ``It's a bit like trying to catch a taxi.''
   But the Culture Club's taxi took a wrong turn.
   In July 1986, Boy George was arrested in London for heroin
possession. He pleaded guilty to the charge, was fined $370 and
agreed to enter a treatment program for his drug addiction.
   Shortly after his conviction, Michael Rudetski, a friend and
colleague, died at the singer's London mansion from a heroin
overdose. Boy George was not home at the time, however, and no
additional criminal charges were brought against him.
   Then on Dec. 20, 1986, Boy George and pal Mark Golding were
arrested for marijuana possession outside a London nightclub. The
next day, Golding, a 20-year-old musician, was found dead in his
apartment from a drug overdose.
   Boy George was never connected to the death, but he received a
warning for the marijuana charge.
   He is sensitive to questions about those troubled times.
   Asked what he has learned from those painful experiences, he
said: ``I think it's very difficult to put into words. There are
certain things that I feel that I couldn't possibly explain without
making it sound really futile.''
   Nonetheless, the quick-witted star found a bit of humor in the
ordeal, which unfolded across the pages of the tabloids.
   ``I used to think being in the papers was proof I was good,'' he
joked.
   Since that time, he has been working to recoup his health, his
career and ultimately, his life. ``It took me maybe 2{ years to get
over it, and that's a long time, especially for someone like me
because I wanted to work and I wanted to get out and do things _ it
was hard.''
   Sitting in his hotel room in Hollywood, Boy George looked fit
and content. In a T-shirt, sweat pants and clunky hightop sneakers,
he appeared nothing like the old Boy George who favored flowing
caftans and ballet shoes.
   His hair was crew-cut and naturally light brown, and during the
interview he was without the customary cosmetics. But he emphasized
he would be made up after lunch and insisted he wasn't toning down
his look.
   ``I still wear makeup, and as far as I know, I still stand out
in a crowd,'' he said. ``When I get on a lift people still look at
me. So I guess I must be doing something right.''
   He is jokingly critical of other male groups, especially rock
'n' roll bands that have adopted makeup and teased hair.
   ``You look at these heavy metal bands _ they look like a bunch
of ugly old women. At least when I dressed up I looked good,'' he
said with a smirk.
   But Boy George isn't all jokes when it comes to his persona and
career. He is a serious businessman. In England he has an
independent record label, More Protein, which releases some of his
work as well as the music of others. He also is in a new group
called Jesus Loves You and hopes to eventually record enough songs
with the band to release an album.
   In the meantime, he's sneaking around rumors that Culture Club
might get back together.
   ``There's a possibility we'll make an album together, but at the
moment it's a possibility,'' he said. ``Basically, if the songs are
good we'll do it. If they're not good we won't do it.''
   He says he still has discouraging days, and now must take his
life one step at a time. The thing that keeps him going is his
music _ whether it is successful or not.
   ``I'm a songwriter, I love singing and music is my life. It's
not a means to and end for me,'' he said, then added with a smile:
``I'm not making records so I can afford to keep up my mortgage.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 27-29</NOTE>
