<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Holden Adv27-29   10-16 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Holden, Adv 27-29,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 27-29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: From ``Knight Rider'' to Country Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tra Star is cq in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She once was a computer expert who
helped fight crime with TV's ``Knight Rider.'' But all Rebecca
Holden ever really wanted to do was sing country music.
   ``Finally, I'm getting to do what I've always wanted to do,''
she said in an interview. ``I think I'm happier than I've ever
been.''
   After a modeling and acting career that included a brief stint
on the soap opera ``General Hospital,'' Holden has settled in
Nashville and is making records and music videos for Tra Star
Records.
   On ``Knight Rider,'' she portrayed April Curtis, a computer
expert who helped fight crime. This led to her role as the wicked
Elena on ``General Hospital.''
   When her soap character died, she turned to country music. She's
been the opening act at concerts by country stars such as Lee
Greenwood, Tom T. Hall, Earl Thomas Conley and Ronnie McDowell. She
and her four-piece band also made a concert tour of Canada.
   Holden kept her hand in acting by appearing in music videos with
the Statler Brothers and Ronnie Milsap.
   ``Singing is the only thing I ever wanted to do, ever,'' she
said. ``People get the idea that I'm an actress that's now trying
to sing. That's not right. It just took me a while to make it
happen. If I'd had my druthers, that's all I would have ever done.''
   Holden, raised in San Antonio, majored in piano and voice at
North Texas State University. She had a modeling and TV career in
New York where she also put together a country music band.
   ``My television career blossomed into something I never
expected,'' she said. ``I never had dreams of television or an
acting career.''
   Millions saw her astride a horse in a TV commercial, carrying
cologne on a tray to a waiting, handsome young man.
   ``They glued the bottle to the tray,'' she recalled.
   Then later, she loved the challenge of the soap opera daily
grind.
   ``There is a lot of dialogue to memorize. You do 70, 80 pages a
day whereas on an episodic show maybe seven or eight. The crews
have to be commended because you turn out an enormous amount of
material each day,'' she said.
   ``It was exciting. I loved being put to the test.''
   She calls her singing style contemporary country and believes
she can broaden the base of country music.
   ``There are so many good young artists out there,'' she said.
``I think maybe some of the newer people coming in to an industry
can bring a new audience in. Maybe young people will hear them and
say, `Hey I like that. Is it country? I like it anyway.' Maybe I'll
be able to bring in an audience who didn't like it before.''
   Holden had to pay her dues in country music just like anyone
else, she said. ``You have to prove yourself. You can't just come
and say, `just because I was in television I'm going to be a
singer.' It doesn't work that way. I wanted to prove myself, and
you have to. You have to do your share of showcases.''
   Showcases are performances by singers designed to show their
talent to record producers and others. It's this kind of performing
she enjoys most.
   ``There's something about a live audience and the immediate
response that I like,'' she said. ``There's really nothing like it;
there's magic that happens that you don't get if you're working on
an isolated sound stage.
   ``There's a high you get from it that's unexplainable. There's a
feeling of unity and togetherness from the people that's like no
other.
   ``When you are acting, you get that from whoever you are doing
the scene with. You get those special moments when a scene really
works,'' she said.
   ``Another thing is that when you are acting, you always are
another character. When you are on stage, you are yourself.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 27-29</NOTE>
