<DOCNO> AP891016-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:LaserVideo     10-16 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Laser Video,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Laser Video</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY701, NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON GUSTAFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Laser video, introduced about a dozen years ago _ long before
the compact disc, monitor-receivers and the home video boom in
general _ has come of age.
   The format is the choice of consumers in Japan, where the
industry is booming with sales of $1.5 billion annually.
   Its growing popularity in the United States probably is linked
to the acceptance of the compact audio disc.
   And since laser-read optical videodiscs have remained compatible
since their introduction, older discs will play on today's new
machines.
   Engineers have taken advantage of this compatibility and merged
the laser videodisc and compact disc into a format they call CD
video.
   A wide variety of programming is available on optical discs,
ranging from audio-only CDs to feature films such as ``Gone With
the Wind'' and ``Rain Man.''
   It might be confusing if you're not familiar with the laser
format, so here's the lowdown on the discs and players:
   Compact audio discs are five inches in diameter and contain
about 75 minutes of recorded material per side. There also are
three-inch CD singles.
   The new CD videos also are five inches in diameter. They can
have up to five minutes of video and an additional 20 minutes of
audio per side. The current catalog of CDVs lists mostly pop
artists featuring their hit videos and selected songs from audio
albums.
   Laser videodiscs containing both video and audio programming are
8 and 12 inches in diameter. The smaller discs most often feature
selections of popular music videos. The big discs contain
everything from hit movies to operas and concerts. One even has an
encyclopedia.
   The 12-inchers can hold up to 60 minutes of material per side.
   Laser CDV players are being sold in the United States by such
manufacturers as Sony, Yamaha, Magnavox and Phillips. Other makers
are expected to join the market soon.
   Pioneer's LaserDisc Corp. of America is the leading manufacturer
of laser videodiscs in the United States, with its Long Beach,
Calif., plant capable of turning out 600,000 discs a month. Pioneer
also imports discs from Japan; they are compatible with players
being sold in the U.S.
   The format is important to collectors of classic motion pictures
because of quality.
   Laser videodiscs are capable of producing more than 400 lines of
resolution and a picture much sharper than my VHS HQ deck. The
higher resolution makes a noticeable difference, especially on
larger monitors.
   Many of the discs also contain digital sound tracks, with the
same quality as CDs.
   There are other assets to laser video.
   Price, for one. Discs usually cost much less; movies that might
be $89 on videocassette go for as little as $25 on disc.
   With the hardware competition heating up, players also have come
down in price, with combination units available for under $500 at
some outlets.
   Pioneer has a basic unit for only 8- and 12-inch discs only. Its
audio circuitry is analog rather than digital, but consider that
discs are easier to store and care for than tapes.
   And the discs should, theoretically, last a lifetime.
   Other advantages of the format include programmability. If
you're watching a concert disc, you can skip to any song you prefer
simply by using the remote control. The individual song you select
_ no matter where it appears on the disc _ will be searched out by
the player in just a few seconds.
   Discs also contain educational features, with such discs
programmed so users can freeze single frames for as long as they
like with no jitter or glitches.
   Laser video also offers audio channel selection, allowing
consumers to choose full stereo or left and right channels
individually.
   A prime example of using channel selection to its fullest is the
``King Kong'' disc from the Criterion Collection. The first audio
channel contains the original soundtrack. The second channel
carries a running commentary by film historian Ronald Haver. This
disc also contains a visual essay on the making of the movie.
   Discs with digital and Dolby Surround Sound add a dimension to
the home audio-video experience as well.
   The direction of technology points to the laser-read optical
disc as the format of the future.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   (Ron Gustafson is features and newswire editor of the Evening
Observer, Dunkirk, N.Y.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0700EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:LetterboxVideos     10-16 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Letterbox Videos,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Letterbox Videos</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RON GUSTAF50N</HEAD>
<BYLINE>For AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When ``E.T.'' finally came home on video, he did so ln letterbox
style.
   Videophiles who purchased copies of the blockbuster Steven
Spielberg film on laser videodisc were able see it in the original
wide screen theatrical format _ better known as letterbox _ on home
video.
   Presenting wide-screen versions of popular releases on video
discs and cassettes is a trend many of the major studios are
grasping.
   And in this age of high-resolution, large-screen
monitor@receivers, it's no wonder that video connoisseurs are
gobbling up letterbox videos.
   The purpose of the wide-screen videos is to present films for
home viewing in their entirety.
   Take for instance the breathtaking countryside scenes in
MGM-UA's ``Dr. Zhivago'' or the spectacular chariot race in the
studio's ``Ben-Hur.''
   Without letterboxing of these two films, the viewer is missing
up to two-thirds of the actual original frame.
   When movies are made for the wide screen, they are generally
twice as wide as they are tall, a 2-to-1 ratio. The ratio can be a
large as 3-to-1, as are ``Dr. Zhivago'' and ``Ben-Hur.''
   What most home video viewers have become accustomed to is a
process known as ``pan and scan,'' which keeps the action at the
center of the screen.
   But in the ``pan and scan'' process, the picture must be
cropped, in some instances considerably, to accommodate the
television screen.
   To make the wide-screen process work on current televisions and
high-resolution monitors, the letterboxed material appears
centered, with portions of the screen blacked out on both top and
bottom. For viewers who have not seen this type of video before, it
may take some getting used to.
   Critics have referred to letterboxing as Band Aid video, saying
they prefer a full screen in ``pan and scan.''
   But pro-letterboxers appreciate seeing films as they originally
were intended to be viewed _ on a wide screen.
   This may be too small on a 19-inch television, but on a 27-inch
monitor, letterbox editions are preferred.
   It's refreshing to see Judah Ben-Hur (Charlton Heston) talking
to Messala (Stephen Boyd) instead of carrying on a conversation by
himself, as in the ``pan and scan'' version. And the thrilling
20-minute chariot race shown full, instead of chopped to a third of
its original width, is obviously preferable.
   The special effects-laden ``Die Hard'' becomes another favorite,
thanks to letterboxing.
   Because of high video resolution, more letterboxed versions of
collectors' favorite movies are on laser videodiscs than on tapes.
   Other titles currently available in the wide-screen format
include: ``Blade Runner,'' ``The Blob'' (1958 version with Steve
McQueen), ``The Princess Bride,'' ``North By Northwest,''
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers'' (1956 version), and ``The Sound
of Music.''
   In fact, many studios are reissuing previously released titles
in letterbox.
   Some tapes, such as ``Ben-Hur,'' incorporate pan and scan and
letterboxing. The newest tape version switches to wide screen
during spectacular scenes such as the chariot race.
   Video jackets state if the program material is in the letterbox
or wide-screen version.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   (Ron Gustafson is features and newswire editor for the Evening
Observer, Dunkirk, N.Y.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0701EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:HomeTheater     10-16 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Home Theater,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Home Theater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON GUSTAFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tired of watching movies at home because they don't have the
same punch as the ones at the local cinema?
   You can build a high quality theater at home, where your family
and friends can enjoy a real, cinema-like experience. And you don't
have to be a millionaire to finance an entertainment room fitted
out with thoughtfully selected basics.
   The basic components of a home theater are a large screen
monitor-receiver, hi-fi VCR and@or laser videodisc player, and a
quality audio system with surrounding sound.
   Depending on your tastes and pocketbook, a complete home theater
could cost a few thousand dollars or soar onto the megabucks scale.
It took me several years to finance and build my system.
   Since my theater room is relatively small, I decided that a
27-inch Sony monitor-receiver would do the job.
   The only video source driving the screen is a Magnavox videodisc
player, because I'm a collector of classic and blockbuster motion
pictures. I also have a VCR which I use on a portable TV in another
room to view rental tapes. Once I've made up my mind I want a movie
for my collections, I buy a copy in the high quality disc format.
   The audio system consists of an Onkyo TX-51 receiver (43 watts
per channel), a separate 10-band graphic equalizer, Pioneer audio
tape deck, Fisher Dolby Surround Sound decoder-amplifier (30 watts
per channel), a pair of magnetically-shielded speakers at the front
of the room and a pair of surround speakers hung from the ceiling
at the rear of the room.
   Since I had to place the front speakers near the
monitor-receiver, I bought magnetically shielded ones to prevent
picture distortion.
   The final result from this mixed bag of electronic components is
a theater-like experience in my own home.
   The Dolby Surround Sound decoder makes the jets in ``Top Gun''
sound like they're soaring right past you. It also puts the viewer
right in the middle of the action in the barroom fight in ``Raiders
of the Lost Ark.''
   Many of the other movies and concerts in my collection were
processed with Dolby sound tracks for added ambience and less
distortion.
   If you haven't heard a surround sound processor on home video,
try one out at a local dealer. It just may surprise you. (A note
for unsuspecting consumers: the processor must have a licensed
Dolby circuit to decode those hidden sound tracks on a tape or
disc. Don't settle for a cheaper unit which only ``manufactures'' a
surround mode. Look for the Dolby logo on the component or ask the
salesperson.)
   With the monitor-receiver offering more than 450 lines of
horizontal resolution, the picture achieved from the disc player is
superb.
   Simply put, my home theater gets the job done.
   When selecting your components, ask for a full in-store
demonstration. Since speakers are considered the heart of the audio
system, take some time to shop around for them. Be certain they fit
your exact needs before investing in them.
   If purchasing a large screen television or monitor-receiver,
consider the signal sources you will use at home. For instance, if
you are using a standard VHS HQ videocassette deck, then insist
that the salesperson give you a demonstration using a VHS HQ deck.
   Those big screens can be made to look extremely impressive in
stores when laser videodisc players, ED Beta or Super VHS decks are
driving them.
   Save yourself the trouble and disappointment of lugging a big
set home if it will not perform as you expected.
   There are a lot of audio components offered at varying prices on
today's market.
   Select what is right for you and your pocketbook. Stay away from
the frills if you won't use them. Select quality, brand name audio
components.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   (Ron Gustafson is features and newswire editor of the Evening
Observer, Dunkirk, N.Y.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
