<DOCNO> AP891016-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0705EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:Security     10-16 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Security,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With a house full of electronics, it seems only natural to use
the same technology to protect it, along with the house and your
family.
   You can install an electronic household security system that
talks, figures out the type of emergency at hand and automatically
calls the police, fire department or ambulance _ all for about
$600. Or you can use a variety of single-function controls, costing
from about $7 to $75, to increase home security.
   A wireless security system from Dicon Systems, Inc., lets you
program an autodialer and digital recorder to store and deliver
emergency messages. The Dicon 9000's ``intelligent''console knows
which sensor has been triggered _security, fire or medical _ and
automatically places an emergency call to the police, fire or
hospital numbers you have programmed. The machine talks to
answering party, telling them in an electronic voice what type of
emergency it is. Then your own pre-recorded message is delivered.
Each message is repeated three times. The machine's speaker also
features a siren.
   During checkups of the system, its electronic voice guides you
through all procedures for programming and sensor placement and
alerts you when new operating or backup batteries are needed.
   For securing a single door or window, Honeywell's Security Alarm
Bar detects an actual or attempted entry and sets off a pulsating
alarm and a bright, flashing light.
   Automatic lighting devices to make your house seem occupied also
may discourage intruders. Honeywell offers a TimeTracker electronic
timer that turns lights on and off several times a day. The device
also compensates for seasonal changes, turning lights on earlier in
the day as winter days grow shorter. The company's Motion Activated
Light Control uses an infrared sensor that reacts to changes in
heat, so that when someone enters a room, the light automatically
goes on in response to the warmth of his body. Primarily an
energy-saving device for normal room use, it also could startle an
intruder.
</TEXT>
