<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:SmallAppliances     10-16 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Small Appliances,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Small Appliances</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Electronics, having spawned new generations of gadgets not even
dreamed about decades ago, is pumping new juice into old, familiar
household appliances.
   An electronically controlled mixer, for example, knows how to
adjust its motor when a batter gets heavier and gooier and to shut
down when it gets overloaded or something interferes with the
beaters. While it does this, the machine also alerts you with a
warning beep and light.
   The machine, the Black &amp; Decker Automatic Shut-Off Stand Mixer
with Timer, features 12 electronically controlled speeds and a
200-watt motor. A timing control, with a built-in digital display
and pause feature, lets you stop to add ingredients without losing
track of the specified mixing time. And if you're distracted by
other activities, the mixer shuts itself off when its job is done.
   Black &amp; Decker also has applied electronics to one of the oldest
appliances, the iron.
   Its Advanced System Automatic Shut-Off Iron has a light and
beeper to signal when it has reached the desired temperature. The
relative saturation of steam can be adjusted to deal with light or
deep-set wrinkles. For safety, the iron will shut itself off after
30 seconds on its soleplate or 12 minutes on the heelrest, beeping
to alert you. The iron also cleans itself, using ordinary tap water
in its steam system.
</TEXT>
