<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0706EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Electronics:Briefs     10-16 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Electronics: Briefs,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Briefs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY706</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Get Them While They're Young Dept.: Now your three-year-old can
have his own computer game floppy disk.
   Fisher-Price, the toy manufacturer, has teamed with GameTek,
producer of Nintendo-type games, to come up with six computer games
with color graphics for children ages three through eight. Based on
the toy company's most popular products, each costs $14.95 and is
available for IBM PC, AT, XT and 100 percent compatibles; Commodore
64 and 128 and Apple personal computers. --_
   A night out at the traditional big-screen movie palace may soon
be replaced with a visit to a small theater with large-screen
television monitors, run with advanced and high-definition
videodisc, VCR and stereo systems.
   ``Theaters with smaller rooms and smaller screens are showing up
all over the country, especially in shopping malls,'' says Phil
Denslow, technical supervisor of the animation workshop at UCLA's
film and television department.
   High definition television (HDTV) and the cost of movie tickets
will fuel the trend to this bridge between movie and home theater
experience, he says. --_
   On the theory that music should be heard and not seen, Bose
Corporation has come up with a line of stereo speaker panels and
cubes that hide in the walls or pose as light fixtures.
   Audio components can be built into walls when building or
remodelling or installed as a retrofit, the company says. A system
can be operated by a wall-mounted control panel and may cover a
number of rooms. The cube speakers suspend from the ceiling with
single or track-style mounts and resemble spot lighting. The cubes
come in black or white. --_
   Honeywell has several products to make household controls more
convenient and safer.
   The NoTouch Light Switch, making use of an infrared sensor, lets
you turn a light on and off by waving your hand under it. The
switch is useful in workrooms or kitchen, where your hands may be
too messy or wet with paint or food; it's also convenient if you
have arthritis or any other mobility limitation.
   To avert fire danger from appliances that have been left on,
there is the Hour-Off Control, which automatically shuts off the
circuit after the appliance has been connected for the length of
time you set.
   And the Power LockOut Control, enclosing equipment plugs, makes
it impossible for children or others to use an appliance while the
control box is locked. --_
   A computer that's instantly in its program when you turn it on
and has peripherals that snap in has been introduced by HeadStart
Technologies.
   The Explorer is the first ``instant on'' personal computer, the
company says. A modem, joystick, printer, or other peripherals can
be added with snap-in connections. A 40MB hard disk with l0
software programs can be purchased separately and added by sliding
it into the side of the computer, without making the usual
mechanical connections.
   The computer has picture capabilities similar to Macintosh and
is IBM compatible.
</TEXT>
