<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Gardening Adv19   10-16 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 19,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19 ^For release Thursday, Aug. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Indoor Garden Planning Starts During Summer Harvest</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: George Bria retired from the AP in 1981 after 40
years that included coverage of World War II from Italy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BRIA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POUND RIDGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the midst of summer harvest, I've
already started my indoor winter garden.
   Tiny tomato plants have formed true leaves in 4-inch pots in my
``poor man's greenhouse'' _ a fluorescent stand in the dining room.
If all goes well, their cherry-sized fruit will redden in time to
join my lettuce, arugula, basil, parsley and chives in a Christmas
Day salad.
   If you crave fresh greens and flowers in snow time, invest in
lights. For beginners it's a good way to learn the fundamentals,
and retirees moving into apartments will find it a rewarding way to
keep gardening skills alive.
   As more people do it, equipment has improved to meet their
needs. You can begin with basic two-tube stands costing around $50
and graduate to elaborate affairs that may run to four figures,
depending on the size and decor. Seed houses, nurseries and
hardware stores carry them or you can build your own.
   My wife and I share a custom-built stand, six feet long, six
tall and one deep, running along a wall of the dining room. She's
the flower gardener and I'm the vegetable man. More or less
amicably, we've settled ``turf'' conflicts by allocating the two
middle shelves to her plants and the top and bottom to my lettuces
and herbs. We also have a smaller, catalog-purchased stand mainly
for starting seeds for indoor plants and for transplanting outdoors
in the spring.
   Although many different vegetables will grow indoors, space
limits most of us to salad greens, herbs, small tomatoes and some
baby veggies like carrots.
   Some tomatoes, like Florida Petite and Red Robin, are perfect
for shelves, growing no taller than eight inches. Don't expect to
raise big heads of iceberg or knee-high romaine or feed large
families. Tender leaf lettuces like Oak Leaf do excellently,
however, succession plants providing us with salads a couple times
a week all winter long. The same with spicy arugula, also known as
rocket and roquette, which develops a more delicate taste and
texture indoors. Basil, chives and broad-leaf parsley also prosper.
   My wife grows plants both from seeds and cuttings. Among flowers
that have graced her shelves are African violets, gloxinias,
cyclamens, gardenias, miniature roses, Jerusalem cherries,
Christmas cacti and marigolds.
   Trial and error have taught us one vital rule about gardening
under lights: fluorescent tubes are infinitely weaker than
sunlight. This means you must keep pots or flats very close to the
tubes at the sprouting stage or the seedlings will quickly become
spindly and ``drawn'' and you've got to start over again.
   By ``close'' I mean within one inch of the lights. Most stands
have chains or pulleys letting you adjust the height of the tubes.
Or you can use blocks of various sizes under your pots. Shoe boxes
are good for this. After the plants become sturdy, I keep them
within three or four inches of the lights.
   Although weaker than sunlight, fluorescents have the advantage
of steady light as long as you want it. This beats windowsill
growing, which depends on the length and quality of the day. I turn
the lights on when I get up and turn them off at bedtime for a
total of some 17 hours of light. (Plants also need recuperative
periods of darkness.)
   You can buy special fluorescents that promote growth by emitting
blue and red rays. You get similar results by combining cool white
and warm white tubes.
   Sterilized potting soil obtainable at nurseries and hardware
stores prevents diseases and eliminates weeding. Special mixes are
also available, adapted to the needs of certain plants.
   Plants vary widely on moisture, but you can be sure vegetable
greens need dampness. Lettuce, in particular, thrives in water,
becoming bitter without it. Before the seeds sprout, you must keep
the soil constantly moist. This is done best with a sprayer that
produces a fine mist.
   Fertilizing needs also vary. I feed vegetables every two weeks
or so with a spoonful of 20-20-20 all-purpose fertilizer dropped
into the watering can.
   You might ask, why all this in the dining room? When icicles
adorn the windows, we think it's nice to dine among fresh-blooming
flowers. Also, I like to lean over from the table and pick a sprig
of parsely for my filet of sole.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
