<SECOND>BC-PRI--Briefs, Adv 19,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Oct. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Michigan Geriatric Institute Will Be First of Kind In U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Michigan Medical
Center plans to use a five-year, $6.1-million grant from the
National Institute on Aging to work on ways to take care of the
nation's growing older population.
   ``Our population is aging considerably and people are now living
longer, thanks to the advances in medicine and health care and
their own interest in nutrition and health,'' said Dr. Jeffrey
Halter. ``We are now seeing health problems that used to be ignored
that we now have to come to grips with.''
   The average 75-year-old today is healthier than the average
75-year-old was 10 or 15 years ago, said Halter, the medical
center's director.
   The National Institutes of Health projects that there won't be
enough geriatricians in the country by the year 2000 as the number
of Americans over age 85 doubles by the year 2000 to more than 5
million, and that use of short-term hospital care by older people
will rise 50 percent in the next decade.
   The Geriatric Research and Training Center will study brain
disorders, loss of muscle strength and increased fatigue, bone and
joint malfunction, and high blood pressure, among other ailments,
said hospital spokesman Mike Harrison. It will tap resources of the
University of Michigan Medical School, the school's Institute of
Gerontology and other University of Michigan units.
   The aging population is in dire need of such a center, which
will be a first in this country, said NIA Director Dr. T. Franklin
Williams. ``Today's serious shortage of geriatric educators and
researchers is having a negative influence on our society's ability
to provide quality care.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Helpful Hints Offered for Home Caregivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 2.9 million Americans who need
long-term care are living at home. The sons, daughters, wives and
husbands providing that care can often find themselves stretched to
the limit by resentment and isolation.
   ``Take Care!'' a new booklet prepared by two social workers and
available from the Amherst H. Wilder Foundation, can help.
   Jane Royse and Sheryl Niebuhr offer advice on managing stress,
coping with difficult feelings, taking time for oneself,
maintaining a positive outlook and identifying and using community
resources, among other subjects.
   Royse is a consultant to the National Council on Aging and
co-chair of the Minnesota Coalition for Caregiver Support; Niebuhr
is with the Community Care Resources Program of the St. Paul-based
Wilder Foundation.
   The booklet, funded in part by Medtronic Foundation, is
available for $2.50 from the Amherst H. Wilder Foundation, 919
Lafond Ave., St. Paul, MN 55104.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 19</NOTE>
