<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES first item based on closing in Japan; picks up 2nd item,
f0047</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's Friday the 13th scare reverberated around the
world, with stocks falling in Tokyo and following suit in other
Asian markets early today as trading resumed in full force in the
wake of the U.S. market's near-record plunge.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues opened down about 600
points and quickly recovered about a third of its losses before
falling again in the afternoon. It closed at 34,468.69, down 647.33
points, a drop of 1.8 percent from Friday when the index rose
329.97 points.
   Today's drop was the largest this year. The previous biggest was
a drop of 484.11 points on Sept. 26.
   The dollar opened in Tokyo at 139.95 yen, sharply lower than its
Friday closes of 144.00 yen in Tokyo and 142.05 yen in New York.
But it quickly picked up more than a yen and was trading at 140.75
yen in the late afternoon. There was no indication that the Bank of
Japan had intervened in currency trading.
   Stocks also tumbled in early activity before steadying in late
morning activity on markets in Hong Kong, Australia, New Zealand
and Taiwan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve put out the word that it
stood ready to flood the banking system with money to prevent the
second-biggest point drop in the history of the stock market from
developing into something worse.
   The Fed commitment Sunday came as the Bush administration
continued its own efforts to reassure investors reeling from
Friday's 190-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrials average.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All parties in a pilot-management takeover bid
for the parent of United Airlines that fell short last week worked
over the weekend to restructure the offer ``as rapidly as we can,''
a pilots union spokesman said. Banks balked at financing the $6.75
billion cash offer for UAL Corp. led by the Air Line Pilots
Association and a management group, and the announcement Friday
that the bid had fallen through triggered the sharpest stock market
drop since the crash of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The huge Mexican glass company Vitro SA says
it has signed a definitive agreement to buy Anchor Class Container
Corp. and Latchford Glass Co. of California for more than $900
million.
   The Anchor deal, valued at about $800 million, would be the
largest Mexican takeover of a U.S. company, Vitro said Sunday.
   Vitro's protracted effort to take over Tampa-based Anchor, the
nation's second-largest glass company, won approval by Anchor's
directors after the glass giant raised its cash tender offer for
Anchor stock from $20 to $21.25 a share. Anchor's board of
directors in August rejected the $20-a-share bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union workers at Boeing Co.'s helicopter division
have approved an indefinite contract extension at their
Pennsylvania plant, avoiding a strike that has hit Boeing plants
elsewhere.
   No negotiations were scheduled in the nearly 2-week-old strike
by machinists, but contract talks were set to begin Monday between
Boeing and its second-largest union, representing engineers and
technical workers.
   Members of United Aerospace Workers Local 1069, which represents
about 3,200 hourly production and maintenance workers at Boeing
Helicopters' suburban Philadelphia plant, approved their extension
Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp rise in energy costs helped trigger a
rebound in wholesale price inflation in September, wiping out three
rare monthly declines this summer, the government said.
   The 0.9 percent increase Friday in the Labor Department's
Producer Price Index, measuring inflation one stop short of the
retail level, represented a return to the high inflation rates
experienced in the first five months of the year.
   In another economic report, the Commerce Department said retail
sales rose a stronger-than-expected 0.5 percent last month, the
seventh consecutive rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plunge in General Motors Corp. car and light
truck sales led an 11.9 percent decline in early-October vehicle
sales by domestic automakers compared with last year, the companies
said.
   The eight major companies making vehicles in North America said
Friday their cars and light trucks sold at an average rate of
30,734 a day during the Oct. 1-10 period this year, compared with
34,867 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in 1990 will slump to
its slowest pace in eight years with an outright recession a
distinct threat unless the Federal Reserve lowers interest rates,
the nation's top business executives forecast.
   The Business Council, composed of the chief executives of 100 of
the country's largest corporations, said Friday the economy began
to lose steam this summer. They predicted the sluggish period would
last through much of next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young &amp; Rubicam, one of the nation's
largest advertising agencies, pleaded innocent to charges it paid
nearly $1 million in bribes to Jamaican officials for the island's
lucrative tourism campaign.
   Two of the company's executives and a former executive also
pleaded innocent Friday in U.S. District Court Friday.
   Young &amp; Rubicam faces up to $7.5 million in fines if it is
convicted. Young &amp; Rubicam still holds the Jamaica account, which
won praise for its theme ''Come Back to Jamaica,'' and has
vigorously denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest selloff since the crash of 1987 rocked the stock
market Friday, driving prices into a free-fall decline following
news that a big buyout deal for UAL Corp. had fallen through. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials plunged 190.58 points, or 6.91
percent, to 2,569.26.
   Currency dealers pounded down the dollar in hectic selling
incited by the stock plunge.
   Bond prices rocketed higher in heavy trading afternoon as
investors fled the panicky stock market.
   Tumbling stock prices triggered temporary trading halts for
stock-index futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, in a drop
that mirrored a near- record selloff on Wall Street; orange juice
futures plunged; and crude oil futures jumped higher.
</TEXT>
