<FIRST>r f PM-Market-Glance     10-16 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Glance,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is look at the stock market's drop Friday,
some safeguards against large declines and some other markets that
might be affected when trading resumes Monday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHAT HAPPENED:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrials average of 30 major stocks tumbled
190.58 points to 2,569.26, most of it in the final hour of trading
after markets overseas already had closed. It was the second
largest point drop in history behind the 508-point drop on Oct. 19,
1987. In percentage terms, however, the decline was much less
severe, a 6.91 percent loss, the 12th biggest.
   Broader stock indexes also plunged. As measured by the Wilshire
Associates Equity Index, the market value of New York Stock
Exchange, American Stock Exchange and over-the-counter issues, fell
$189.571 billion on Friday to $3.296 trillion, a 5.44 percent
decline from Thursday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHY IT HAPPENED:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Most market strategists agree that a combination of events
played a role, including nervousness over higher inflation,
widespread use of computerized trading strategies and fears that a
prolonged boom in debt-financed corporate takeovers may be ending.
Many say the catalyst for the drop was news that an employee-led
group seeking to buy UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines, had
failed to obtain financing from banks for its $6.75 billion bid.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHAT IT MEANS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market historically has been regarded as a barometer
and forecaster of economic health, so any severe selloff always
provokes anxiety. Many economists say single-day behavior in the
market is difficult to interpret, but if stocks continue to drop
then investors and consumers could become fearful and stop spending
money, possibly leading to a recession.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>REFORMS SINCE THE CRASH:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   After Black Monday, Oct. 19, 1987, the nation's major stock and
futures exchanges voluntarily began cooperating to avoid panicky
selling that could cause similar collapses in the future.
   Their reforms include coordinated ``circuit breaker'' halts in
trading when the Dow Jones industrial average falls 250 points or
the Standard &amp; Poors 500 futures contract declines 12 points; a
special ``hot line'' crisis communication system among exchanges;
shared surveillance and audit trail information; expanded computer
capacity to handle heavy trading; and special priority to
individual investors during days of heavy market volatility.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MAJOR STOCK MARKETS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   New York Stock Exchange, hours 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. EDT.
   London Stock Exchange, hours 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. London time (4
a.m. to noon EDT).
   Tokyo Stock Exchange, hours 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Japan time (8 p.m.
to 2 a.m. EDT).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>IMPORTANT MARKET INDEXES:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   New York _ Dow Jones industrial average, closed Friday at
2,569.26, down 190.58.
   London _ Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, closed
Friday at 2,333.9, down 3.9.
   Tokyo _ Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, closed
Friday at 35,116.02, up 329.97.
</TEXT>
