<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Markets     10-16 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Markets,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Financial Center Girds for Market Opening</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be led with early trading and with later activity; market
opens at 4 a.m. EDT. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an atmosphere of apprehension and government
silence, the already battered British stock market awaited the
opening of trading today to see if the City would mimic Wall
Street's steep selloff.
   Some British analysts were predicting an instant drop of 100 to
200 points on the key Financial Times Stock Exchange 100 share
index when trading resumed for the first time since Friday's
near-record plunge in the U.S. stock market. The index closed
Friday at 2,233.90.
   However, market experts said it was unclear how sustained any
early London selloff would be.
   Wall Street's Dow Jones Industrial Average tumbled 190.58 points
on Friday _ mostly in the final hour of trading _ in a 6.91 percent
market slide that wiped out $200 billion in paper wealth. The
plunge occurred almost exactly two years after a 108-point Dow drop
presaged the Oct. 19, 1987, Black Monday crash of 508 points.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve indicated it was ready to move large
amounts of cash into the American banking system when U.S. markets
opened today, if money was needed to prevent a financial crisis.
   But that was not seen as an option for Britain, which has been
tightening credit in an attempt to curb high inflation. Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson last week raised base lending rates
to an eight-year high of 15 percent to control inflation that has
been running at 7.6 percent.
   ``We are looking over a cliff,'' said one British broker, who
asked not to be identified. ``The government can't help us this
time, and I think the chancellor might just let share prices take
the strain.''
   British shares already had been declining for weeks, falling
about 8 percent since reaching a post-1987 Crash high in early
September, amid gloom about inflation, interest rates and the
overall state of the economy.
   Wall Street's plunge Friday dragged the dollar down and boosted
the British pound nearly three cents to $1.58, taking pressure off
the British government to increase interest rates yet again.
   The state-run Bank of England said Saturday it saw ``no reason
for such an exaggerated fall in London share values'' as occurred
in the United States.
   Neither Lawson nor Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office
issued statements on the stock market situation over the weekend.
Mrs. Thatcher was scheduled to leave today for the Commonwealth
summit in Malaysia and is to return Oct. 25.
   The Sunday Telegraph said it was evident Cabinet ministers
feared political reaction could make the situation worse. It quoted
an unidentified treasury source as saying, ``It is perfectly
possible for people to talk themselves into a mess.''
   The Observer newspaper on Sunday said government officials did
not anticipate as severe a fall in London as on Wall Street and
that the Bank of England was emphasizing it regards the New York
crash as ``a special case, sparked off by the collapse of the
high-risk `junk bond' market, which does not exist on anything like
the same scale in London.''
</TEXT>
