<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-16 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Sinks; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged early today against most major
currencies in active European trading as shares plummeted on the
world's stock markets. It then staged a slight recovery, dealers
said.
   Gold strengthened in Europe.
   The dollar opened more than 5 West German pfennigs down, and
analysts said they expected it to fall as low as 1.80 West German
marks. It also fell more than 2 cents against the British pound.
   Dealers in London said the dollar rebounded slightly after the
opening of trading in Europe. In Frankfurt it pulled back up from
an early low of 1.8490, to 1.8570.
   But Chris Furness, an analyst at Hill Samuel Bank Ltd., said he
expected the dollar to fall further, especially because central
banks have been attempting to push it down in recent weeks.
   ``The market is very, very nervous,'' said a trader at a
Frankfurt bank. ``Nobody knows what they should do. Everyone is
just squaring positions.''
   Said Jens-Uwe Fischer, senior trader at Manufacturers Hanover in
Frankfurt: ``Anything can happen. Everyone will be watching the
stock markets very carefully.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 3.25 Japanese yen to close at 140.75 yen.
Later, in London, it edged back up to 140.94 yen.
   Other selected early dollar rates compared with late Friday's
prices, inlcuded: 1.8555 West German marks, down from 1.9025;
1.6285 Swiss francs, down from 1.6720; 6.3068 French francs, down
from 6.4562; 2.0873 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1465; 1,365.50
Italian lire, down from 1,396.50; 1.1745 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1750.
   In London, the British pound opened about 2{ cents stronger
before shedding a cent to stand at $1.5780, compared with $1.5625
late Friday.
   Gold, which traditionally gains when the dollar and stock
markets are nervous, picked up overnight on profit-taking and
Middle East selling, dealers said. It then lost some of its gain,
which had taken it to a high of $371 a troy ounce, but remained
well above Friday closing levels.
   Bullion opened in London today at a bid price of $368 a troy
ounce, up from $364.25 late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.45.
   In Zurich, gold fetched $366.75, up from $363.70 late Friday.
   In Hong Kong, the metal dropped 32 cents from Saturday to close
at $367.08.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.16 a troy
ounce from $5.12 bid late Friday.
</TEXT>
