<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 0921EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   10-16 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Takes Deepest Plunge Of The Year, But No Confidence Is Lost</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf to include other markets.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange took their
biggest tumble of the year today but trading was calm despite
Friday's big plunge on Wall Street, which Tokyo analysts blamed on
excessive U.S. takeover activity.
   The dollar opened sharply lower against the Japanese yen, then
rebounded slightly in hectic trading.
   Other financial markets in the Far East, from New Zealand and
Australia to Manila and Hong Kong, posted moderate to large
declines. But on the whole investors in the region, especially in
the rich Tokyo market, did not send share prices reeling deeply as
happened two years ago when Wall Street crashed.
   Amid reports of pledges by world monetary authorities to do
anything to buttress stock and foreign currency markets, government
officials sought to keep investors' eyes on local conditions.
   ``Domestic economic conditions are still favorable,'' Japanese
Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told reporters shortly after the
market opened for the day, saying he doubted the Tokyo markets
would plunge following Friday's deep 190-point _ or nearly 7
percent _ slide in the Dow Jones average.
   The closely watched 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average opened down
about 600 points and quickly recovered about a third of its losses
before falling again in the afternoon. It closed at 34,468.69, down
647.33 points, a drop of 1.8 percent from Friday.
   Volume was a thin 520 million shares, less than the 550 million
shares traded Friday when the Nikkei index rose 329.97 points.
   As the Nikkei index slid lower in the afternoon, brokers were
trying to resist panic.
   ``I am telling you that it's not time to sell yet. It's not too
late if we wait until tomorrow and see how New York will do,'' a
broker at a Nikko Securities office in the central Ginza district
was overheard saying on the phone.
   Several dealers had said Sunday they thought the market could
have absorbed a 1,000-point drop. Monday's drop was the largest
this year. The previous biggest was a drop of 484.11 points on
Sept. 26.
   The dollar opened in Tokyo at 139.95 yen, sharply lower than its
Friday closes of 144.00 yen in Tokyo and 142.05 yen in New York.
But it quickly picked up a yen and closed at 140.75 yen.
   There was no indication that the Bank of Japan had intervened in
currency trading that was described as hectic, with volume 30
percent higher than Friday.
   Masaru Takagi, chief economist at Fuji Bank Ltd., a major
commercial bank, said he expected the yen to continue to rise as
stock markets show the difference in fundamentals between the
Japanese and U.S. economies.
   Tokyo analysts pinned Friday's Wall Street plunge on excessive
takeover activity in the United States. They said the situation
otherwise was favorable for stock markets, with interest rates not
a big problem.
   In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index closed at 2,601.7,
down 180.60 points, or 6.5 percent. An analyst at County NatWest
Security Asia Ltd said, ``If the market in New York tonight is
holding, or down by not more than 40 to 50 points, I believe the
Hong Kong market will be all right tomorrow.''
   The wave knocked about 8 percent off share prices in Australia
and New Zealand, 10 percent in Singapore and 11.5 percent in
Malaysia. Stock indices in the Philippines, South Korea, Singapore,
Thailand and Taiwan also fell.
   If London and New York were watching Tokyo for the most
important sign of how the world's markets would act after Friday's
plunge on Wall Street, by the afternoon in Tokyo and elsewhere,
people were wondering how Wall Street's Monday would go.
   Keiishi Nishida, a dealer at the Tokyo office of Kidder Peabody
Securities Co., said Japanese investors were not placing buy orders
because ``they want to make sure that the New York plunge was only
a one-time thing, and the Dow Jones will not go down further Monday
there.''
   Nishida said today's market action was ``nothing like the crash
two years ago when private investors rushed to the brokers from
early in the morning and sold all they had. I don't think any
investors expect Tokyo shares to drop like New York this time.''
   Friday's drop in the Dow Jones raised fears that world markets
might crash in series as they did in October 1987 when a similar
big drop on a Friday led to whopping plunges on the following
Monday, Black Monday in New York, which was followed by Black
Tuesday in Tokyo, London and elsewhere.
   In 1987 the Dow Jones dropped 23 percent on Oct. 19, the Nikkei
dropped a record 15 percent on Oct. 20 and the Hong Kong exchange
was so flustered that it closed for a week.
</TEXT>
