<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0416</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market struggled under a crush of sell
orders today as nervous investors sought to unload shares in the
wake of the worst setback on Wall Street since the crash of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials skidded 49.18 to
2,520.08 in the first 30 minutes of trading. But not all stocks
included in the widely watched measure had opened for trading by 10
a.m. EDT because of order imbalances.
   The New York Stock Exchange had anticipated a flood of sell
orders and activated its computers at 7:30 EDT, an hour earlier
than usual, so it could sort out business ahead of the 9:30 EDT
market opening. Nonetheless, trading in numerous stocks was delayed.
   Losers raced to a big lead over gaining ones on the Big Board,
with 815 shares down in price, 104 up and 172 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.91 million shares after a
half hour of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
3.09 to 182.47.
   Wall Street analysts were reluctant to speculate how the market
might fare today after the 190-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average on Friday. Markets overseas, which had closed by
the time the New York slide started Friday, were knocked down by
powerful selling waves today.
   Among components of the Dow Jones industrial average, American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph shed [ to 39|, USX fell ~ to 32[,
International Business Machines fell 3{ to 98{, Eastman Kodak fell
1[ to 43|, General Motors dropped [ to 42~ and Procter &amp; Gamble
lost 2} to 117.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average sank 190.58 points,
or 6.91 percent, to 2,569.26. It was the second biggest point drop
in history, exceeded only by the 508-point loss on Black Monday,
Oct. 19, 1987.
   NYSE volume totaled 251.17 million shares, up from 160.12
million in the previous session and the heaviest total since 254.87
million traded on Jan. 27.
   Declining issues swamped advances by about 11 to 1 in nationwide
trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 153 up, 1,600 down and 228
unchanged. Consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 288.43 million shares.
   The NYSE's composite index tumbled 11.43 to 185.55. At the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down 16.56 at
378.45.
