<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Market-IndexFutures     10-16 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Index Futures,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Index Futures Rally After Dropping 5-Point Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock index futures bounced
higher early today on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, rallying
after a brief ``circuit breaker'' trading restriction was triggered
by a selloff at the opening.
   After the first hour of trading, the contract for December
delivery of the 500 stocks comprising the S&amp;P 500 index was trading
more than 8 points above Friday's close of 328.85.
   The contract had opened 5 points below Friday's close,
triggering a ``circuit-breaker'' rule preventing traders from
selling below that level for 10 minutes. But buying surfaced
minutes after the opening, trimming the loss, and trading never
came to a halt because there were always orders to sell at the
limit or buy above the limit, said Merc spokeswoman Julie Jacobs.
   ``Now it looks like a normal trading day,'' said Iris Poliski,
another Merc spokeswoman.
   Meanwhile, the Chicago Board of Trade said today it had added a
20-point opening limit to its Major Market Index contract, a
stock-index futures product that is not as heavily traded as the
Merc's S&amp;P 500 contract.
   The MMI opened sharply lower but did not immediately drop by 20
points, which would have triggered a 30-minute halt to all trading
in the contract, said BOT spokesman Michael O'Connell.
   The limits are designed to slow the markets and prevent panic
selling in the event of a sudden collapse of stock prices.
   Stock-index futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of
stocks at specified prices by a specified date. Large institutional
investors use stock-index futures in various trading strategies to
profit from the difference between stock prices and futures prices.
   The index futures had tumbled Friday, triggering a trading halt
in the S&amp;P 500 index futures, when stocks plunged on Wall Street in
the second-worst market selloff ever.
</TEXT>
