<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-16 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices edged lower in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting a
weekend of good harvesting weather and heavy farmer selling of
their crops.
   Friday's plunge in the stock market appeared to have little
effect on the grain markets.
   Because of the advancing harvest and the farmer selling, ``we
would have opened lower anyway,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Weather forecasts generally call for continued good harvesting
conditions in the Midwest through the middle of next week, although
rain and colder temperatures are expected in the next few days.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent to } cent lower with
the contract for December delivery at $4.06 a bushel; corn futures
were } cent to 1} cents lower with December at $2.32\ a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 1} cents lower with December at $1.38} a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with November
at $5.44 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were sharply lower in early trading
today on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid stock-market jitters.
   Live cattle were .35 cent to .95 cent lower with October at
73.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to .85 cent lower
with October at 82.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .50 cent to
1.10 cents lower with October at 47.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .12 cent to 1.15 cents lower with February at 50.40
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
