<FIRST>r f BC-Kmart-PACE     10-16 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-K mart-PACE,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>K mart Reaches Purchase Agreement With Colorado Membership Warehouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major retailer K mart Corp. will purchase
PACE Membership Warehouse Inc. for about $322 million under an
agreement announced Monday.
   The board of PACE has approved the agreement and recommended
that stockholders tender their shares, K mart and PACE said in a
joint news release. K mart will pay $23 a share.
   The acquisition of PACE would expand discounter K mart's
business in warehouse retailing. K mart already has a warehouse
club chain, called Makro Inc., which has six outlets in the
Cincinnati, Washington, Philadelphia, Baltimore and Cleveland areas.
   After the takeover, PACE and Makro will continue to be operated
under their present managements.
   ``The membership warehouse concept has great potential, and the
long-term prospects for PACE Membership Warehouse and its employees
will be enhanced by the affiliation with K mart,'' said Joseph E.
Antonini, K mart's chairman and chief executive officer, and Wayne
H. Patterson, PACE's chairman and co-CEO.
   PACE, based in Aurora, Colo., has operations in 11 states. Its
41 outlets are in California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Iowa,
Kentucky, Maryland, Michigan, Nebraska, North Carolina and
Pennsylvania. The company had 1988 revenue of $1.3 billion.
   K mart has 4,150 stores in the United States, Puerto Rico and
Canada, including 2,283 K mart discount stores, 1,247 Waldenbooks,
279 Pay Less Drug stores and 141 Builders Square outlets.
   K mart, with 1988 revenue of $27.3 billion, is the country's
second biggest retailer after Sears, Roebuck and Co.
</TEXT>
