<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1148EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Markets-MutualFunds     10-16 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Mutual Funds,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customers Flood Fidelity With Calls, But Not Pulling Out Entirely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customers of Fidelity Investments, the nation's
largest mutual fund company, are shifting their money out of the
stock market due to the turmoil on Wall Street, but volume has been
lower than during the 1987 crash, a spokesman said today.
   Lawrence Dwyer, a spokesman for Fidelity, said this morning the
company received about twice as many calls as normal since the Dow
Jones industrial average plunged about 190 points on Friday.
   But he said that two years, during the Black Monday collapse of
Oct. 19, 1987, the phone volume was about double that amount.
   Also, while many people are asking to redeem their investments
in stock funds, ``redemptions are running just about under a third
of what we ran into in the stock market crash,'' he said.
   Dwyer said most people who redeem their stock investments simply
move their money into a more conservative investment fund, such as
a money market mutual fund.
   ``They still have their money and want to invest it,'' he said.
``But they just want to put it in more conservative investments.''
   A mutual fund is an organization that pools and invests money of
its shareholders in a group of securities.
   Fidelity polled its customers over the weekend, and 84 percent
said they were investing for the long term, Dwyer said.
   Mutual fund investors, in general, ``have a pretty good
understanding of what they're in _ they just don't leap,'' said
Betty Hart, a spokeswoman for the Investment Company Institute, a
Washington organization that represents mutual funds.
   Hart said her agency surveyed stock mutual fund customers around
the country after the 1987 crash, and found that only 4 percent
withdrew their investments completely within the first six weeks.
   ``We're probably going to see investors staying the course,''
said John Woerth, a spokesman for Vanguard Group, a mutual fund
company in Valley Forge, Pa.
   ``They've learned the lessons from '87,'' he said. ``If they
would have stayed put, it would have been better than switching
out.''
</TEXT>
