<FIRST>u f PM-Markets-Bonds     10-16 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Bonds,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Decline As Investors Seek Profits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With PM-Markets, Bjt. Stands for PM-Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Treasury bond market fell sharply in
early trading today as investors cashed in on Friday's big price
runup that had stemmed from a move to safer fixed-income
investments from a plummeting stock market.
   In other credit markets, high-yield ``junk'' bonds continued to
decline in value but trading activity was picking up from last
week's near-standstill and prices were showing some signs of
recovering from today's opening slump, traders said.
   Investment-grade corporate bonds were slightly higher while
municipal bonds turned mixed, they said.
   Overseas, bond prices were mostly higher, reflecting the decline
in stock prices abroad. Yields on the Eurobond markets, for
example, were down around 0.25 percentage point in afternoon
trading.
   Market experts said most of today's slump in the U.S. market
came from profit-taking, particularly in Treasury bonds.
   ``We're getting the flip side of Friday,'' said Maria F.
Ramirez, managing director and money market economist for Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. ``Greater opportunities (for profits) like
this don't come that often.''
   On Friday, prices of some government bonds rose as much as $25
per $1,000 face value and yields skidded to levels not seen in two
years following a 190.58-point tumble on the Dow Jones Industrial
average. Concerns about corporate takeovers and the junk bonds that
are often used to finance them helped stoke he panicky selling in
stocks.
   Fixed-income securities _ especially Treasury bonds _ often are
viewed as a safe haven in times of turmoil on Wall Street.
   Today, stock prices were mostly lower in volatile trading. But
bond traders said the fact that the stock market wasn't as far off
as many speculated kept a lid on bond prices.
   ``A lot of people thought the stock market would be a lot
weaker,'' said William V. Sullivan, director of money market
reserach for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``(But) the market's
tentative. It could rebound very sharply if the equity market goes
into a full-fledged retreat.''
   By midday today in the secondary market for Treasury bonds, the
bellwether 30-year issue was off about 1| point, or $16.25 per
$1,000 face amount, after rising around $20 on Friday.
   Its yield, which moves inversely to the price, jumped to 7.96
percent from late Friday's rate of 7.88 percent, the lowest level
since early April 1987.
   Prices of short-term government issues fell between [ point and
3-16 point, intermediate maturities were down around 5-16 point,
and long-term issues declined by around 1| point, according to
figures provided by Telerate Inc., a financial-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, stood at 1,191.79, down 4.58.
   Meanwhile, yields on three-month Treasury bills soared to 7.45
percent as the discount rose 28 basis points to 7.23 percent.
Yields on six-month bills jumped to 7.67 percent as the discount
rose 25 basis points to 7.31 percent. Yields on one-year bills
increased to 7.73 percent as the discount rose 24 basis points to
7.24 percent.
   In corporate bond trading, highly rated issues gained some
ground today. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which
measures total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with
maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.91 to 337.33.
   High-yield, non-investment-grade ``junk'' bonds continued to
decline today, although many traders said some issues that had
fallen as much as $30 or $50 per $1,000 face value, were showing
less severe losses of around $10 or $20 by midday.
   ``The market is also more active,'' said Ray Lemanski, a
managing director Prudential-Bach Securities Inc. ``At least there
are some people saying maybe it's going cheap enough that they
deserve to be bought.''
</TEXT>
