<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     10-16 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0466</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong selling hit most stocks today in the wake
of the worst setback on Wall Street since the crash of 1987 but
blue chip shares rallied after an initial slide.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which skidded more than
49 points in the first 30 minutes of trading, sported a gain of
43.24 points at 2,612.09 by noon on Wall Street.
   Trading volume was extremely heavy. Volume on the Big Board came
to 255.04 million shares at noon on Wall Street, which would be a
hefty amount for an entire day. By midday on Friday a more typical
80.86 million shares had changed hands.
   Losers outpaced gainers by a wide margin on the Big Board, with
1,282 down in price, 343 up and 225 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
recovered its earlier loss and was up 1.60 to 187.16.
   Wall Street analysts were reluctant to speculate how the market
might fare during the remainder of the day, the first session since
the 190-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Friday.
   Markets overseas, which had closed by the time the New York
slide started Friday, reacted with moderate to large declines today.
   Stocks rocked back and forth in morning activity in the United
States. Substantial price declines encouraged some buyers to hunt
for bargains, which helped lift the Dow Jones industrial average.
Computer-driven program trading also contributed to the price
swings.
   Most components of the Dow Jones industrial average showed gains
at midday. Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone
&amp; Telegraph, up 1] to 41[, USX, up ] to 33], Eastman Kodak, up [ to
44~, General Electric, up [ to 54] and Philip Morris, up 1{ to 42{.
   One loser was International Business Machines, which today
announced a 29.7 percent slump in third-quarter earnings. IBM fell
2[ to 99~.
   Market strategists blamed a series of factors for sending the
stock market into a tailspin on Friday. Disappointing inflation and
interest rate prospects had an influence on the selling and program
trading intensified the decline.
   Word that an employee-led group seeking to buy UAL for $6.75
billion had failed to secure financing was cited as the direct
cause of the market's drop. The news cast doubts on all future
debt-financed corporate takeovers.
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, plunged to 224}, down 55 from
the point at which it was halted Friday.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average sank 190.58 points,
or 6.91 percent, to 2,569.26. It was the second biggest point drop
in history, exceeded only by the 508-point loss on Black Monday,
Oct. 19, 1987.
</TEXT>
