<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in hectic, nervous European trading Monday, reflecting
tremors in the stock market.
   Gold prices rose.
   Traders in London and Frankfurt said the dollar swung wildly as
it mirrored the sharp movements of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
   ``The Dow has led the day,'' said one London dealer, who added
that the foreign exchange markets had become considerably calmer
toward the end of the day, with market participants beginning to
turn their attention to Tuesday's U.S. trade figures.
   ``It was a very nervous market today,'' said Ernst Pullmann,
chief trader at Deutsche-Girozentrale Deutsche Kommunalbank in
Frankfurt. ``First the Dow Jones was down 3 percent, and then it
was up 1 percent and the dollar followed right along. But it looks
like the dollar has decoupled itself from the stock market now.
Things are quieting down.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 3.25 yen to a closing 140.75 yen from
Friday's 144.00. Later, in London, it was quoted at a higher rate
of 141.10 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5820 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5625 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.8650 West German marks, down from 1.9025; 1.6345 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6720; 6.3365 French francs, down from 6.4562; 2.0805
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1465; 1,372.50 Italian lire, down from
1,396.50; 1.1765 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1750.
   Gold, which historically gains when the dollar and stock markets
are nervous, picked up in choppy trading as traders adjusted their
positions with stock market swings, dealers said.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $366.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $364.25.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $367.00 compared
with $363.70 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 32 cents an ounce to close at a
bid $367.08.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market, trading at a
late bid price of $5.11 a troy ounce, compared with $5.12 Friday.
</TEXT>
