<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Widely Mixed in Extremely Heavy Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong selling knocked down a broad range of
stock prices today in the wake of the worst setback on Wall Street
since the crash of 1987 but blue chip shares bobbed up from an
earlier plunge.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which sank more than 49
points in the first 30 minutes of trading, sported a gain of 36.27
points at 2,605.53 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Trading volume was extremely heavy. Volume on the Big Board came
to 330.51 million shares with two hours left to go, which would be
an unusually hefty amount for an entire day.
   Losers maintained a wide lead over gainers on the Big Board,
with 1,202 down in price, 470 up and 252 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.47 to 187.03.
   Wall Street analysts were reluctant to speculate how the market
might fare during the remainder of the day, the first session since
the 190.58-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Friday.
   Markets overseas, which had closed by the time the New York
slide started Friday, reacted with moderate to large declines today.
   Stocks rocked back and forth in hectic U.S. trading. Substantial
price declines encouraged some buyers to go after bargains, which
helped lift the Dow Jones industrial average. Computer-driven
program trading intensified the price swings.
   AMR, owner of American Airlines, skidded 16~ to 81} after
investor Donald Trump announced he had withdrawn his $120-a-share
offer for the company.
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, tumbled 55{ to 224\. Word that
an employee-led group seeking to buy UAL for $6.75 billion had
failed to secure financing was cited as the direct cause of the
market's drop on Friday. The news cast doubts on all future
debt-financed corporate takeovers.
   Most components of the Dow Jones industrial average showed gains
in the afternoon. Gainers among the blue chips included American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up 1~ to 41|, USX, up 1 to 34, General
Electric, up 1\ to 55{ and Philip Morris, up 1} to 42}, which was
the most active Big Board issue.
   One blue chip loser was International Business Machines, which
today announced a 29.7 percent slump in third-quarter earnings. IBM
fell ~ to 101[.
   Besides worries about highly leveraged takeovers, market
strategists blamed a series of factors for sending the stock market
into a tailspin on Friday. Disappointing inflation and interest
rate prospects motivated sellers while program trading added to the
downward momentum.
   Friday's drop in the Dow Jones industrial average came to 6.91
percent of its value. It was the second biggest point drop in
history, exceeded only by the 508-point loss on Black Monday, Oct.
19, 1987.
</TEXT>
