<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-MainStreet Bjt   10-16 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Main Street, Bjt,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Street America Buffered From Storms of Wall Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The frenzied froth of Wall Street tapered off Monday to more of
a controlled simmer on Main Street, partly because small investors
prefer long-term strategies and have learned to ride out the
storms, market pros and investors said.
   ``People haven't been terribly spooked, despite the wild
gyrations in the market,'' said Tom Rosencrants, director of
research for Interstate-Johnson Lane in Atlanta.
   ``They're not panicking at this point. They are not jumping out
the windows,'' said Earl Silver, a senior vice president of Dean
Witter Inc. in Chicago.
   Jitters mounted over the weekend after a frantic sell-off in the
last 90 minutes of trading Friday plunged the Dow Jones industrial
average 190.58 points. The Friday the 13th swoon raised fears of a
repeat of 1987's Black Monday, when the Dow crashed a record 508
points.
   Out in the mainstream, the Monday mood was a mixture of calm and
concern.
   A heavyset man in casual dress watched the ticker at the Charles
Schwab &amp; Co. office in Pittsburgh with bemused calm. ``It's never
the end of the world,'' he said, declining to give his name.
   ``I go in for the long-term so I'm just going to hang in there.
I didn't panic or anything,'' said Leon Straub, 51, an unemployed
electronics technician in Appleton, Wis. ``I'm optimistic.''
   ``In a week, we'll have forgotten all about it,'' said Tom
O'Hara, executive director of the 132,000-member National
Association of Investors Corp. ``Fluctuation is part of life in the
stock market. The worst part is these things scare people out of
the market.''
   Only a fraction of Americans own or trade stock, so the impact
of a roiling market merely stirs worries about the economy in
general, according to Thomas Juster, professor of economics at the
University of Michigan.
   ``There almost certainly isn't any direct impact on the vast
bulk of Americans because they aren't in the stock market,'' Juster
said. ``But if there is a visible erosion in the economy, they turn
cautious. They avoid making commitments on purchases.''
   John Wright of Wright Investors Inc. in Bridgeport, Conn., said
35 to 40 percent of the publicly owned stock has been removed from
the market because of leveraged buyouts and takeovers in the past
five years.
   ``Mr. Main Street doesn't own much stock. He's a bystander in a
weak position. I don't think there was much individual reaction.
This was a battle of computers,'' Wright said.
   In today's market, most trading is done by computers, and is
done in multimillion-dollar transactions by trust departments,
foundations and institutions such as mutual and pension funds.
   And those who have sunk money into stocks have learned not be be
alarmed at market swings.
   ``The general public is a little more sophisticated than they
were two years ago,'' said Pat Campbell, senior vice president for
trading at The Ohio Company in Columbus, Ohio. ``There is no crisis
in confidence.''
   ``Why panic?'' said Joan Estep, 60, a retired pharmacist from
Burien, Wash. ``I've been through ups and downs before. You're
going to have gyrations. I'm not making any changes in my
portfolio.''
   Gene Armentrout, president of Gradison Financial Services in
Cincinnati, Ohio, sensed ``a certain amount of skittishness,'' but
his brokers were generally advising people to hold on rather than
sell.
   ``We're in this for the long haul,'' Armentrout said. ``We have
memories as to what happened to people who sold out at the bottom
of the crash in 1987. They didn't do so well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
