<DOCNO> AP891016-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Market-MutualFunds     10-16 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market-Mutual Funds,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mutual Funds Receive Lots Of Callers, Not As Many Deserters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The turmoil on Wall Street led mutual fund
customers to shift money from stocks into safer havens Monday, but
firms also reported that last week's plunge attracted some
bargain-hunting investors.
   ``We're seeing a lot of buying as well as selling,'' said Steven
Norwitz, a spokesman for T. Rowe Price Associates of Baltimore.
``Some people are moving their money (out of stock accounts), but
other people are looking at this as a good opportunity.''
   A mutual fund is a company that pools money from shareholders
and invests it in a group of securities.
   As opposed to an investor who might buy stock in one company
hoping for a quick profit, a mutual fund customer is ``buying a
diversified portfolio. They're buying for the long term,'' Norwitz
said.
   Fidelity Investments, the country's largest mutual fund company,
received about twice as many calls as normal since the stock market
plunged 190 points on Friday, said Lawrence Dwyer, a spokesman for
the Boston-based firm.
   But he said the phone volume was about half of what it was
during the October 1987 stock market crash.
   While many people were asking to redeem their investments in
stock funds, ``redemptions are running just about under a third of
what we ran into in the stock market crash,'' he said.
   Also, as the day progressed, Fidelity got an increasing number
of orders to buy into stock funds, he said.
   Dwyer noted that most people who redeem their stock investments
simply move their money into a more conservative investment fund,
such as a money market.
   ``They still have their money and want to invest it,'' he said.
``But they just want to put it in more conservative investments.''
   Fidelity polled its customers over the weekend, and 84 percent
said they were investing for the long term, Dwyer said.
   Mutual fund investors, in general, ``have a pretty good
understanding of what they're in _ they just don't leap,'' said
Betty Hart, a spokeswoman for the Investment Company Institute, a
Washington organization that represents mutual funds.
   Hart said her agency surveyed mutual stock fund customers around
the country after the October 1987 crash, and found that only 4
percent withdrew their investments completely within the first six
weeks.
   At the end of August this year, total assets in mutual stock
funds stood at $242.1 billion, just below the $242.9 billion of
August 1987.
   ``We're probably going to see investors staying the course,''
said John Woerth, a spokesman for Vanguard Group, a mutual fund
company in Valley Forge, Pa.
   ``They've learned the lessons from '87,'' he said. ``If they
would have stayed put, it would have been better than switching
out.''
   Mutual fund companies said they had plenty of cash reserves to
handle stock redemption orders, and they would not be forced to
sell stock in order to shift money from the accounts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
