<FIRST>r f AM-Scotus-BusinessRdp     10-16 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Business Rdp,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Whether States May Use Federal Law to Break Up Mergers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, agreeing to hear a case
involving the $2.5 billion merger of the Lucky and Alpha Beta
supermarket chains, said Monday it would decide whether states and
possibly private citizens may use federal antitrust law to break up
corporate mergers.
   The justices agreed to hear arguments by California officials
seeking to scuttle the Lucky-Alpha Beta deal, which was placed on
hold by an order issued by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor in August.
   Lucky, California's largest supermarket chain, and Alpha Beta,
the fourth largest, operate 550 stores between them.
   Alpha Beta's parent company, American Stores, acquired Lucky in
June 1988.
   American Stores said California customers would save more than
$50 million a year because of increased efficiency from the merger.
But the California attorney general's office said in a lawsuit last
year that a merger means less competition _ leading to $440 million
worth of higher prices each year.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon in Los Angeles temporarily
blocked completion of the merger, ordering continued separate
operation of the chains even though the financial acquisition had
occurred.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the judge's
ruling in March, saying in effect that California Attorney General
John Van de Kamp waited too long to sue.
   The appeals court said California officials, if they had moved
quickly enough, could prevent the merger. But the appeals court
said only the federal government, not states and private citizens,
has the power to break up mergers after financial arrangements are
completed.
   O'Connor's order in August had the effect of temporarily setting
aside the 9th Circuit court's ruling.
   In other actions Monday:
   _The court rejected an appeal by a right-to-work group that
sought to limit the power of unions to collect dues from
non-members. The court refused to hear arguments in an Illinois
case in which the group claimed it was treated unfairly by a
federal appeals court.
   _The justices refused to free Pan American World Airways from
having to pay $951,500 plus interest to two families of 1974 crash
victims.
   The court, without comment, left intact awards stemming from the
April 22, 1974, crash in Indonesia of a Pan Am plane flying from
Hong Kong to Los Angeles in which 96 passengers and 11 crew members
were killed.
   _The court decided not to consider whether the Internal Revenue
Service, when assessing inheritance taxes, may challenge deductions
state courts have allowed for legal fees and executor's commissions.
   _The justices rejected an appeal by a right-to-work group that
sought to limit the power of unions to collect dues from
non-members. The court refused to hear arguments in an Illinois
case in which the group claimed it was treated unfairly by a
federal appeals court.
</TEXT>
