<SECOND>BC-Hooker-Bid,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Receive $409 Million Bid for Most Holdings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.J. Hooker Corp., operating under bankruptcy
court protection, on Monday said it would carefully review a $409
million bid from a private investment group seeking to acquire most
of its holdings.
   The cash offer announced over the weekend covers L.J. Hooker's
three regional shopping malls, shopping centers, a large Atlanta
office building and undeveloped land in several states. It also
includes L.J. Hooker International Inc., a commercial real estate
brokerage.
   Excluded from the acquisition proposal are L.J. Hooker's
department store chains, B. Altman &amp; Co. and Bonwit Teller. The
company has said it is looking for buyers for B. Altman and expects
to retain Bonwit Teller.
   A spokesman for L.J. Hooker, David McAdam, said the company
wouldn't comment on the proposal until after reviewing it.
   ``It's something we will take under serious consideration,'' he
said Monday.
   The investment group making the bid is led by the Shidler Group
and the Simpson Organization Inc. The group was assembled by the
London-based investment banking company Hoare Govett, a subsidiary
of Security Pacific Corp.
   Shidler, based in Honolulu, specializes in commercial real
estate investment and says it has $1 billion in assets.
Atlanta-based Simpson is a development firm and its chief executive
A. Boyd Simpson was a senior Hooker officer from 1979 to 1988.
   ``This large cash infusion provides the opportunity for Hooker
to substantially repay its creditors without subjecting itself to a
protracted period of piecemeal sales of assets,'' Simpson said in a
news release.
   L.J. Hooker, which has headquarters in Atlanta, sought
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code on Aug. 9. Sanford C. Sigoloff, a corporate executive who
specializes in improving the business of troubled companies, is
steering L.J.Hooker through its reorganization.
   Hooker Corp. of Sydney, Australia owns L.J. Hooker. The parent
company is run by a court-appointed provisional liquidator.
   The properties included in the Shidler-Simpson proposal include
the massive Forest Fair Mall in Cincinnati, the Richland Fashion
Mall in Columbia, S.C. and the Thornton Town Center mall in
Thornton, Colo. The Columbia mall is expected to open on Nov. 15
while the Thornton mall opened last month.
   Among the other Hooker properties covered by the offer are a
20-story office tower in midtown Atlanta, scheduled for completion
by February, and vacant sites in Florida and Ohio plus other
shopping centers.
