<HEAD>Relieved Grain Futures Gain On China Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rallied Monday
on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders, relieved by the stock
market's apparent recovery, reacted to news that China wanted
400,000 tons of U.S. wheat.
   Wheat futures surged in response to the news but gains in the
corn and soybean markets were limited by selling linked to the
rapidly advancing harvest.
   Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said
grain traders were pleased with the stock market's strong rebound
from a Friday's plunge of about 190 points in the Dow Jones
industrial average.
   The Dow average was up nearly 50 points when the grain markets
closed at 1:15 p.m. Central time.
   ``If the stock market had collapsed today, it would have made
people gloomy and doomy down here and they would have been inclined
to sell the grains,'' Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat futures were 2} cents to 5 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.10} a bushel; corn
futures were 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.36 a
bushel; oats were \ cent lower to 2} cents higher with December at
$1.42} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 4 cents higher with
November at $5.46 a bushel.
