<HEAD>Sell Largest Liquor Retail Chain For $40 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LEANDRO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liquor Barn, the nation's largest
liquor retail chain which has been under federal bankruptcy court
protection for nearly a year, has been purchased for $40 million by
an investor group.
   The assets of Liquor Barn Northern California and Liquor Barn
Southern California were purchased by LBI Holdings, which plans to
operate the 68-outlet chain under the same name with new management.
   The closing of the $40 million cash deal, first revealed in late
August, was announced this past Friday.
   Safeway Stores sold Liquor Barn to Majestic Wine PLC of Britain
in 1987. In November 1988, Liquor Barn filed for reorganization
under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code. The sale to LBI had
been approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Northern
District of California.
   A plan of reorganization will soon be submitted to creditors,
according to a Liquor Barn news release.
   ``As a result of our efforts over the past eleven months inside
Chapter 11, Liquor Barn has recaptured a significant portion of its
market share and is poised to continue that trend,'' said C. John
Thompson III, the outgoing president and chief executive officer.
