<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1614EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-CircuitBreakers     10-16 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Circuit Breakers,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Circuit Breakers: Stop Lights or Invitations to Trouble?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The securities industry compares its
``circuit-breaker'' system of temporary market trading pauses with
traffic lights at an intersection.
   Like traffic lights, the circuit breakers are intended to help
calm wild markets by halting severe price declines and giving
traders and investors a chance to stop and check the financial
landscape before continuing.
   But critics argue that the system _ which takes effect
automatically when prices fall wildly _ is possibly
counterproductive and could worsen any downturn by causing a
traffic jam of people who want to sell but can't do so.
   ``The reality of it is ... it could really snowball and cause
more selling,'' said Jack Baker, who handles trading of large
blocks of stocks for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The circuit breakers essentially are temporary trading
restrictions and halts that are imposed during major price swings
on the New York Stock Exchange and Chicago Mercantile Exchange
stock index futures market.
   The system was deployed on those markets a year ago to help
restore investor confidence after the Oct. 19, 1987 crash saw the
Dow Jones Industrial Average plummet 508 points.
   Institutional investors employing computerized trading
strategies often use stock-index futures traded on the Chicago
exchange to hedge against losses in the stock market. But that kind
of trading often can cause wild price swings on both markets, and
was blamed by many critics for worsening the 1987 crash.
   The securities industry and federal regulators felt more
coordination was needed between the equities and futures markets.
   Richard Torrenzano, spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange,
said that in a wild market the circuit breakers``can slow things
down and let everyone assess what is going on.''
   The system kicked in on the Merc last Friday, after stock index
futures tumbled in response to a plunge in stock prices that saw
the Dow Jones industrial average finish down 190.58 points.
   But on Monday, the circuit breakers barely figured in trading as
the Dow industrials shook off a sharp early decline and finished
well above Friday's close.
   Under the NYSE system, stock trading is halted for an hour if
the Dow falls 250 points from its previous close and for two hours
if it falls an additional 150 points for a total of 400 points in a
single day.
   One feature of the system was tripped early Monday when Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 index futures contracts fell 5 points at the opening.
An opening 5 point drop in those contracts traded on the Chicago
Merc triggers a 10-minute period during which those contracts
cannot be traded at any lower price.
   A spokeswoman for the Merc, Julie Jacobs, said that on Monday
buyers surfaced within seconds at prices matching or higher than
the opening price and trading was never interrupted.
   On Friday, one Mercantile Exchange trading limit was imposed
shortly after 2 p.m. when S&amp;P futures contracts fell 12 points _ or
the equivalent of almost 100 points in the Dow industrials. The
price of those contracts was not allowed to fall for 30 minutes
although trading could continue at that price or higher. The next
pause was reached about 45 minutes later when the S&amp;P futures fell
30 points from the previous day's close. The circuit breaker
program calls for trading at that price or higher for an hour.
Since Friday's trading day was to end 30 minutes later, the pause
ended trading at any lower price for the day.
   Alfred E. Goldman, director of technical analysis at the
investment firm A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said the
restrictions in the futures market ``didn't do any good
whatsoever.'' He noted the bulk of the Dow's decline of 190.58
points Friday came in the final hour of trading.
   Shearson's Baker said that while the futures markets limits were
in effect, sell orders simply backed up. ``People who can't go to
the futures markets are going to sell stocks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891016-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1636EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     10-16 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Ends Widely Mixed in Volatile, Heavy Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue chip stocks bounded ahead in unusually
brisk trading today, recovering from the worst setback on Wall
Street since the crash of 1987, but share prices of many other
companies trailed behind.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, knocked down by a
powerful selling wave in the opening minutes of trading, rallied as
buyers flocked to the market to snap up bargains. Market analysts
said the 190-point plunge in the widely watched barometer on Friday
pushed many stocks to attractively low prices.
   The broader market failed to overcome the impact of an early
selloff, however, and losers still held a lead over gainers at the
closing bell.
   In morning trading, stocks seesawed up and down as substantial
price declines encouraged fresh buying but by midday the Dow Jones
industrial average was embarked on an upward course for good.
Computer-driven trading strategies intensified the early swings.
   Airline stocks bumped into more turbulence. Investor Donald
Trump announced he was withdrawing his $7 billion bid for AMR,
parent of American Airlines, after the company's stock slid more
than $13 a share. AMR was halted briefly for the news and skidded
21| to 76] after trading resumed.
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, tumbled 56} to 223. Word that an
employee-management group seeking to buy UAL for $6.75 billion had
failed to secure financing for the deal had been cited as the
direct cause of the market's drop on Friday. The news cast doubts
on all future debt-financed corporate takeovers.
   Most components of the Dow Jones industrial average finished
higher.
   Besides worries about highly leveraged takeovers, market
strategists blamed a series of factors for sending the stock market
into a tailspin on Friday. Disappointing inflation and interest
rate prospects motivated sellers while program trading added to the
downward momentum.
   Market strategists were reluctant to speculate about how stocks
will fare in the near future but they note that current economic
and business conditions bare few similarities to two years ago.
</TEXT>
