<DOCNO> AP891016-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1637EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-Stockbroker Bjt  10-16 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Stockbroker, Bjt, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Broker's Day Rises And Falls With Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some clients had no desire to ride
on Monday's see-saw stock market, others thought it was an ideal
time to buy and one investor even threatened to sue because his
regular broker was out sick.
   As the Dow Jones industrial average dropped more than 60 points
in the first hour of trading, Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. broker John
Rodstrom Jr. sank into his swivel chair in his Fort Lauderdale
office, juggled calls and tapped at his computer terminal for stock
quotes.
   A raspy voice from Wall Street barked out advice over a speaker.
   ``This is hand-holding time,'' said Rodstrom. ``Everyone gets so
worked up on days like this that part of my job is just getting
them to calm down.''
   On Friday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks plunged
190.58 points to 2,569.26, the second-largest drop behind the
508-point ``Black Monday'' crash of Oct. 19, 1987. Most analysts
said the $200 million drop was linked to an announcement that
financing was unavailable for a $6.75 billion buyout of United
Airlines' parent UAL Corp.
   But forecasts of another frantic sell-off Monday were
contradicted by mid-morning with a rally that brought the market
above the opening level.
   While other brokers raced to put in orders, Rodstrom held back.
His advice to clients: patience.
   ``This market is going to testing how high it can go and testing
how low it can go,'' said Rodstrom. ``There's definitely going to
be a new level come out of this correction. Figuring out where it
will be is the trick.
   ``There's a saying: `Don't fight the tape.' It's good advice
when things are this crazy.''
   By 10:15 a.m. EDT, the selling frenzy reached a crescendo. The
tick _ the number of stocks either up or down _ had reached minus
940. Rodstrom usually uses minus 800 as a signal to buy.
   He put in one order. Others were written out, but not executed.
   Rodstrom took another call. The client, a well-heeled investor
with a large stock portfolio, was nervous and wanted an update.
Everything was down.
   ``Just sit tight,'' he told the client. ``We're a long way away
from another Black Monday. I just don't see it.''
   Rodstrom noted that Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average was down 1.8
percent from Friday, much less than many analysts had feared, and
the early drop on the New York Stock Exchange was steady, not like
the free fall of Black Monday.
   The client decided not to sell. Rodstrom gave a quick thumbs up
sign as the market rally began.
   ``Everyone seems a bit smarter after the '87 crash,'' said
Rodstrom, 37, whose desk was littered with market performance
graphs and telephone message slips. ``There doesn't seem to be that
panic reaction to shifts in the market. We're more inclined to lay
back than jump in screaming to sell.''
   Other factors distinguishing the current market from October
1987 are declining interest rates and a healthy U.S. dollar.
   ``And you don't hear anyone blaming the deficit for this latest
drop,'' he said. ``There's the feeling Gramm-Rudman (the federal
deficit-reduction law) is working and the economy is going in the
right direction.''
   By early afternoon, with the Dow up more than 70 points,
Rodstrom was beginning to take orders from money managers for
fast-rising issues such as Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., Eastman Kodak
Co. and General Electric Co.
   For individual investors, Rodstrom was touting utilities, whose
dividends would be more attractive if interest rates fall further.
   ``Back in the old days someone bought 100 shares of IBM and
stuck it in a safe-deposit box,'' said Rodstrom. ``That whole idea
is out the window. It's all oriented to the short-term money and
the immediate profit.
   ``For a company holding stocks in their pension fund for 20
years, this is just a hiccup. For someone who just got in the
market last year, this is a big event. It's all a matter of
perspective.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
