<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-Europe 1stLd-Writethru   10-16 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Europe, 1st Ld - Writethru,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Nosedive in Europe, Then Recover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, On Wall... to UPDATE with closing Dow Jones.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices nosedived across Europe on Monday in
their first reaction to Wall Street's Friday the 13th plunge, but
finished above their lows on optimism that New York prices would
not collapse.
   Volatility and heavy volume helped disrupt trading in most
European financial centers. Severe price drops triggered trading
halts in some markets and computer problems in others, although
activity remained orderly in Madrid and in London, the Continent's
biggest stock exchange.
   ``We're not out of the woods yet, but at least we didn't
crash,'' said a dealer with a large British brokerage firm in
London.
   Declines in European stock indexes ranged from 3 percent to 13
percent lower on the day.
   London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down
by more than 9 percent at one point as investor nervousness
increased near the opening of trading across the Atlantic on Wall
Street, but recovered to finish at its high of the day. The index
finished down 70.5 points, or 3.2 percent, from Friday at 2,163.40.
   Trading was extremely heavy. Volume in London came to a 959.3
million shares, more than double Friday's volume of 457.7 million.
   Share prices on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange tumbled in their
steepest fall ever, with the German Stock Index plunging 12.8
percent in what one Frankfurt dealer called ``a blood bath.''
   But other German and some Norwegian traders reported that while
individual investors were dumping stocks, institutions were holding
back.
   Sharp price drops triggered European versions of ``circuit
breakers'' _ market procedures designed to calm roiled markets _
and prompted some authorities to step in to contain the damage.
   Price drops of 15 percent triggered trading suspensions in many
shares in Paris, Brussels, and Lisbon.
   A deluge of sell orders caused computer problems in Brussels,
where there was little trading all session. Amsterdam also had
computer problems during its session.
   The Frankfurt exchange and others stayed open late to compensate
for the trading difficulties.
   ``Right now, with the dollar up and Wall Street up, it certainly
doesn't look like any crash,'' said a Zurich dealer.
   ``It's all Wall Street right now,'' an equities analyst with the
London investment firm James Capel and Co. said, adding that New
York's performance after the European markets closed would set
Tuesday's tone for Europe.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which
plummeted 190 points on Friday, fell sharply after its opening
before bouncing higher and lower throughout the session. The
widely-followed market index finished up 88.12 points at 2,657.38.
   Friday's debacle in New York occurred after European centers had
closed for the weekend and European investors were not reassured by
a modest setback in Tokyo earlier Monday.
   Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, Nigel Lawson, issued a
statement after a routine meeting with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, saying Monday's share price declines were ``not
surprising.''
   He blamed the largely American phenomenon of junk bonds _
low-rated securities used widely to help finance the U.S. corporate
takeover wave _ for the slide.
   Lawson also said, ``As the events of 1987 demonstrated, there is
no need for sharp fluctuations in the stock market to have
significant effects on the real economy.''
   A spokesman for the West German central bank, the Bundesbank,
said, ``We're observing the situation very intensively. We've been
in constant contact with the affected countries.'' He requested
anonymity.
   Madrid Stock Exchange President Pedro Guerrero said the main
challenge was to maintain liquidity at all costs, ``and this has
been achieved totally.'' He described trading as ``frenetic, but
satisfactory.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
