<FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MarketAnalysis 1stLd-Writethru   10-16 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market Analysis, 1st Ld-Writethru,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Crash Replay For Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS two new grafs for 5th and 6th graf pvs ``But the ...''
to update with closing Dow figure and some other measures lower; uppicks
7th graf ``Still, ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a worldwide audience watching, the stock
market pulled off one of its favorite tricks Monday _ heading off
in a much different direction from where it was expected to go.
   After a worried weekend, government policymakers, business
managers and investors big and small arrived at work early, braced
for a possible re-enactment of the Crash of 1987.
   Instead, they witnessed a rally among many blue-chip stocks as
the market zigzagged erratically in a barrage of trading that left
analysts and statisticians who track its progress gasping to keep
up.
   ``This can't be right,'' said a brokerage-house economist at
midmorning, checking a quotation machine that showed a small gain
in the Dow Jones industrial average only moments after it had been
down some 60 points.
   But the numbers were correct. The widely recognized average of
30 big-name stocks had begun a rebound from its early drop, and
from the 190.58-point loss it suffered on Friday, to sport a gain
of 88.12 points to 2,657.38.
   Some broader gauges of stock price trends declined, testifying
that investors had not grown bold enough yet to chase
enthusiastically after the shares of smaller, lesser-known
companies.
   Still, it was clear that the market wasn't sticking to the
script of almost exactly two years ago, when it followed a Friday
afternoon selloff with a record 508-point drop on Black Monday,
Oct. 19, 1987.
   The strength in the blue chips seemed to support the assertions
of officials in Washington and Wall Street that Friday's
``massacre'' did not stem from any crisis in the outlook for the
economy, the dollar or interest rates.
   For the moment at least, the market's problems appeared to be
confined to a collapse of enthusiasm for debt-financed takeover
deals, intensified by word Friday afternoon that financing could
not be found for a planned buyout of the airline holding company
UAL Corp.
   In a separate deal, investor Donald Trump said Monday he was
withdrawing a bid for AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines.
   ``We had two days to reflect, and people became aware of the
sharp differences between now and 1987,'' said Hugh Johnson, an
analyst at First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y.
   Like voters listening to campaign promises, veteran investors
have learned to be leery of official statements designed to bolster
markets in trouble. In the dark days of 1929, for instance,
repeated assurances were issued that ``conditions are fundamentally
sound.''
   This time, however, the optimistic message evidently got
through, amplified by supportive comments from prominent advisers
at several brokerage firms.
   A good many Wall Streeters gave the Federal Reserve high marks
for its tactics over the weekend, making its presence felt subtly
without issuing any formal statements that might have been heard as
alarm bells.
   ``That was enough to stabilize the confidence of institutional
investors,'' Johnson said. ``They went down their lists of stocks
and found quite a few that looked cheap.''
   Another theory to explain the market's resilience had little to
do with the Fed or the business outlook.
   According to this view, professional traders and money managers
were acting on their memories of 1987, when those who bought stocks
at depressed levels in the midst of the crash were handsomely
rewarded by the market's subsequent revival.
   Monday's session, so it seemed, offered a second chance to play
this profitable game.
   Whether that kind of thinking pays off once more remains to be
seen. In the meantime, the activity in stocks Monday provided a
resounding affirmation of another principle, summarized two decades
ago by money manager George A. Chestnutt Jr.: ``The market always
does what it has to do to make the majority wrong.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Business Writer Chet Currier has covered Wall
Street for The Associated Press since 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
