<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed in hectic U.S. trading
on Monday, as a rebound in a widely followed U.S. stock market
index propelled it above its closing levels earlier in the day on
overseas markets.
   Gold prices finished higher. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted an after-hours bid for a troy ounce of gold at $365.80, up
$1 from Friday's late bid.
   Analysts credited a rebound in the Dow Jones industrial average
for the dollar's improved showing in domestic trading compared with
its closing levels overseas. Despite the improvement, the dollar
finished below Friday's New York closing levels against the West
German mark, Japanese yen and Swiss franc.
   The rise in blue-chip stock prices in New York following
Friday's huge selloff was viewed as taking some of the pressure off
the Federal Reserve to reduce interest rates.
   ``The dollar seemed to be moving in lockstep with the stocks,''
said Jeffrey Mondschein, managing director for foreign exchange at
Continental Bank in Chicago.
   Falling U.S. interest rates would make the dollar less
attractive to foreign investors.
   The Dow Jones industrial average traded in plus territory for
most of the afternoon, and finished with a 88.12-point gain,
recovering about half of the 190.58 points lost on Friday.
   But Jack Barbanel of First Global Asset Management in Princeton,
N.J., said the fact that the dollar did not finish broadly higher
in the U.S. compared with Friday's closing levels here indicates
``a lack of confidence'' by foreign currency traders that the stock
market has fully recovered from Friday's loss.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to 140.75 yen from 144.00 yen on Friday.
Later in London, the dollar was quoted at 141.10 yen. In New York,
the dollar finished at 141.80 yen, but that was still down from
142.05 yen on Friday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound, which rose
to $1.5820 from $1.5625 late Friday. But the pound weakened against
the dollar in New York, falling to $1.5750 from $1.5820 on Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late rates
Friday included: 1.8680 West German marks, down from 1.8720; 1.6340
Swiss francs, down from 1.6420; 6.3480 French francs, up from
6.34325; 1,374.50 Italian lire, up from 1,370.37; and 1.17675
Canadian dollars, up from 1.17385.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Friday,
included: 1.8650 West German marks, down from 1.9025; 1.6345 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6720; 6.3365 French francs, down from 6.34375;
2.0805 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1465; 1,372.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,396.50; 1.1765 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1750.
   In the gold markets, bullion advanced in New York and Europe
after falling in Hong Kong.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery rose
$4 a troy ounce to settle at $367.30.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $366.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $364.25. In Zurich, gold rose to
$367.00 an ounce from $363.70 late Friday. Earlier, in Hong Kong,
gold fell 32 cents an ounce to close at a bid of $367.08 an ounce.
   Silver for immediate delivery rose 2.5 cents a troy ounce to
$5.104 on New York's Commodity Exchange. But silver fell earlier in
London to a late bid price of $5.11 a troy ounce from $5.12 on
Friday.
</TEXT>
