<FIRST>u f AM-Market-IndexFutures     10-16 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market-Index Futures,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebound Strongly After Shaky Opening</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures prices surged in heavy
trading Monday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, erasing a lot of
investor fears and more than half of last Friday's dizzying losses.
   ``What we saw today was an avalanche of confidence,'' said
Morris Markovitz, president of Mercury Management Associates Inc.,
a commodities trading advisory firm based in New York.
   The contract for December delivery of the 500 stocks tracked by
the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 15.65 points higher at
344.50, the biggest-one-day gain ever. The contract is worth $500
per point.
   The contract opened at 323.85, five points below Friday's close,
triggering a ``circuit-breaker'' rule prohibiting further selling
at prices below that level for 10 minutes.
   But buying surfaced almost immediately, lifting the contract to
more than 8 points above Friday's close within an hour of the
opening.
   Traders and analysts attributed the rally to a resurgence of
investor confidence following Friday's 30-point plunge in the S&amp;P
500 futures, which corresponded to a 190-point drop in the Dow
Jones industrial average.
   The Dow average rallied 88 points on Monday.
   Experts said Monday's supportive factors included the strength
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, where the main market barometer fell
by a modest 1.8 percent; the lack of high-volume computerized
strategies known as program trading, and the stated determination
of British Airways PLC to continue as a 15 percent partner in a
group seeking to buy United Airlines parent UAL Corp. The collapse
of the UAL deal contributed to the Friday selloff.
   Program trading involves the use of computers to buy and sell
huge blocks of stocks and index futures in an attempt to profit
from minute differences in prices on the two markets. The practice
can cause rapid price swings and is believed by some to have
accelerated the stock-market collapse of Oct. 19, 1987.
   Bill Finke, a vice president of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
Chicago, speculated that program traders may have withdrawn from
the market intentionally.
   ``I would assume the firms that do program trading knew it was a
crucial day for people to have confidence in the market,'' he said.
   Stock-index futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of
stocks at specified prices by a specified date. Large institutional
investors use stock-index futures in various trading strategies
aimed at profiting from the difference between stock prices and
futures prices.
   Circuit breakers had halted trading in S&amp;P 500 futures twice on
Friday, for 30 minutes each time, as prices plunged.
   The halts were designed to slow the markets and prevent panic
selling.
   The circuit-breakers were installed last October as part of a
coordinated effort to prevent another stock-market crash like the
508-point plunge in the Dow average that occurred two years ago.
   The Chicago Board of Trade said Monday it had added a 20-point
opening limit to its Major Market Index contract, a stock-index
futures product that is not as heavily traded as the Merc's S&amp;P 500
contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
