<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-16 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock-Index Futures Rebound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures prices soared Monday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, erasing some investor fears and more than half
of last Friday's losses while easing jitters on other commodity
markets.
   Also on Monday, copper futures fell sharply while precious
metals gained; grains and soybeans rallied; livestock and meat
futures retreated and energy futures sagged.
   The contract for December delivery of the 500 stocks tracked by
the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 15.65 points higher at
344.50 in heavy trading on the Merc. The contract is worth $500 per
point.
   ``What we saw today was an avalanche of confidence,'' said
Morris Markovitz, president of Mercury Management Associates Inc.,
a commodities trading advisory firm based in New York.
   Traders and analysts attributed the rally to a resurgence of
investor confidence following Friday's 30-point plunge in the S&amp;P
500 futures, which corresponded to a 190-point drop in the Dow
Jones industrial average.
   The Dow rallied 88 points on Monday.
   Experts said Monday's supportive factors included the
encouraging performance of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, where the main
market barometer fell by a modest 1.8 percent; the stated
determination of British Airways PLC to continue as a 15 percent
partner in the group seeking to buy United Airlines; and a dearth
of program trading, which can sometimes cause rapid price swings.
   The Chicago Board of Trade said Monday it had added a 20-point
opening limit to its Major Market Index contract, a stock-index
futures product that is not as heavily traded as the Merc's S&amp;P 500
contract.
   Copper futures slumped to two-week lows on New York's Commodity
Exchange, partly on stock-market jitters and partly on a report
that a settlement of the 14-week-old strike at Canada's Highland
Valley copper mine was imminent.
   Officials of the mine, located in British Columbia, announced a
breakthrough in contract negotiations last week.
   The copper market, particularly vulnerable to industrial demand,
opened sharply lower on stock-market jitters, then recovered along
with stocks only to retreat in afternoon trading amid speculation
about the Canadian strike situation.
   On the bullish side, the London Metal Exchange said in a weekly
report that stocks of copper registered for delivery against its
futures contracts tumbled by 13,575 tons to 89,300 last week.
   Copper futures settled 1.5 cents to 3.5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $1.2745 a pound.
   Precious-metals futures rallied on the Comex, partly reflecting
investor nervousness about the stock market.
   Precious metals are often perceived as a safe haven during times
of economic uncertainty.
   Gold and silver made intra-day highs before the stock market
opened but they remained firm, despite stocks' recovery, on
lingering doubts about the stock market, said Bette Raptopoulos, a
metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Gold settled $3.90 to $4.10 higher with October at $367.30 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.5 cents to 2.5 cents higher with December
at $5.163 a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures prices rallied on the Chicago Board of
Trade as traders, relieved by the stock market's recovery, reacted
to news that China was bidding for 400,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat and had purchased 150,000 metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Wheat futures settled 2} cents to 5 cents higher with December
at $4.10} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents higher with
December at $2.36\ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 3 cents higher
with December at $1.42{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 3{ cents
higher with November at $5.47 a bushel.
   Weak cash markets encouraged profit-taking in the livestock and
meat markets on the Chicago Merc, where live cattle futures settled
.15 cent to .78 cent lower with October at 73.35 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .60 cent to 1.13 cents lower with October at
82.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to the limit 1.5 cents
lower with October at 47.37 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.02 cent to .75 cent lower with February at 50.62 cents a pound.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 22 cents to 30 cents lower with November at
$20.59 a barrel; heating oil was .24 cent to .50 cent lower with
November at 60.42 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to
.71 cent lower with November at 55.85 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
