<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks 1stLd-Writethru   10-16 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Reprots Huge Loss As Exected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with Security Pacific earnings; No pickupp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc. said Monday it suffered a $1.8 billion
third-quarter loss, as expected, reflecting its decision to add $2
bilion to its reserve cushion against shaky Third World loans.
   The loss for the three months ended Sept. 30, amounted to $9.92
per share, compared with a profit of $233.6 million, or $1.25 a
share, during the same period a year ago.
   It was in line with projections made Sept. 21, when Morgan
announced it was adding $2 billion to its loan-loss reserve. Other
major banks took similar action and also suffered big third-quarter
losses.
   The addition brought to $3 billion Morgan's total reserves, or
100 percent of its estimated portfolio of medium- and long-term
debt to Third World countries _ the highest of any money-center
bank.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Morgan's net loss totaled
$1.4 billion, or $7.87 a share, compared with earnings of $744
million, or $4 per share, last year.
   Morgan said non-interest income rose by 12 percent to $414
million in the third quarter. However, quarterly non-interest
expenses also increased, to $496 million from $429 million.
   Net interest income fell to $254 million from $347 million,
while net interest expenses rose to $496 million from $429 million.
   Morgan is the parent of flagship Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. of
New York, and the nation's third-largest banking company with
assets of around $100.4 billion.
   Security Pacific Corp., the nation's sixth-largest bank holding
company, said its quarterly profit rose 10 percent, with strong
results from California and the Northwest overcoming weakness in
Arizona commercial real estate.
   For the quarter ending Sept. 30, the parent of Security Pacific
Bank with operations throughout the West earned $185.1 million, or
$1.55 per share, compared with $167.9 million, or $1.47 per share,
for third-quarter 1988.
</TEXT>
