<FIRST>r f AM-Perkin-Elmer-Hughes     10-16 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Perkin-Elmer-Hughes,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perkin-Elmer Sells Telescope Optics Division to Hughes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perkin-Elmer Corp. announced Monday that
Hughes Aircraft Co. of California will buy the company's division
that helped build NASA's super-powerful Hubble telescope.
   The electro-optics technology division in Danbury, Conn., which
employs 800, will be sold as part of a restructuring announced in
April, Perkin-Elmer spokesman Edward Bloch said. Terms of the sale
were not disclosed.
   The division built the optical systems, or innards, of the
Hubble telescope, which is scheduled to be launched next year
aboard the space shuttle. The telescope will allow scientists to
look seven times deeper into space than earth-based telescopes.
   ``With land-based telescopes we can see a certain distance out
into space, but a lot of what we see is obscured by haze around the
earth,'' Bloch said. ``But when it's up 350 miles above the earth,
it will expand the volume by about 350 times from what we can see
on the ground.''
   Hughes is the nation's largest defense electronics company, with
75,000 employees and $7.4 billion in sales in 1988. The company
designs and produces electro-optical sensors, laser systems and
data processing systems for use in space and on land.
   ``The acquisition by Hughes will strengthen its position as a
leading supplier of electro-optical systems for scientific and
military applications,'' Malcolm R. Currie, Hughes' chairman and
chief executive officer, said in a statement.
   The sale is the second this year in Perkin-Elmer's effort to
unload three of its divisions. Late last month, the Norwalk-based
company announced it was selling its German aerospace unit in
Ueberlingen, West Germany, to the Diehl Group for an undisclosed
price.
   Perkin-Elmer is also negotiating to sell its semiconductor
equipment unit, and hopes to negotiate a sale by the end of the
year, Bloch said.
   Perkin-Elmer is retaining its analytical instruments division,
which produces scientific instruments used in laboratories; and its
material sciences division, which involves the heat- and
wear-resistant coatings used on jet engines.
   The company said in April, when the restructuring was announced,
that it wanted to focus on instruments and materials technology to
provide more consistent growth and profits.
 
</TEXT>
